WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.240
[Amit Varma]: How well do you know yourself? I don't mean this question in a sense of self-reflection

00:00:10.240 --> 00:00:15.320
[Amit Varma]: in some metaphysical or existential sense. I mean your material self. How well do you

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:19.760
[Amit Varma]: know your body? Do you know what the food you eat does to your body? Do you know what

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:23.820
[Amit Varma]: hormones are released when you don't get enough sleep? Or why staring into a screen

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:28.640
[Amit Varma]: all day alters your chemistry? Often, we lack the tools to measure these things. But even

00:00:28.640 --> 00:00:33.160
[Amit Varma]: if we had them all, I suspect we would be in denial. Unless we fell ill and had no choice

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:37.900
[Amit Varma]: but to solve that problem. Or unless we played sports and the incentives were aligned. By

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:42.320
[Amit Varma]: knowing our bodies, we can not just live healthier and longer, but we can be the best version

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:47.040
[Amit Varma]: of ourselves. And we can also discover, if we truly test ourselves, that our limits are

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:51.300
[Amit Varma]: not where we thought they were, and that we can go beyond what we thought possible. This

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:56.560
[Amit Varma]: is not just true of sports or physical activity. This is true of life. Sometimes other people

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:17.280
[Amit Varma]: place limits on us, and sometimes we do it to ourselves. Don't let that happen.

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:21.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Shruti Jagirdar, a volleyball player,

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:27.480
[Amit Varma]: a fitness freak, a trained nutritionist, a start-up founder, and a petroleum engineer by training.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:31.240
[Amit Varma]: Shruti is based in Berlin, and I met her on Twitter, where we interacted a bit, and then

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:35.200
[Amit Varma]: she said I really must do an episode on women's sports in India. That seemed like a great

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:39.720
[Amit Varma]: idea to me. I'd done an episode with Snehal Pradhan, but that had looked mainly at cricket

00:01:39.720 --> 00:01:44.480
[Amit Varma]: and covered a lot else apart from sport. It's a great episode. So I asked Shruti to suggest

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:49.480
[Amit Varma]: a guest, and she gave me a few names. But while talking about her experiences, I realised

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:53.600
[Amit Varma]: that hey, I had the perfect guest. And there was a lot else we could talk about, as she's

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:58.040
[Amit Varma]: a trained nutritionist who goes beyond the flawed conventional wisdom of the day. She

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:02.560
[Amit Varma]: runs a fitness start-up. She's trained for the MMA in Thailand's top mixed martial arts

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:06.800
[Amit Varma]: school. She's run through the desert in the UAE. And she's overall done such crazy things

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:11.600
[Amit Varma]: that I lost a bunch of galleries just listening to her stories. This conversation was recorded

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:16.480
[Amit Varma]: when she came to India and visited Mumbai, where we recorded at my home studio. I found

00:02:16.480 --> 00:02:24.520
[Amit Varma]: it both fun and enlightening. But before we get to it, let's take a commercial break.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:28.080
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:32.760
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:37.200
[Amit Varma]: Clear Writing. An online community has now sprung up of all my past students. We have

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:42.140
[Amit Varma]: workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community interaction.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:46.640
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through 4 webinars spread over 4 weekends, I share all I know about

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:51.020
[Amit Varma]: the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises, much interaction, a lovely

00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:56.600
[Amit Varma]: and lively community at the end of it. The course costs Rs 10,000 plus GST or about $150

00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:01.080
[Amit Varma]: and is a monthly thing. So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiancut.com

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:06.720
[Amit Varma]: slash clear writing. That's indiancut.com slash clear writing. Being a good writer doesn't

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:11.780
[Amit Varma]: require God-given talent, just the willingness to work hard and a clear idea of what you

00:03:11.780 --> 00:03:15.560
[Amit Varma]: need to do to refine your skills. I can help you.

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:20.240
[Amit Varma]: Shruti, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you for having me Amit.

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:25.200
[Amit Varma]: So I was just chatting on WhatsApp yesterday with a frequent guest on my show Shruti Rajgopalan

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:29.200
[Amit Varma]: and I told her that I'm recording with another Shruti tomorrow and her antennae immediately

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:34.240
[Amit Varma]: went up and she was like, who, who, who? And then I sort of send your Twitter bio. And

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:38.840
[Amit Varma]: this is an interesting recording for me because on the one hand, it's about a subject that

00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:44.560
[Amit Varma]: I haven't really thought about too much. Sport, especially the kind of sport that you have

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:50.600
[Amit Varma]: experienced in and also things like fitness and nutrition and all of that. So it almost

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:55.520
[Amit Varma]: feels like I'm traveling a little bit out of my comfort zone in terms of subjects I

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:59.780
[Amit Varma]: know a hell of a lot about. But at the same time, I'm really glad I'm doing so because

00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:05.180
[Amit Varma]: I'll hopefully get to learn a lot. But tell me where you are now and what you do now and

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:11.280
[Guest]: what are you doing in Bombay right now? Yeah, I guess apart from, from recording this

00:04:11.280 --> 00:04:19.720
[Guest]: podcast with you in Bombay, I am right now based in Berlin. Very late in my life, I took

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:26.240
[Guest]: the decision to do an MBA. And, and I realized I'm getting to an age where the MBA colleges

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:32.800
[Guest]: might not want me. So I better do it now. And so I'm based in Berlin and I'm studying

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:40.880
[Guest]: at the moment. But prior to that, I came from Pune, and I studied engineering. And yeah,

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:45.160
[Amit Varma]: you want me to get into? No, we'll get to that. We'll get to that in just a bit right

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:49.640
[Amit Varma]: from the very start. But you know, so the way we connected was you wrote to me on Twitter,

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:53.620
[Amit Varma]: and we had a conversation there and all of that. You know, over lunch, I was finding

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:58.640
[Amit Varma]: your sort of use of Twitter fascinating in the sense that you went on for a brief while

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:02.240
[Amit Varma]: when the Chennai floods happened, and you went off, then you came back, then you found

00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:05.920
[Amit Varma]: that there are good things and bad things about it. Let me check out what they're like.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:09.440
[Amit Varma]: And the good thing, of course, is that people like you and I can connect and Twitter is

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:14.360
[Amit Varma]: something that I really have mixed feelings about. Because on the one hand, it's a toxic

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:19.840
[Amit Varma]: space, the discourse is so polarized, the most unpleasant people in the world get a

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:24.200
[Amit Varma]: platform to, you know, attack you and get personal if that's what they want to do. And

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:28.240
[Amit Varma]: it can be really ugly. But at the same time, it's a beautiful space and two margins. And

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:33.080
[Amit Varma]: one of them is that you can curate your own feed, you have the best minds in the world

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:38.440
[Amit Varma]: thinking aloud every day, for your benefit, you know, where else do you get that? That's

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:42.780
[Amit Varma]: mind blowing. And the other is that people can just connect like you, you and I could

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:47.840
[Amit Varma]: have a conversation about what you do on Twitter, and you are in Berlin, and I'm here and now

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:52.240
[Amit Varma]: here you are, and we are sitting in kind of recording this. So what is your sense of Twitter

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:57.480
[Amit Varma]: given that you are a relatively new person that before you really got active, you thought

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:03.040
[Amit Varma]: about it. And for the rest of us jaded Twitterites, it might be, you know, the both the good and

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:04.240
[Amit Varma]: the bad might be normalized.

00:06:04.240 --> 00:06:11.920
[Guest]: Yeah, so yeah, you're absolutely right. I was on Twitter in 2015, just to see how I

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:17.080
[Guest]: could help the Chennai flood situation. And then I did a little bit of it for a month

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:24.520
[Guest]: or so and, and then just got off it. I also feel that a lot of people who are engineers

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:31.040
[Guest]: who are in the corporate, doing, you know, their desk jobs, most of them are not too

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:39.120
[Guest]: active on Twitter. I mean, if you talk about a large part of my circle as well, none of

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:45.040
[Guest]: them are on Twitter. That's another reason why I probably never got back on to Twitter

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:52.040
[Guest]: until 2021. Because I was active on Instagram. And I was active because I've traveled quite

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:55.960
[Guest]: a lot. And I know quite a lot of people that I don't see regularly. And they're all on

00:06:55.960 --> 00:07:01.840
[Guest]: my Instagram. And so I was active there. Although I got on to Instagram as well very late in

00:07:01.840 --> 00:07:08.840
[Guest]: 18 and 19. But then back, back in 2021, I came came on to Twitter to check what how

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:15.880
[Guest]: people were helping with the second wave during COVID. Then I did a bit bit of work with some

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:22.200
[Guest]: some groups that were calling different places and checking on the bed situation, the oxygen

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:29.580
[Guest]: cylinder situation. And when that was done, I stayed back because I sort of found a couple

00:07:29.580 --> 00:07:35.000
[Guest]: of handles that I hadn't seen on Instagram, or if I did follow them, they were not active.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:41.000
[Guest]: And I think you know, I'm a big fan of the Wait But Why blog by Tim Urban. And I saw

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:47.760
[Guest]: that he had he was very active on Twitter. Some some artists that I like are on active

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:52.680
[Guest]: on Twitter. And I was like, hey, these people are not very active on Instagram. So maybe

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:59.360
[Guest]: I should stick around and I should I should see if I get to learn a little bit here. And

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:06.160
[Guest]: it was a weird space to navigate. Because, you know, when you open an Instagram account,

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:11.160
[Guest]: you instantly have at least 50 or 70 of your friends just following you. And then you sort

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:16.720
[Guest]: of have conversations, somebody's liking your pictures, and you know, these are your friends.

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:22.840
[Guest]: But with Twitter, I sort of always felt that, hey, I know nobody here, like none of my really

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:29.120
[Guest]: close friends are on Twitter, or if they are, they're not very active, because of my background,

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:36.840
[Guest]: which is engineering and not a lot of engineers on it. So I stayed on it, I started following

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:44.680
[Guest]: people that I liked. And what actually made me really stay on Twitter was some women I

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:55.720
[Guest]: was following. And how articulate they were on Twitter. And how bold they were on Twitter.

00:08:55.720 --> 00:09:03.040
[Guest]: I really, really admired them. I admired the depth of their knowledge, or the depth of

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:10.680
[Guest]: their opinion, how strongly opinionated they were. And I mean, there was a variety of people,

00:09:10.680 --> 00:09:19.560
[Guest]: there were artists and actors, there were geoscientists and a variety of writers. And

00:09:19.560 --> 00:09:24.200
[Guest]: I was really impressed. And I was like, hey, you know, this is something I would like to

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:30.960
[Guest]: learn, if at all, and where are they getting it from? And also, I was not so exposed to

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:39.720
[Guest]: the wider world, in terms of me putting my opinions out there. Because I wasn't on Twitter.

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:45.960
[Guest]: And because I was trying and setting up my own startup at the time, I was literally sort

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:53.760
[Guest]: of 24 hours of my time sucked into making my startup work. So I had absolutely no time

00:09:53.760 --> 00:10:02.600
[Guest]: to get onto Twitter and find out what's happening with the world. And then at some point, I

00:10:02.600 --> 00:10:10.360
[Guest]: realized that, hey, if I am on Twitter, it's sort of prompting me to put my opinion on

00:10:10.360 --> 00:10:16.900
[Guest]: it. Because I do have opinions, I am opinionated. And now you're reading someone else's opinions,

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:21.720
[Guest]: and it's triggering you, or in a good way, your thoughts. And then you're like, hey,

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:27.280
[Guest]: now I want to share what I feel about this. And then after I was on it for about three

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:34.600
[Guest]: or four or five months, I was sort of looking back at a couple of my own tweets and feeling

00:10:34.600 --> 00:10:41.400
[Guest]: like, hey, I did not know I could express myself like this. It doesn't matter how many

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:49.800
[Guest]: people had liked those tweets or whatever. But I hadn't tested myself on really putting

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:57.080
[Guest]: my opinions through in writing, especially in a short form writing. And so to be very

00:10:57.080 --> 00:11:04.320
[Guest]: honest for me, Twitter is about how I am learning and discovering what I am, what topics really

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:13.960
[Guest]: trigger me positively or negatively, what topics prompt me to tweet, what sort of people

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:20.200
[Guest]: do I really enjoy following. Sometimes I even feel like there are a lot of people who are

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:27.080
[Guest]: popular on Twitter, who are very intelligent, who write well. But then sometimes I look

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:32.520
[Guest]: at their tweets and I'm like, hey, these tweets don't connect with me, the way they write.

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:41.480
[Guest]: They are very emotionless. And sometimes you go back and read these people's writing, like

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:47.960
[Guest]: they could be writing articles or op-eds or whatever. And you feel like, yeah, perhaps

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:54.280
[Guest]: that's their job. The article they are writing, maybe the writing is great, but it doesn't

00:11:54.280 --> 00:12:02.080
[Guest]: require them to emote in it, in a way. And then you see that in their tweets as well.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:07.280
[Guest]: And even that I have learned about myself, that there is a certain form of tweeting or

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:14.840
[Guest]: expressing that I do not like, I do not want to do that. So it's really self-exploration

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:23.040
[Guest]: for me. And sometimes I feel very, very frustrated with myself because I look at Twitter and

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:29.920
[Guest]: I'm like, hey, this is a space for, you know, journalists, artists, people who have very

00:12:29.920 --> 00:12:37.280
[Guest]: specific skill sets. And here I am, who's an engineer, who's a bit of a generalist.

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:44.960
[Guest]: And sometimes I feel like, hey, what do I really tweet about? Why should I be on Twitter?

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:49.160
[Guest]: And it frustrates me. I sometimes look at my tweets and I'm like, hey, I don't have

00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:55.360
[Guest]: political opinions. And, okay, I may have them sometimes, but you can't identify my

00:12:55.360 --> 00:13:05.960
[Guest]: account as a political commentary. And then I'm also not maybe, you know, so, so much

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:11.440
[Guest]: into tweeting about the startup world, because I'm also a little aware of the fact that I

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:17.520
[Guest]: don't want to give gyan on Twitter, because I have experienced something, make my Twitter

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:23.840
[Guest]: account into an advice forum. I don't want that to happen. I'm not a poet. I'm not a

00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:32.840
[Guest]: writer. I'm not a journalist. I'm not an artist who, by their popularity itself, get followers.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:39.000
[Guest]: So sometimes it really frustrates me. And I'm asking myself, why am I on Twitter? What

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:45.160
[Guest]: am I tweeting about? Why is anybody following me at all? You know, but I guess that's part

00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:46.160
[Guest]: of the excitement.

00:13:46.160 --> 00:13:52.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And it's also fascinating how there is this dichotomy, almost like a Jekyll and

00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:58.160
[Amit Varma]: Hyde side of Twitter, in the sense that something that you remarked upon earlier during lunch

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:04.600
[Amit Varma]: is how so many people, so many women, especially, are so open with sharing what they go through.

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:08.880
[Amit Varma]: And that can be valuable to other women as well, because it can tell them that they're

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:14.040
[Amit Varma]: not alone in terms of what people are feeling, it can maybe show them a way forward and all

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:19.920
[Amit Varma]: of that. And just even outside of the context of women tweeting and women reading, I just

00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:25.640
[Amit Varma]: feel that, you know, the most magical kind of interactions I have had in general through

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:30.600
[Amit Varma]: the internet, not just Twitter, are those personal ones, where you get to feel like

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:34.400
[Amit Varma]: you know someone personally, either because you're reading something from them, or maybe

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:37.980
[Amit Varma]: you've written something and that's touched them and they reach out to you. And those

00:14:37.980 --> 00:14:43.160
[Amit Varma]: personal connections are valuable. Like I certainly feel these with many of my writing

00:14:43.160 --> 00:14:48.040
[Amit Varma]: students, including people I haven't met in, you know, in real life, that you over time,

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:53.040
[Amit Varma]: you build a connection, you talk so much. And that can be one of the beautiful things

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:58.400
[Amit Varma]: of Twitter, that you have these personal connections between people sharing their lives and their

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:04.240
[Amit Varma]: thoughts in good faith. But it's also a space which is incredibly public, incredibly toxic,

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:08.640
[Amit Varma]: that you could say something in one context, which is making you vulnerable and revealing

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:12.640
[Amit Varma]: a side of you. And then the next day, you have people picking that up as a gotcha moment

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:15.080
[Guest]: and attacking you and misinterpreting that and all of that.

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:20.680
[Guest]: That happened with me as well. I was, I was very new on Twitter. I think I replied to

00:15:20.680 --> 00:15:29.200
[Guest]: somebody's tweet. And I made a comment about ambition. And I, of course, made it in a very

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:36.320
[Guest]: specific context. But as we will maybe get into it a little bit later, you know, the

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:43.080
[Guest]: moment you use the words ambition and competition, people take it personally. And they have become

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:51.040
[Guest]: topics where, you know, it's very easy for people to start saying things like, oh, but,

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:55.760
[Guest]: you know, why should everybody be competitive? Why should everybody have ambition and then

00:15:55.760 --> 00:16:02.080
[Guest]: just get into, I think, the circular discussion. And somebody, some people started trolling

00:16:02.080 --> 00:16:11.040
[Guest]: me on it. And it doesn't bother me. But yeah, it sometimes you, none of what you do or say

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:18.680
[Guest]: on Twitter is controversial, nor is your account that big. But then something gets picked up.

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:23.840
[Guest]: And people start trolling. And you're just looking at it. And you're like, you know,

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:31.880
[Guest]: this is so out of context, this whole trolling bit of it. But yeah, that's life on Twitter.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:36.080
[Amit Varma]: That's life on Twitter. Tell me about life before Twitter. So, you know, where were you

00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:45.960
[Guest]: born? What was your childhood like? So I was born in Pune. My parents both met in Pune.

00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest]: My father studied journalism in Pune. And he was a freelance journalist for the Indian

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:00.960
[Guest]: Express and Times of India. And he started in Bombay TV actually, and then moved to Pune.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:06.640
[Guest]: And he worked in the Film and Television Institute as a senior faculty for direction.

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:11.280
[Guest]: Which years? He retired in 2011, actually. So the 30 years

00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:16.680
[Amit Varma]: before that. So my dad was director of FTII between 86 and 91.

00:17:16.680 --> 00:17:21.640
[Amit Varma]: Then I'm sure he knows him. Yeah, yeah. I mean, yeah, small world. Yeah.

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:31.080
[Guest]: So and my mom was acting in films and very, very active in theatre, in Marathi theatre

00:17:31.080 --> 00:17:36.640
[Guest]: in Pune. And they met in the Film and Television Institute when mom was shooting for something.

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:44.640
[Guest]: Then I was born in Pune and studied there. I studied petroleum engineering. And as we

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:51.000
[Guest]: discussed before as well, at lunch, we have Ferguson College in common as well, which

00:17:51.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Guest]: is very close to I think all Punekar's hearts. And yeah, I pretty much grew up in a middle

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:08.520
[Guest]: class, upper middle class Maharashtrian setup. And very proud of my Pune background as all

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:16.800
[Guest]: Punekars are. Always had a very active life. And the best part about Pune is it's surrounded

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:23.440
[Guest]: by hills. Yeah, that's pretty much it. Used to go up the hills, do a lot of sport. Due

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:32.680
[Guest]: to my family's background in art, I guess, always enjoyed music, films, reading. So got

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:39.320
[Guest]: the best of both worlds. Enjoyed sport while growing up, enjoyed art a lot. Went to Abhinav

00:18:39.320 --> 00:18:48.040
[Guest]: Vidyalaya, which was at the time sort of a unique school for Pune. Very popular, but

00:18:48.040 --> 00:18:54.240
[Guest]: not a convent. So an English medium school, but which wasn't a convent. And it was started

00:18:54.240 --> 00:19:00.520
[Guest]: by a lady who came up with a concept of a school where she was like, I'm going to expose

00:19:00.520 --> 00:19:09.840
[Guest]: children to each and every form of exploring their skills. So we would have all kinds of

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:16.960
[Guest]: activities in school. The school would support it and including academics and sport. And

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:21.280
[Guest]: I guess that's how I really, really got into sport as well.

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:25.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. And you just made me nostalgic by mentioning the tekris we used to go up

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:34.760
[Guest]: and down in Ferguson. Anywhere and everywhere, you feel like you want to climb, you can find

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:35.920
[Amit Varma]: an entry point.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:39.560
[Amit Varma]: So this brings me to a tangential question. Like one, of course, there were the tekris

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:43.680
[Amit Varma]: of people who wanted to climb, could climb. And two, you happen to be in a school where

00:19:43.680 --> 00:19:48.620
[Amit Varma]: you were exposed to everything, including sport. But by and large, you know, the environment

00:19:48.620 --> 00:19:53.360
[Amit Varma]: for Indians is just not, doesn't seem to be conducive to sport. Like we just don't have

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:59.080
[Amit Varma]: a sporting culture. You go to Australia, Europe or whatever, people will engage in sport beyond

00:19:59.080 --> 00:20:02.680
[Amit Varma]: watching sport on TV and giving gyan on Twitter. They'll actually go out and play different

00:20:02.680 --> 00:20:06.960
[Amit Varma]: sports and they'll go out surfing on the weekend or whatever. They'll be doing things. But

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:10.400
[Amit Varma]: Indians have never had that kind of sporting culture. And there are, of course, various

00:20:10.400 --> 00:20:14.280
[Amit Varma]: theories for it, like, hey, the weather is too hot, which to me is not a great theory

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:18.200
[Amit Varma]: because you know, even Brazil produces such great footballers and so on and so forth.

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:23.140
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of similar weather there, isn't it? So what is your sense of why we don't

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:27.360
[Amit Varma]: have that kind of sporting culture? Is it a vicious circle that at some point you have

00:20:27.360 --> 00:20:31.440
[Amit Varma]: an equilibrium where perhaps people are too poor to have leisure time and there just isn't

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:37.760
[Amit Varma]: much sport? And then that sort of, you know, feeds on itself and the culture never forms?

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:42.400
[Amit Varma]: Or are there external factors to it also? Or what is sort of your sense of that?

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:48.980
[Guest]: Yeah, for sure. It's a mix of, Amit, it's a mix of things. I think first and foremost

00:20:48.980 --> 00:20:54.000
[Guest]: is the mindset. It doesn't have to be only sport. If you find children that are interested

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:02.560
[Guest]: in arts or show an early inclination towards a specific art form or sport, it's the school

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:09.400
[Guest]: and the parents, I think, in India that do not give it the importance that they give

00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:16.400
[Guest]: academics. Even now, I have rarely seen parents who say, hey, you know, my son has been doing

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:22.040
[Guest]: so well at sports or my daughter's been doing so well at sport. I'm a fine if they drop

00:21:22.040 --> 00:21:28.960
[Guest]: out after 12th. And I honestly feel if you want to develop as a sportsman, you cannot

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:36.800
[Guest]: say that I'm doing it parallelly. I'm that, hey, I'm going to be doing okay at my studies

00:21:36.800 --> 00:21:43.800
[Guest]: at the same time parallelly give time to sport. Then you cannot say I want to be world class.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:50.560
[Guest]: Because it needs the time it needs, not only for skill development, but also physical fitness

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:59.160
[Guest]: and growing up as an individual. So if you look at countries outside of India, the sportsmen

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:06.400
[Guest]: that do well in their teams itself, like take Coco Gough, for example, in tennis, who went

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:11.640
[Guest]: to the third or the fourth round in the French Open in her first showing a couple of years

00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:20.600
[Guest]: ago, was just 16 years old. So I think, first of all, countries outside of India have that

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:27.440
[Guest]: ability to spot talent, and then say that, hey, you know, this is what you need to do

00:22:27.440 --> 00:22:34.280
[Guest]: now. And we have a program for you. And that program then includes letting the person,

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:41.040
[Guest]: letting the sportsman grow as an individual as well. What that person can do in terms

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:49.160
[Guest]: of their sporting skill is a part of the process. They've shown that they're prodigal or whatever.

00:22:49.160 --> 00:22:55.520
[Guest]: And the skill development continues on the side, the strategy and planning what tournaments

00:22:55.520 --> 00:23:01.280
[Guest]: to enter, everything. But I think the countries are, apart from India, they're also looking

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:07.480
[Guest]: at how this sportsman can grow as a person. And if that can happen in time, then they

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:13.400
[Guest]: can compete at international levels with sportsmen much older than them. So for example, Coco

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:20.320
[Guest]: Gough played the first round with Venus Williams on her first showing, and she beat Venus.

00:23:20.320 --> 00:23:28.600
[Guest]: And you know, just to be able to play a match in a Grand Slam with a sportsman you've grown

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:37.680
[Guest]: up admiring, no matter how, you know, no matter how senior Venus is to her, Venus can really

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:45.520
[Guest]: beat a 16 year old purely based on how experienced she is. But to give her a tough competition

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:49.880
[Guest]: and then at the end of the match at the net, literally, you know, hug her and say that,

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:55.400
[Guest]: hey, I grew up looking at you, but not have that feeling when you're her opponent. To

00:23:55.400 --> 00:24:01.320
[Guest]: teach all those things that you need to first grow as a person. And if they can make a 16

00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:07.320
[Guest]: year old understand that, then she can become a competitor at an international level. Now

00:24:07.320 --> 00:24:14.400
[Guest]: when you come to India, what is the 16 year old doing on average in India? We are probably

00:24:14.400 --> 00:24:20.360
[Guest]: writing our 10th standard exams. Everybody in the society is asking you, oh, which college

00:24:20.360 --> 00:24:24.960
[Guest]: you're going to take, what stream you're going to take, and how much did you score, how much

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:32.920
[Guest]: did your friends score. And that is where I think the problem is that we do not allow

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:38.520
[Guest]: somebody to say, hey, academics is not my thing. You know, you should be able to say

00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:44.760
[Guest]: that openly and say that I am spending eight hours of my day not in school, but in a sports

00:24:44.760 --> 00:24:51.200
[Guest]: school. And we will talk when I have done something in what I am focusing on. So it's

00:24:51.200 --> 00:24:57.400
[Guest]: really the society. But also if you talk about infrastructure, we don't have the kind of

00:24:57.400 --> 00:25:03.600
[Guest]: infrastructure that can allow world class sportsmen to really shine. So I have in my

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:10.400
[Guest]: school as well, had the company of a lot of sportsmen who represented India internationally.

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:18.480
[Guest]: In TT, now I know somebody in rock climbing, I have played with women volleyballers who

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:26.160
[Guest]: played for the international team. And at some point, everybody says that, hey, okay,

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:32.080
[Guest]: fine, I played nationals, internationals, everything, but what does this give me in

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:39.120
[Guest]: terms of career? And I guess that's also another reason why parents don't really see a future

00:25:39.120 --> 00:25:47.100
[Guest]: and don't want to promote a skill beyond a certain point. So I think it's everything.

00:25:47.100 --> 00:25:52.640
[Guest]: It's infrastructure, it's mindset, it's actually not having enough opportunities compared to

00:25:52.640 --> 00:25:58.920
[Guest]: studying and doing something with your life. Yeah, I would say that that's the difference,

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:04.600
[Guest]: I guess, countries outside of Australia and the US especially. I was just speaking to

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:10.920
[Guest]: a friend of mine two months ago, she's Spanish, and she spent two years in high school in

00:26:10.920 --> 00:26:18.120
[Guest]: the US. And over a conversation, she told me that, you know, I was doing swimming when

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:26.360
[Guest]: I was in US and I was winning. And I had this final competition, maybe school level competition

00:26:26.360 --> 00:26:32.360
[Guest]: or something on the day of the final exam. The authorities at school just called me and

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:38.040
[Guest]: said, go do your swimming, win medals, do not even worry about your exam, you're going

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:46.880
[Guest]: to get 100%. Now, you know, I've been excused on a lot of my sports tournaments as well.

00:26:46.880 --> 00:26:53.320
[Guest]: But nobody tells you in these terms, you know, just go do your thing, we are going to take

00:26:53.320 --> 00:27:01.000
[Guest]: care of your studies and we are going to pass you or nobody, you don't hear it in these

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:06.680
[Guest]: very words. So that's the kind of support and this is this is just for somebody who

00:27:06.680 --> 00:27:11.520
[Guest]: was studying high school and who was probably just doing sport because at that time, she

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:18.680
[Guest]: was liking the sport. So imagine if they actually found somebody who had very high potential,

00:27:18.680 --> 00:27:21.000
[Guest]: what kind of support that person must be seeing?

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:26.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, lots to double click on like one of the just tangentially thinking aloud, you

00:27:26.880 --> 00:27:31.400
[Amit Varma]: know what you said about needing to grow someone as a person. I remember back in the day when

00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:36.920
[Amit Varma]: I was covering cricket, we used to discuss why so much young talent from Pakistan that

00:27:36.920 --> 00:27:41.900
[Amit Varma]: would come into cricket would just blaze their way to the top of the game and then completely

00:27:41.900 --> 00:27:46.280
[Amit Varma]: fall apart and disappear. And this was a pattern that kept happening in the 90s and the early

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:51.200
[Amit Varma]: 2000s and all of that and I don't follow the game closely enough to know how it is now.

00:27:51.200 --> 00:27:56.760
[Amit Varma]: And my feeling at the time was, and I think Harsha Bhogle agreed with me in a conversation

00:27:56.760 --> 00:28:00.940
[Amit Varma]: that I had with him, maybe we discussed it on a podcast, I don't remember. But the gist

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:06.100
[Amit Varma]: of it was that because Pakistan didn't have a middle class per se, it was either really

00:28:06.100 --> 00:28:10.680
[Amit Varma]: poor people or it was an elite at the top. And your cricketers, this enormous talent

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:17.440
[Amit Varma]: would emerge from, you know, the lower layer, they would not then have the sort of the social

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:21.760
[Amit Varma]: and cultural tools to be able to deal with the sudden success and the sudden fame and

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:25.520
[Amit Varma]: the sudden money and everything that attends those things and they would not be able to

00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:30.240
[Amit Varma]: cope. Whereas, if you look at all the great Indian cricketers of that time, they were

00:28:30.240 --> 00:28:34.240
[Amit Varma]: and this was a point Harsha made, that they embodied middle class values, in a sense.

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:40.320
[Amit Varma]: So your Tendulkar, your Dravid, your Laxman, even Ganguly, sort of embodied those middle

00:28:40.320 --> 00:28:45.200
[Amit Varma]: class values and therefore, they were less likely to just flame away and fall apart and

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:51.760
[Amit Varma]: all of that. And later, I think what happened post IPL and what you see in the current day

00:28:51.760 --> 00:28:58.840
[Amit Varma]: is that they are so exposed to sort of top quality cricket at the IPL level, that by

00:28:58.840 --> 00:29:03.040
[Amit Varma]: the time somebody actually plays for India, they've played many of the best players in

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:06.840
[Amit Varma]: the world already in packed stadiums full of screaming people. So there's no pressure

00:29:06.840 --> 00:29:11.640
[Amit Varma]: to them, which is why, you know, we could do what we did in Australia last year, where,

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:16.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, our third string 11, as it were, you know, won the series for us. Now, a couple

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:20.480
[Amit Varma]: of points that, you know, sort of emerged from what you were saying. And when I was

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:24.880
[Amit Varma]: speaking about sporting culture, I was talking about a broader sporting culture, not just

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:29.200
[Amit Varma]: in terms of parents supporting the kids when, if they want to do sports, but just the parents

00:29:29.200 --> 00:29:32.000
[Amit Varma]: going out and playing themselves on a Sunday afternoon when they're free.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:36.280
[Guest]: Oh yeah, absolutely, Amit. I mean, not even parents. This happened with me a few years

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:44.280
[Guest]: ago. I really enjoy skating as a pastime. It's something, it's probably the first sport

00:29:44.280 --> 00:29:52.520
[Guest]: that I sort of started learning, but not taught by anybody, just watching people skate on

00:29:52.520 --> 00:29:58.320
[Guest]: the streets and then get my skates and then skate on top of the take D in Pune, by the

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:04.640
[Guest]: way. So it's something I've always enjoyed doing as a pastime. And I was fortunate enough

00:30:04.640 --> 00:30:12.080
[Guest]: to live in Dubai for a couple of years. And at that time, I bought myself a pair of skates.

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:19.160
[Guest]: This was in 2015. And then I used to go skating on the beach with my friends and stuff. And

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:24.880
[Guest]: then I got my skates back to India when I came back and I still wanted to skate. And

00:30:24.880 --> 00:30:30.240
[Guest]: I'm not a very early morning person, which is why I'm also not a very huge fan of running

00:30:30.240 --> 00:30:36.080
[Guest]: because everybody starts at four and five in the morning. But I did not want to do that

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:40.680
[Guest]: with skating. If I wanted to find good roads and go skating, I didn't want to wake up at

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:47.680
[Guest]: five or 5.30 in the morning and go skating. So I went to a club in Pune and they have

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:54.640
[Guest]: a lovely skating school and great facilities. And I was like, Hey, I want to just, I have

00:30:54.640 --> 00:31:00.440
[Guest]: skates. I'm not a very professional skater, but I would like to use the facilities. And

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:08.840
[Guest]: they said, No, but we do not have these free hours where you can just come and skate. You

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:14.480
[Guest]: would have to join a class. And I said, Okay, why not? I've never really learned skating,

00:31:14.480 --> 00:31:22.160
[Guest]: so I don't mind it. And then I said, But what, what batch are you going to take me in? And

00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:26.760
[Guest]: then they were like, No, but you're already you're you're an adult. So we will take you

00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:34.160
[Guest]: in with our senior batches. And I was like, Okay. And then I went on that day. And the

00:31:34.160 --> 00:31:41.800
[Guest]: senior batches were full of 12 year olds and 11 year olds. And I was like, Hey, listen,

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:46.880
[Guest]: this is not going to work out. And so I basically couldn't skate. I couldn't find a place in

00:31:46.880 --> 00:31:54.220
[Guest]: Pune where adults went skating. Or I would say the only place where you see adults really

00:31:54.220 --> 00:32:01.240
[Guest]: pushing themselves and getting into it is badminton courts in India. So if they are

00:32:01.240 --> 00:32:07.600
[Guest]: not experiencing the sport and the benefit of it and the goodness of it, and if they

00:32:07.600 --> 00:32:15.600
[Guest]: are not part of the sporting conversations, how do you expect them to as parents do it

00:32:15.600 --> 00:32:22.280
[Guest]: for their children? So absolutely, I don't, it's, you're right, when you when we talk

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:27.440
[Guest]: about the sporting culture, it's the adults in India who themselves drop out and do not

00:32:27.440 --> 00:32:33.040
[Guest]: consider themselves competitive anymore, which is also a problem.

00:32:33.040 --> 00:32:38.400
[Amit Varma]: And also, I think that, you know, the the field of possibilities for someone discovering

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:42.880
[Amit Varma]: that they're good in sport as a kid is limited when that sporting culture isn't there, because

00:32:42.880 --> 00:32:46.800
[Amit Varma]: it's not a natural thing that Sunday court time and the whole family goes out and plays

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:51.920
[Amit Varma]: or you know, whenever the kid has free time, the kid goes out and play. I'm sure in most

00:32:51.920 --> 00:32:55.880
[Amit Varma]: of India, many more kids are sitting in with their phones or their laptops or doing other

00:32:55.880 --> 00:32:59.640
[Amit Varma]: stuff rather than actually playing a sport. And the proportion for that would be greater

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:03.760
[Amit Varma]: than elsewhere. So we're probably losing a lot of quality sports people because of that

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:06.400
[Amit Varma]: because they never discovered that they love the sport or want to play it because they

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:11.080
[Amit Varma]: never really get into it in the first place. And equally apart from the culture itself,

00:33:11.080 --> 00:33:15.640
[Amit Varma]: I guess incentives matter a great deal. Like the reason we have this cricket renaissance

00:33:15.640 --> 00:33:21.040
[Amit Varma]: with so much strength and so much depth is really because the IPL changed the incentives

00:33:21.040 --> 00:33:24.920
[Amit Varma]: and now you don't just have, so a kid in Delhi isn't just thinking that shit, I have to

00:33:24.920 --> 00:33:28.800
[Amit Varma]: get into the Delhi team, there's one buyer for my services and there's so much corruption

00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:33.520
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. But now there are so many teams competing for you. And I guess, you

00:33:33.520 --> 00:33:36.840
[Amit Varma]: know, Joy Bhattacharya's Volleyball League, which we were speaking about would hopefully

00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:44.320
[Amit Varma]: do the similar kind of thing in volleyball. So I guess those incentives also sort of matter.

00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:49.780
[Amit Varma]: But we'll come to that. Let's talk about your journey in sport. Like how did you start getting

00:33:49.780 --> 00:33:53.840
[Amit Varma]: into sport? Because just given who your parents were and all of that, one would imagine you'd

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:58.440
[Amit Varma]: be into arts and you'd be acting in plays and you'd be, you know, learning Bharatnatyam

00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:08.000
[Guest]: and singing things. I did learn Bharatnatyam. No, I think I was always exposed to the arts

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:15.200
[Guest]: and I always enjoyed them. And I was always taking part in elocution and singing competitions

00:34:15.200 --> 00:34:23.760
[Guest]: in school. And so I was pretty much into arts. But my inclination was always towards sport.

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:29.920
[Guest]: And that's another thing that I always feel that there is, you know, there's no element

00:34:29.920 --> 00:34:35.080
[Guest]: of discovering what somebody's interest. You would be able to see it and you would see

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:40.120
[Guest]: it at the very nascent phases of somebody's growing up years. So you don't really have

00:34:40.120 --> 00:34:45.520
[Guest]: to, you know, find out. And now I sometimes feel there's all kinds of tests to find out

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:52.920
[Guest]: what our interests are, what our skills are, what our thought processes are like. But most

00:34:52.920 --> 00:35:00.680
[Guest]: often than not, your core beliefs, your core skills, your core abilities are shown at some

00:35:00.680 --> 00:35:07.640
[Guest]: point. And for me, it was the same. So in school, like I was just, I mean, I'll take

00:35:07.640 --> 00:35:15.200
[Guest]: you back to the skating story. So when I was about seven, eight or nine years, my friends

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:21.440
[Guest]: and I from my building, we used to carry our skates up the Tekdi, which is a hill in Pune.

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:28.360
[Guest]: And it was about just 10 minutes from where we lived. And I don't remember how often we

00:35:28.360 --> 00:35:33.800
[Guest]: used to go, but very often. And we used to carry them up the hill, which took us about

00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:43.880
[Guest]: 15 minutes to climb. Because the ARAI, which is a company that was nestled in the hills,

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:50.640
[Guest]: used to test cars before they were launched commercially. And because they tested those

00:35:50.640 --> 00:35:59.120
[Guest]: cars, the road up the hill that led to ARAI building was always very well maintained.

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:04.820
[Guest]: And only the cars that were being tested or the employees of ARAI would use that road.

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:11.240
[Guest]: And so all kinds of skating lessons used to happen early in the morning on this road.

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:19.040
[Guest]: And my friends and I, we used to go up early and we used to get our skates on and we used

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:25.320
[Guest]: to compete with the guys who were getting trained by a coach. So they would start and

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:30.040
[Guest]: they would skate and we would be parallelly skating with them and we would try and compete

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:35.600
[Guest]: and try and beat them. And their coach was not really teaching us, but we were competing

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:41.320
[Guest]: with them and we got better at it at some point. So I guess that's the first time I

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:48.160
[Guest]: sort of did any sort of sport. And I have to thank my parents to somehow have agreed

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:59.440
[Guest]: to get me a pair of skates. But even in school, right from your spoon and lemon races to your

00:36:59.440 --> 00:37:07.760
[Guest]: gunny bag races or whatever, I was always very competitive in them from the age of six

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:16.360
[Guest]: and seven in my first standard. I have sort of flashes of some of those races as well.

00:37:16.360 --> 00:37:26.480
[Guest]: Even now, now I'm way past my 30s, but the times that you really overcame and you won,

00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:32.020
[Guest]: those flashes are still very clear in my mind, even if they were like these little races.

00:37:32.020 --> 00:37:40.160
[Guest]: And then of course, as you grow up, as you come to your fourth standard or so, you start

00:37:40.160 --> 00:37:45.760
[Guest]: participating in inter-school dodgeball and other things. And by then the school has seen

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:50.520
[Guest]: that, okay, there are a few girls that are very active in sports, so they would take

00:37:50.520 --> 00:37:57.480
[Guest]: you into those dodgeball teams. And then in my case, in the fifth standard, my school

00:37:57.480 --> 00:38:05.640
[Guest]: decided to create a girls volleyball team. And we did not have a volleyball coach. So

00:38:05.640 --> 00:38:13.160
[Guest]: one of our sports coaches in school was sent on some training program where he had to learn

00:38:13.160 --> 00:38:18.320
[Guest]: and then come back and form a volleyball team. At that time, I was among the taller girls

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:24.820
[Guest]: in class and I had been playing in the inter-school matches in the previous years and all of that.

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:31.000
[Guest]: So he gathered a team and then he started training us. It wasn't really like, oh, I

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:37.800
[Guest]: love volleyball, so I'm going to join this sport. It wasn't like that. And we just started

00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:47.440
[Guest]: practicing volleyball in school with Sanjay sir, who remains my biggest influence or guru

00:38:47.440 --> 00:38:56.720
[Guest]: in terms of sport. Then the team that he collected, we became very good friends. And we just enjoyed

00:38:56.720 --> 00:39:04.840
[Guest]: going to the school in the evening and practicing together and just being friends as such. And

00:39:04.840 --> 00:39:09.000
[Guest]: then you know, then you participate in the city tournaments. Then you learn, oh, after

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:14.880
[Guest]: the city tournaments, there's further levels up all the way up until nationals. And then

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:19.960
[Guest]: if you are inherently competitive people and you are also part of a sports team, you obviously

00:39:19.960 --> 00:39:28.200
[Guest]: slowly and steadily start aiming for higher and better. And yeah, so that just sort of

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:35.240
[Guest]: continued with me and we started enjoying the game, having a lot of success. So my school

00:39:35.240 --> 00:39:41.560
[Guest]: volleyball team was the number one team in Pune that always won the city tournaments

00:39:41.560 --> 00:39:46.600
[Guest]: and then reached all the way up to the state level. And then there is another school in

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:52.240
[Guest]: Pune called Symbiosis. The boys team of that school was always the winners at the city

00:39:52.240 --> 00:39:59.960
[Guest]: level. So we wanted to maintain legacy at some point. So that's how it continued.

00:39:59.960 --> 00:40:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And when you would skate with these boys, would you beat them?

00:40:02.880 --> 00:40:08.880
[Guest]: I don't remember now. I think I would. But you know, it's really funny. I honestly believe

00:40:08.880 --> 00:40:14.080
[Guest]: that nothing you've ever done in your life goes waste. I do not remember if I used to

00:40:14.080 --> 00:40:23.840
[Guest]: beat them. I remember I was very good. But many years later, when I was 22 or 23, like

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:29.560
[Guest]: I said, I studied petroleum engineering and I joined Shell afterwards. And we had an onboarding

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:35.780
[Guest]: program in Oman. The onboarding program, of course, had recruits like, you know, new recruits

00:40:35.780 --> 00:40:41.060
[Guest]: from everywhere in the world. And there was this team building activity and it was an

00:40:41.060 --> 00:40:50.080
[Guest]: amazing race. So we had to go from Muscat, take a car with our teammates and try and

00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:55.020
[Guest]: do quite a few activities on our way to another town where we had to finally assemble and

00:40:55.020 --> 00:41:01.320
[Guest]: make a scrapbook. And one of the challenge activities was that the entire team should

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:08.960
[Guest]: be on an ice skating ring and nobody falls. And all seven of us should be there without

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:15.640
[Guest]: holding anybody's hands. And I had never done ice skating before that. And the Omanis

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:19.640
[Guest]: with me, for them, they had seen the ice skating ring before. It's quite a popular sport and

00:41:19.640 --> 00:41:25.000
[Guest]: they had done it. And when I finally wore the ice skates, and I had never even worn,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:30.960
[Guest]: I used to do roller skating. I hadn't even worn the inline skates before. And it took

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:34.880
[Guest]: me just 15 minutes to get the hang of it. And I was like, yeah, I'm ready. Let's let's

00:41:34.880 --> 00:41:40.800
[Guest]: take this picture. And then now I'm a huge fan of ice skating. So after Tehkadi, I had

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:48.280
[Guest]: never touched skates until that day in Oman. But I could get get on to the ice skating

00:41:48.280 --> 00:41:56.560
[Guest]: ring only because I knew originally how skating worked. So that's that's honestly, I really

00:41:56.560 --> 00:42:04.140
[Guest]: believe that no matter what happens, give whatever opportunity you have to try something

00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:09.120
[Guest]: new a chance, because you don't know where you're going to need it.

00:42:09.120 --> 00:42:13.160
[Amit Varma]: This is such a fabulous story. You know, when you started talking about Oman and you're

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:17.280
[Amit Varma]: 22, and you're in this new company, I thought there's going to be some angle about how this

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:21.480
[Amit Varma]: another boy from Pune who remembers you because you used to beat him in skating down the hill

00:42:21.480 --> 00:42:25.160
[Amit Varma]: and you know, very filmy kind of.

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:31.120
[Guest]: Yeah, no, I hope I don't I don't have any such enemies that I've created when I was

00:42:31.120 --> 00:42:34.560
[Guest]: seven and eight years old. Come back to haunt me now.

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:39.600
[Amit Varma]: Not even enemies, someone who could have fallen for you, maybe, you know, who knows, who knows

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:46.560
[Amit Varma]: nice arc for a Bollywood-y sort of story right there. So what was the experience like of

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:50.480
[Amit Varma]: sort of going and playing at the interschool level? Because, you know, earlier, you spoke

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:55.600
[Amit Varma]: about how your friend in the US was, you know, sporting event coincided with exam and these

00:42:55.600 --> 00:43:00.200
[Amit Varma]: people, you know, the people said go and play. And I remember when I was in the 11th or 12th

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:06.400
[Amit Varma]: in Ferguson, I forget which, I qualified for the Maharashtra team for the interschool chess

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:15.200
[Amit Varma]: championships. And I came third in Maharashtra and Sholapur. And then ultimately, the event,

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:20.280
[Amit Varma]: the interschool event coincided with the ICSE exams or something, or HSC exams or whatever

00:43:20.280 --> 00:43:23.720
[Amit Varma]: it was. So I had to miss it. And I presume most of the people who qualified had to miss

00:43:23.720 --> 00:43:28.360
[Amit Varma]: it. And it was just so bizarre. But what I remember about the qualification at Sholapur

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:34.240
[Amit Varma]: was it was an interschool event. So it wasn't only chess, right? So but my chess team from

00:43:34.240 --> 00:43:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Pune was about four of us. And we land up there and all the other sports are there,

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:45.320
[Amit Varma]: there's, you know, all your wrestling and running and all of those. And some 150 of

00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:50.240
[Amit Varma]: us were then asked to sleep in this large hall, which would, we've all been there. Yeah.

00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:54.440
[Amit Varma]: So we had to somehow lie down on the floor, like side by side and cheek to jowl and all

00:43:54.440 --> 00:43:58.400
[Amit Varma]: of that. And part of the floor was wet and all of that. And in the morning, there was

00:43:58.400 --> 00:44:04.160
[Amit Varma]: just these two outdoor toilets, which you had to compete for. And we were chess players.

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:08.560
[Amit Varma]: There are wrestlers and judokas and all of that. So what chance do we do we have to do

00:44:08.560 --> 00:44:13.840
[Amit Varma]: our ablutions in peace? And that was kind of what it was. And I thought, my God, what

00:44:13.840 --> 00:44:19.800
[Amit Varma]: a massive disincentive, you know, and this was a late 80s, right? So the thing is, no

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:25.260
[Amit Varma]: wonder I didn't have like, I kind of retired from chess at 19. Because I figured that look

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:30.240
[Amit Varma]: in India, the way it is, you know, if I wasn't Vishwanathan Anand, I was nobody. And of course,

00:44:30.240 --> 00:44:34.680
[Amit Varma]: I wasn't that good. Though one of the kids I used to play with went on to become a grandmaster

00:44:34.680 --> 00:44:40.040
[Amit Varma]: and a national champion and all of that. But it just wasn't rational for me to stay on

00:44:40.040 --> 00:44:44.800
[Amit Varma]: in that particular sport, whether or not one calls it a sport. And for other people from

00:44:44.800 --> 00:44:49.180
[Amit Varma]: people from, say, a different economic strata, there might still have been the incentive

00:44:49.180 --> 00:44:53.840
[Amit Varma]: that you'll get a job with services or railways or whatever. But otherwise, if for someone

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:59.280
[Amit Varma]: like me, it just didn't make sense. You know, there's a famous story of Sunil Gavaskar.

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:02.880
[Amit Varma]: This was, of course, in the late 60s, when he used to play for Bombay University. And

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:06.560
[Amit Varma]: there was a guy called, I think, Ramesh Nagdev, who used to open with him, who was a swashbuckling

00:45:06.560 --> 00:45:11.680
[Amit Varma]: stroke player. And everybody was as impressed with him as by Gavaskar. But Nagdev went abroad

00:45:11.680 --> 00:45:16.760
[Amit Varma]: to do degree and job and all of that and completely understandable. And I would imagine things

00:45:16.760 --> 00:45:20.700
[Amit Varma]: are different now. But what were they like in your time? And especially, you're a group

00:45:20.700 --> 00:45:24.920
[Amit Varma]: of girls, right? So when you travel, what is it like? How do you, you know, how do the

00:45:24.920 --> 00:45:30.400
[Amit Varma]: authorities treat you? You know, are you always sort of fighting against the odds to do what

00:45:30.400 --> 00:45:31.400
[Amit Varma]: you do?

00:45:31.400 --> 00:45:40.280
[Guest]: Yeah, so Amit, first and foremost, I know a lot of these sports biopics touch upon the

00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:47.760
[Guest]: gender biases and patriarchy in sport and all of that. But to be honest, I haven't seen

00:45:47.760 --> 00:45:55.520
[Guest]: a lot of that for the main reason being that volleyball itself needed being propped up

00:45:55.520 --> 00:46:01.580
[Guest]: in the first place. Then comes any gender bias and whether the boys teams were treated

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:07.120
[Guest]: better than women or anything like that. So I cannot really comment on that. I haven't

00:46:07.120 --> 00:46:16.680
[Guest]: seen that in volleyball. But of course, as a women's team, we were careful. Yeah, surely

00:46:16.680 --> 00:46:21.760
[Guest]: like our coach would tell us, oh, you have to wear your track suit all the time and just

00:46:21.760 --> 00:46:28.560
[Guest]: be on in your team t-shirt and shorts on the court just before the match and for the warm

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:34.560
[Guest]: up. But that's fine. They were just being careful. In my many years of playing volleyball

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:41.920
[Guest]: and the great thing about having become a volleyball player was that most of the volleyball

00:46:41.920 --> 00:46:48.960
[Guest]: matches used to happen in very small towns in Maharashtra because I think the idea was

00:46:48.960 --> 00:46:55.040
[Guest]: to uplift those towns. So if you really ask me if I have traveled to some of the best

00:46:55.040 --> 00:47:03.000
[Guest]: parts of Maharashtra and tourist destinations, I haven't been. But if you ask me where else

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:10.280
[Guest]: I've been in Maharashtra, almost all small towns. I've been to places like Barshi, Solapur,

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:17.440
[Guest]: Beed, Varna Nagar, Bilawdi. Who talks about these towns? Even when we were playing chess,

00:47:17.440 --> 00:47:26.400
[Guest]: we went to Solapur, Sangli, Kolhapur, Aurangabad, Satara, Banhala, Kolhapur, Aurangabad, Ahmednagar,

00:47:26.400 --> 00:47:33.360
[Guest]: Daund, which is closer from here. And, you know, I have literally traveled everywhere

00:47:33.360 --> 00:47:41.360
[Guest]: in Maharashtra. I have seen every dirty toilet there is to see, basically. And I mean, I've

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:47.840
[Guest]: tried water from all of these towns. And now when I travel as well, I think what I've picked

00:47:47.840 --> 00:47:53.480
[Guest]: up from there is I don't notice the change in taste of the water. I'm not always complaining.

00:47:53.480 --> 00:47:59.000
[Guest]: Even now when I go and travel somewhere, I'm not looking for bistleries. I think your body

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:08.280
[Guest]: just adjusts at some point. And I think that really made us very, very independent as women.

00:48:08.280 --> 00:48:13.600
[Guest]: Like you said, all these sports facilities that would be offered to sports teams at the

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:21.400
[Guest]: time would basically be one of the rooms from a government school with Shahbad tiles and

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:28.440
[Guest]: those iron nets on the top. And basically, it's really funny because you would start

00:48:28.440 --> 00:48:34.400
[Guest]: by cleaning that room. And the magical thing about Shahbad tiles is no matter how much

00:48:34.400 --> 00:48:41.600
[Guest]: you try to clean them, you cannot succeed. So you end up sleeping on whatever you're

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:47.760
[Guest]: carrying, whatever bedding you're carrying. And I think that kind of brings you together

00:48:47.760 --> 00:48:52.520
[Guest]: in some ways, because now I'm still close with all my original volleyball team from

00:48:52.520 --> 00:48:57.520
[Guest]: school and we really laugh about these things. And that's why, you know, movies like Chakde

00:48:57.520 --> 00:49:03.440
[Guest]: really sort of strike a chord with us because they've kind of gotten closer to the living

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:08.600
[Guest]: conditions and all those things. It's quite nostalgic in that sense for us. But in terms

00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:14.000
[Guest]: of the levels of the game that you mentioned earlier on, so how it used to happen with

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:19.280
[Guest]: volleyball is there used to be a city level tournament. So let's say I'm from Pune, all

00:49:19.280 --> 00:49:28.480
[Guest]: the girls teams from Pune play. Then the team that wins plays the district level tournament.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:33.160
[Guest]: And then all the teams from the districts play and then you play the divisions and you

00:49:33.160 --> 00:49:39.960
[Guest]: play as a team. Then the team that wins at the divisions plays the state level tournament.

00:49:39.960 --> 00:49:46.600
[Guest]: And then that's pretty much as high as you can go as a team. And then after that, a few

00:49:46.600 --> 00:49:52.800
[Guest]: of the players that are selected during the state level tournaments enter the national

00:49:52.800 --> 00:50:00.280
[Guest]: level selection trials. And from there, the national level team is then selected. Yeah,

00:50:00.280 --> 00:50:06.680
[Guest]: it's pretty much that whole journey by the time you actually end up playing the nationals.

00:50:06.680 --> 00:50:12.920
[Guest]: And you were saying that a lot of people drop out because they didn't see opportunities

00:50:12.920 --> 00:50:18.600
[Guest]: after maybe attaining, you know, getting to this level, which is true, which is what it

00:50:18.600 --> 00:50:24.120
[Guest]: was during my time as well. And regardless of how well I did or not, at some point I

00:50:24.120 --> 00:50:33.240
[Guest]: would have dropped out. But for me, I attribute all of my life success so far to a specific

00:50:33.240 --> 00:50:41.080
[Guest]: event that happened during my 10th exams. And it was to do with volleyball. And what

00:50:41.080 --> 00:50:48.120
[Guest]: had happened is that you were just mentioning that your CBSE exam, HSC I think since I was

00:50:48.120 --> 00:50:53.920
[Guest]: in Ferguson. Yeah, yeah, yeah. So your 12th exam was was closed. And so a lot of people

00:50:53.920 --> 00:51:00.760
[Guest]: drop out. I had that situation when I was in the 10th standard. So my 10th final exam

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:07.800
[Guest]: was at the end of March or so. And at the end of January, we received a invite for the

00:51:07.800 --> 00:51:13.160
[Guest]: nationals trials. And while I had started playing when I was in the sixth standard,

00:51:13.160 --> 00:51:17.440
[Guest]: I had played a lot of state level tournaments, but then every sportsman wants to play that

00:51:17.440 --> 00:51:22.440
[Guest]: national level. And so you are literally waiting and you have really seen a lot of your colleagues

00:51:22.440 --> 00:51:27.360
[Guest]: and everybody, you know, get selected over the years and you're, you're like, hey, this

00:51:27.360 --> 00:51:32.280
[Guest]: is, you know, this is something I really want to do. A lot of people at that time would

00:51:32.280 --> 00:51:36.680
[Guest]: be like, hey, I'm not going to go anymore, because my 10th exam is coming, coming is

00:51:36.680 --> 00:51:42.880
[Guest]: really close. And I decided to go and I have to thank my parents that they have never,

00:51:42.880 --> 00:51:50.600
[Guest]: never ever pushed me to be academically very ahead of the game or so. I decided to go it

00:51:50.600 --> 00:51:59.760
[Guest]: was the trials were in Solapur and I got selected. And then there was a seven day camp before

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:08.160
[Guest]: the team left for Hyderabad. And I used to play a position called as a tosser. So if

00:52:08.160 --> 00:52:14.600
[Guest]: the volleyball team has 12 players, six reserve and six mains, there are only two tossers.

00:52:14.600 --> 00:52:18.280
[Guest]: So they are like the game makers, the ones who stand near the net, and they are the ones

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:23.040
[Guest]: who toss the ball to the smashers. So we are the ones who are deciding how the game is

00:52:23.040 --> 00:52:28.760
[Guest]: played because we decide the strategy on which smasher will play, whether behind us, ahead

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:33.600
[Guest]: of us, far back of the court. So in that sense, we are the game makers, but there are only

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:42.000
[Guest]: two positions in the team. And so I was selected and after the camp, there was a girl who was,

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:49.080
[Guest]: I think was more experienced than me who came from Nagpur. And her father, I think paid

00:52:49.080 --> 00:52:57.020
[Guest]: the coach at the time, some 5 or 10,000 rupees or so and to get me out of the team and let

00:52:57.020 --> 00:53:03.920
[Guest]: her play. And that's what happened. And because the national team was announced, this was

00:53:03.920 --> 00:53:11.320
[Guest]: not during the trials. It was shocking. And this was corruption. And I don't think there's

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:18.960
[Guest]: any sportsman in India who's not seen corruption. And I was absolutely shocked. If there was

00:53:18.960 --> 00:53:24.400
[Guest]: any time I have hoped that my parents had any connections to reverse this decision,

00:53:24.400 --> 00:53:34.640
[Guest]: it was that time. And of course, we didn't. So we couldn't do anything about it. And my

00:53:34.640 --> 00:53:39.200
[Guest]: aunt stays in Sulapur. So she came to get me. And then, of course, there was a lot of

00:53:39.200 --> 00:53:46.680
[Guest]: crying and how can this happen to me and all of that. But then I came back to Pune. And

00:53:46.680 --> 00:53:54.440
[Guest]: I remember that Sulapur to Pune was about 4 or 5 hours of drive. And the first 2-3 hours

00:53:54.440 --> 00:54:02.200
[Guest]: was literally like, I left my exams and I jeopardized my exams and spent so long here.

00:54:02.200 --> 00:54:05.960
[Guest]: And if it was just the trials, it was 2-3 days. But now I've finished the camp. How

00:54:05.960 --> 00:54:14.920
[Guest]: could they do this to me? 10 days of my study time is just gone. And I mean, what happened

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:20.760
[Guest]: with me was wrong. But it wasn't like by that time, I was doing something amazing in terms

00:54:20.760 --> 00:54:26.000
[Guest]: of my studies in school. I wasn't some topper or top 10 or whatever. I was probably scoring

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:34.120
[Guest]: like mid-70s and not too bothered about it. But in that 5-hour journey, I don't know what

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:39.880
[Guest]: happened to me. I was like, I cannot fail. If this is what's going to happen to me, I'm

00:54:39.880 --> 00:54:47.480
[Guest]: going to kill it in my exams. It was just like a switch in my mind. I had no prior data

00:54:47.480 --> 00:54:51.800
[Guest]: to prove that I could kill it in my exams basically. But it was just the competitive

00:54:51.800 --> 00:55:00.920
[Guest]: spirit that there has to be a win at the end of this. So I came back home and I sort of

00:55:00.920 --> 00:55:06.240
[Guest]: made a study plan. I had about a month left before my exams. My dream was to get into

00:55:06.240 --> 00:55:11.280
[Guest]: Ferguson College because everybody's is in Pune and it's the best college. And I knew

00:55:11.280 --> 00:55:17.280
[Guest]: I wanted science and it's the best college for science. Closes at a high percentage.

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:22.800
[Guest]: And I was like, okay, this is my goal. I wrote it on a piece of paper. I stuck it on the

00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:29.880
[Guest]: wall. I made a schedule, etc. I think that one month I must have studied 18 hours every

00:55:29.880 --> 00:55:41.120
[Guest]: day. I don't think I have focused as much in my entire life. And I scored some 84-85%.

00:55:41.120 --> 00:55:47.680
[Guest]: I was well within Ferguson's range and I was admitted to Ferguson. And I was the only one

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:52.960
[Guest]: amongst my friends circle at the time who actually got into Ferguson because I had scored

00:55:52.960 --> 00:56:02.640
[Guest]: well enough. And I had not seen such academic success or my own potential in academics so

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:14.200
[Guest]: far at that level. I surprised myself. So from that day onwards, I have never thought

00:56:14.200 --> 00:56:21.600
[Guest]: that any failure that came in my life was a personal failure that I couldn't better.

00:56:21.600 --> 00:56:26.480
[Guest]: I guess that event became a turning point in my life. It's unfortunate when corruption

00:56:26.480 --> 00:56:34.640
[Guest]: happens in sport and I'm sure a lot of players get disappointed with it. I guess I always

00:56:34.640 --> 00:56:42.440
[Guest]: knew that I was going to drop out of the sport in that sense. But to drop, to sort of get

00:56:42.440 --> 00:56:48.400
[Guest]: this out of that negative incident that happened in my life allowed me to stay competitive

00:56:48.400 --> 00:56:55.520
[Guest]: my entire life. So once you have gotten into Ferguson, you're again in a pool of very competitive

00:56:55.520 --> 00:57:02.000
[Guest]: people or very talented people, good academically, whatever. Then you continue, you've seen success,

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:08.880
[Guest]: so now you don't want to do any less than what you have. And that then just continues

00:57:08.880 --> 00:57:17.000
[Guest]: and becomes your new normal. I think that for me it worked to have faced that thing.

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:23.160
[Guest]: And then later that year, I had another chance to go to the nationals trials. I got selected,

00:57:23.160 --> 00:57:29.760
[Guest]: I played the nationals. So in that sense, the circle was completed. But I would say

00:57:29.760 --> 00:57:38.400
[Guest]: that by the time I actually played my nationals, I think I had what I really wanted. So yeah,

00:57:38.400 --> 00:57:46.160
[Guest]: I guess you convert your failures into something that works for you or sort of reveal what

00:57:46.160 --> 00:57:53.920
[Guest]: you already had in terms of your desires. So that's my story in terms of...

00:57:53.920 --> 00:58:00.560
[Amit Varma]: That's an amazing story and so many shades to it, which I'll come at. But the girl who

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:02.920
[Guest]: took your place, did you speak to her? What was that like?

00:58:02.920 --> 00:58:05.920
[Guest]: I don't think I spoke to her. No, I didn't see her again.

00:58:05.920 --> 00:58:06.920
[Amit Varma]: You didn't see her again?

00:58:06.920 --> 00:58:07.920
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:58:07.920 --> 00:58:13.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I wonder where she is today. Yeah, no, that's an amazing story. And I want to ask

00:58:13.840 --> 00:58:20.200
[Amit Varma]: you therefore about a couple of C words. And one is camaraderie, which you know, you referred

00:58:20.200 --> 00:58:24.680
[Amit Varma]: to how you became so close to all the girls in your volleyball team and all of that. And

00:58:24.680 --> 00:58:31.560
[Amit Varma]: the other is competitiveness. And competitiveness, to me, in many ways, seems like a double edged

00:58:31.560 --> 00:58:37.000
[Amit Varma]: sword. And I say this from experience, because I can also be competitive in different ways,

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:41.800
[Amit Varma]: though never really in sports unless you call chess a sport. But you know, on the one hand,

00:58:41.800 --> 00:58:45.080
[Amit Varma]: it drives you to do better and better and better because you want to beat someone or

00:58:45.080 --> 00:58:50.360
[Amit Varma]: you want to do better than someone and so on and so forth. But on the other hand, it

00:58:50.360 --> 00:58:55.880
[Amit Varma]: can also sort of corrode your character in the sense that you begin to think of the world

00:58:55.880 --> 00:59:00.800
[Amit Varma]: as a zero sum game. You know, because that's automatic. Sport is zero sum, society is not.

00:59:00.800 --> 00:59:04.320
[Amit Varma]: You don't have to beat anyone in society to get ahead. It's just the other way around.

00:59:04.320 --> 00:59:09.960
[Amit Varma]: It's a positive something. But sport is zero sum, you have to win, you know, and if you

00:59:09.960 --> 00:59:14.400
[Amit Varma]: win, well, if you humiliate the other person while you're at it, right, you just while

00:59:14.400 --> 00:59:19.360
[Amit Varma]: you're playing against them, you just want to destroy them, as it were. And it seems

00:59:19.360 --> 00:59:25.880
[Amit Varma]: to me that there is a certain amount of negative emotion that kind of gets in there. And this

00:59:25.880 --> 00:59:31.080
[Amit Varma]: is both at perhaps a personal level in terms of what it does to you as a person. And this

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:36.400
[Amit Varma]: is also at a wider level, it can bring out our worst tribal instincts, like when it's

00:59:36.400 --> 00:59:40.640
[Amit Varma]: between countries, it's like Orville said, war minus the shooting. And we can come to

00:59:40.640 --> 00:59:45.800
[Amit Varma]: camaraderie after this. But to just speak about competitiveness, what is your sense

00:59:45.800 --> 00:59:51.080
[Amit Varma]: of the competitive person in you? Because on the one hand, it seems that when you go

00:59:51.080 --> 00:59:58.960
[Amit Varma]: for that volleyball tournament, what you really want at that moment is to play the Nationals.

00:59:58.960 --> 01:00:04.320
[Amit Varma]: And when this incident happens that you're not in the team, you change wanting that to

01:00:04.320 --> 01:00:10.000
[Amit Varma]: wanting to murder the exam, so you can get into Ferguson. And all you have done is you've

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:15.280
[Amit Varma]: shifted your locus of competition. And at some level, one could even say, and I'm not

01:00:15.280 --> 01:00:19.040
[Amit Varma]: saying this about you, I've thought about this for myself, that when I have been competitive,

01:00:19.040 --> 01:00:26.320
[Amit Varma]: and I have tried to win, is it just about ego? Is that what is kind of driving it? You

01:00:26.320 --> 01:00:32.800
[Amit Varma]: know, that kind of a sense. And so that always interests me, because on the one hand, I think

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:39.520
[Amit Varma]: it's important to be competitive. On the other hand, I find that more and more, I find myself

01:00:39.520 --> 01:00:45.560
[Amit Varma]: suppressing that instinct. You know, like now, the one way in which I simply like, you

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:49.160
[Amit Varma]: know, people will ask me about other podcasts, how are their podcasts doing? How are your

01:00:49.160 --> 01:00:54.860
[Amit Varma]: podcasts doing? You know, so and so is such a star on YouTube. And for me, I'm not thinking

01:00:54.860 --> 01:00:58.120
[Amit Varma]: about that. Because on the one hand, I can rationalize it and say, I'm trying to do something

01:00:58.120 --> 01:01:02.960
[Amit Varma]: so different that, you know, I'm kind of alone in that space. And I'm just doing it for myself.

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:06.200
[Amit Varma]: And you can't really compete, which is the right way to think about it. But there is

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:12.880
[Amit Varma]: always that competitive instinct. And I try to fight that in myself more than I let it

01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:19.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of drive me and take me to another level. So what is your relationship with your competitiveness?

01:01:19.320 --> 01:01:27.440
[Guest]: Yeah. So, Amit, before I come to your question, I want to sort of say that over time, we've

01:01:27.440 --> 01:01:36.560
[Guest]: demonized this word competition. And sometimes we repeat it in in that very emotion. And

01:01:36.560 --> 01:01:45.000
[Guest]: then it becomes that emotion. And I think if we talk about the bad things of being competitive,

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:51.640
[Guest]: we have also have to talk about the other side of the coin. And I mean, I'm going to

01:01:51.640 --> 01:01:58.400
[Guest]: be abstract here, because you asked me what my thoughts are. And I feel like we have so

01:01:58.400 --> 01:02:03.480
[Guest]: many words describing so many emotions, but I can't think of many words that describe

01:02:03.480 --> 01:02:09.240
[Guest]: competition, the joys of competition. And I don't know if you've heard the song Allah

01:02:09.240 --> 01:02:17.240
[Guest]: Ke Bande, there's a line in that song. And the line is basically, it's talking about

01:02:17.240 --> 01:02:25.000
[Guest]: a bird, the song that a bird that's sort of falling down. And it says, Girta hua wo asma

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:32.320
[Guest]: se, aakar gira zameen par, khabo mein fir bhi badal hi the, wo kehta raha magar. So,

01:02:32.320 --> 01:02:39.600
[Guest]: that is competition for me. Now, in this case, here's somebody who's faced failure and fallen

01:02:39.600 --> 01:02:45.120
[Guest]: flat on their face. Now, if they are, they are on the ground and yet thinking of their

01:02:45.120 --> 01:02:50.440
[Guest]: best days, then at some point, they want to get there and that is competition with the

01:02:50.440 --> 01:02:58.720
[Guest]: self. Competition does not always have to be with an opponent. It doesn't always have

01:02:58.720 --> 01:03:04.800
[Guest]: to be with another team. It doesn't always have to be with your class. For me, competition,

01:03:04.800 --> 01:03:12.800
[Guest]: yeah, sure, if I'm playing a sport, like Martina Navratilova said about sport, she said something

01:03:12.800 --> 01:03:21.000
[Guest]: like, those who say that winning is not always important, probably lost. And that's true

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:28.280
[Guest]: with sport, you know, because why are you on the, on the court, if you're not there

01:03:28.280 --> 01:03:34.280
[Guest]: to win. And by winning, it means if you're not there to give your best, if you gave your

01:03:34.280 --> 01:03:41.280
[Guest]: best and somebody bested you, then accept it and come back. But for me, competition

01:03:41.280 --> 01:03:48.680
[Guest]: is also about bettering myself, about understanding competition as a concept. Think about Usain

01:03:48.680 --> 01:03:56.400
[Guest]: Bolt, for example. How did he know that his 9 seconds plus something timing was the best

01:03:56.400 --> 01:04:02.040
[Guest]: in the world? Because some other people competed. He went on to beat his own record. That's

01:04:02.040 --> 01:04:07.640
[Guest]: a different story. That's a competition he was in with himself. But if other people were

01:04:07.640 --> 01:04:15.640
[Guest]: not running, he would not know that this 9 second was something amazing. So that's how

01:04:15.640 --> 01:04:24.440
[Guest]: I really look at competition that others allowing me to know what my limits are. That is competition

01:04:24.440 --> 01:04:30.720
[Guest]: for me. Because if I was running all by myself, in whatever I'm doing, I would not know if

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:36.240
[Guest]: I'm really doing my best. Or there are people doing much better than me. Are they doing

01:04:36.240 --> 01:04:42.400
[Guest]: much better than me or they're at my level? How do you know that? So that's my only definition

01:04:42.400 --> 01:04:49.640
[Guest]: of competition. Apart from that, I use my competitive spirit when I'm failing miserably.

01:04:49.640 --> 01:04:54.800
[Guest]: Because you really need to find something to pick yourself up. And apart from that as

01:04:54.800 --> 01:05:03.860
[Guest]: well, I think you need to, if you're really getting all the experiences and absorbing

01:05:03.860 --> 01:05:10.000
[Guest]: everything that the sport or whatever you are trying to improve is teaching you. If

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:19.040
[Guest]: you're really introspecting what a certain experience, a certain match, a certain competition

01:05:19.040 --> 01:05:23.880
[Guest]: has taught you, travelling with your team has taught you. If you're absorbing that,

01:05:23.880 --> 01:05:29.520
[Guest]: you're growing as a person and learning to put competition in perspective. So I am not

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:34.840
[Guest]: a voracious reader, but I'm very good at picking random things that somebody is saying

01:05:34.840 --> 01:05:41.520
[Guest]: in a certain context and using it in some other context. And I was recently watching

01:05:41.520 --> 01:05:50.580
[Guest]: some funny video by Kusha Kapila and she had a very funny take on a teacher is talking

01:05:50.580 --> 01:05:59.560
[Guest]: to a parent. And the teacher is trying to advise the parent that, ye kitabe waghra hai

01:05:59.560 --> 01:06:03.800
[Guest]: class ki ye isko padni chahiye, to B plus to aa jayega. And obviously it's an Indian

01:06:03.800 --> 01:06:08.460
[Guest]: parent, so the Indian parent asks, lekin A plus ke liye kya karna padega? And then the

01:06:08.460 --> 01:06:14.880
[Guest]: teacher says, nahi A plus wala toh aapka bacha hi nahi hai. So I am like that, I know where

01:06:14.880 --> 01:06:21.300
[Guest]: I'm not A plus. So I'm not trying to compete in that zone. I think it's self-awareness

01:06:21.300 --> 01:06:28.840
[Guest]: in that sense. So when it comes to competition, I'm able to distinguish where I can be competitive

01:06:28.840 --> 01:06:35.040
[Guest]: and where I cannot be competitive. And I'm not trying to be competitive in places where

01:06:35.040 --> 01:06:39.820
[Guest]: I know I'm going to be disappointed. That's some sort of self-awareness for me. And so

01:06:39.820 --> 01:06:45.740
[Guest]: it doesn't become toxic for me, that I'm trying and trying and trying and not doing better

01:06:45.740 --> 01:06:55.440
[Guest]: at all. I don't get into that zone. But because I worked for Shell after my engineering, and

01:06:55.440 --> 01:07:01.580
[Guest]: at that time Shell was only recruiting from the IITs. And apart from that, they were recruiting

01:07:01.580 --> 01:07:06.980
[Guest]: from MIT Pune's petroleum branch because it was in the top two in India at that time after

01:07:06.980 --> 01:07:15.340
[Guest]: ISM Dhanbad. So we were the only non-IITians who were joining the small batches of engineers

01:07:15.340 --> 01:07:20.660
[Guest]: that Shell was taking at the time. So I have spent eight years in Shell only working with

01:07:20.660 --> 01:07:29.140
[Guest]: IITians. And if I did not have competitive spirit, I could not have survived that environment

01:07:29.140 --> 01:07:37.500
[Guest]: because they are not only intelligent, but very, very, very hardworking and very competitive.

01:07:37.500 --> 01:07:43.400
[Guest]: So I guess the only way I could have survived in that environment was with my competitive

01:07:43.400 --> 01:07:52.220
[Guest]: spirit. And I have seen the negative sides of competition as well. Because if there are

01:07:52.220 --> 01:07:59.940
[Guest]: people who are not able to separate things in their life where they are not competing,

01:07:59.940 --> 01:08:06.140
[Guest]: where they want peace, where they want growth, but not in a very professional sense, if they

01:08:06.140 --> 01:08:11.300
[Guest]: are not able to separate that, then it can make them miserable. No matter the amount

01:08:11.300 --> 01:08:17.940
[Guest]: of money you're getting, no matter the amount of wealth you're accumulating, experiences

01:08:17.940 --> 01:08:24.740
[Guest]: you're accumulating, your mind is constantly thinking about the same thing. That my colleague

01:08:24.740 --> 01:08:30.580
[Guest]: is doing better than me, has gotten a better yearly performance or whatever. And over time

01:08:30.580 --> 01:08:37.940
[Guest]: that just makes you a very, very unevolved person in a sense. You're also looking at

01:08:37.940 --> 01:08:47.420
[Guest]: other individuals from the same lens. And I think that's where I would say one should

01:08:47.420 --> 01:08:56.740
[Guest]: stop and think. So I would say competition, if you use as a concept in your life, then

01:08:56.740 --> 01:09:02.420
[Guest]: you will be able to choose where you want to really put all your time and effort, and

01:09:02.420 --> 01:09:07.140
[Guest]: where you are not competitive enough, and where you need to do just enough. Because

01:09:07.140 --> 01:09:13.780
[Guest]: there are some places where you need to do just enough to survive. Yeah, and honestly,

01:09:13.780 --> 01:09:18.840
[Guest]: if I look at it, I don't find it toxic. If you constantly look inwards, if you're constantly

01:09:18.840 --> 01:09:26.420
[Guest]: looking outwards, then you are basically comparing yourself with things that are out of your

01:09:26.420 --> 01:09:32.340
[Guest]: circle of influence, and then trying to be competitive with those things. And it's really

01:09:32.340 --> 01:09:39.260
[Amit Varma]: like being a fish trying to climb a tree then. Yeah, that's well put. And the thing is, most

01:09:39.260 --> 01:09:43.180
[Amit Varma]: people aren't given to self-reflection. So in that sense, they can get trapped in that.

01:09:43.180 --> 01:09:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And I'll just think aloud here. One concept you might have heard me exploring with some

01:09:47.280 --> 01:09:52.340
[Amit Varma]: of my recent guests has been something I picked up from Luke Burgess's book, Wanting, of thick

01:09:52.340 --> 01:09:57.440
[Amit Varma]: and thin desires. And the way he defines it is that thick desires are what you really

01:09:57.440 --> 01:10:01.420
[Amit Varma]: inherently want to do. You're not doing it because somebody else is or because you feel

01:10:01.420 --> 01:10:06.020
[Amit Varma]: that's the kind of thing you should do. And thin desires are desires that are often mimetic

01:10:06.020 --> 01:10:12.140
[Amit Varma]: desires or desires that you see them as desires in the environment around you, so you pick

01:10:12.140 --> 01:10:16.980
[Amit Varma]: them up, but you don't really, really want them. So, you know, if I want a new Mercedes

01:10:16.980 --> 01:10:21.380
[Amit Varma]: C-Class, that could be a thin desire. Or if a kid growing up today says, Oh, I want to

01:10:21.380 --> 01:10:25.200
[Amit Varma]: get married and have kids, that could be a thin desire, because you just see that as

01:10:25.200 --> 01:10:29.980
[Amit Varma]: a default thing to want over there. And over time, I think people need to kind of figure

01:10:29.980 --> 01:10:34.420
[Amit Varma]: out what their thick and thin desires are, especially because your most intense desires

01:10:34.420 --> 01:10:38.560
[Amit Varma]: at a moment in time could actually be thin desires. And I'm thinking aloud and thinking

01:10:38.560 --> 01:10:45.140
[Amit Varma]: about how sometimes, you know, in your story of shifting that competitiveness from volleyball,

01:10:45.140 --> 01:10:50.340
[Amit Varma]: once you fail to make the team to your exams, you know, one way to look at it is that both

01:10:50.340 --> 01:10:53.860
[Amit Varma]: of those could have been thin desires, or maybe volleyball could have been thick and

01:10:53.860 --> 01:10:58.260
[Amit Varma]: then you transferred it. But another way and I'm thinking aloud, is that the thick desire

01:10:58.260 --> 01:11:02.620
[Amit Varma]: perhaps was to compete because it would be in your nature to compete and therefore the

01:11:02.620 --> 01:11:07.260
[Amit Varma]: thick desire is to always compete. And it doesn't matter so much what you're competing

01:11:07.260 --> 01:11:12.940
[Amit Varma]: in just the very act of competing and doing your best both improves you in that domain

01:11:12.940 --> 01:11:17.380
[Amit Varma]: and also builds your character because and all those other things of discipline and working

01:11:17.380 --> 01:11:22.020
[Amit Varma]: hard and self reflection even because that is how you improve often kind of come with

01:11:22.020 --> 01:11:31.220
[Guest]: it. So what are your sort of thoughts? I think for me, Amit, it has come out of ambition.

01:11:31.220 --> 01:11:38.780
[Guest]: This competitiveness is not my base level, or my everyday level. If you if I speak about

01:11:38.780 --> 01:11:45.380
[Guest]: me, there are people who are competitive 24 hours. I'm not those type of people, but I'm

01:11:45.380 --> 01:11:51.820
[Guest]: ambitious. And when I say ambitious, I'm not saying I want to be the next Jeff Bezos. And,

01:11:51.820 --> 01:11:55.060
[Guest]: you know, when we talk about ambition, also, we are talking about I want to be Roger Federer,

01:11:55.060 --> 01:12:01.700
[Guest]: I want to be Serena Williams, or Jeff Bezos. I'm, I'm saying my own ambition, my own best

01:12:01.700 --> 01:12:08.100
[Guest]: that I can achieve. And in my mind, there's a sort of a mind map, that these are the few

01:12:08.100 --> 01:12:17.900
[Guest]: things that have to happen if I have to get there. And if I am at this moment, tackling

01:12:17.900 --> 01:12:24.440
[Guest]: a big milestone on that mind map, which is in my mind, then I will be very competitive.

01:12:24.440 --> 01:12:29.380
[Guest]: But let's say I'm between milestones, and there are a few things that have to happen,

01:12:29.380 --> 01:12:35.340
[Guest]: but they are okay, they, you know, okay milestones, then I'm not my best, most competitive at

01:12:35.340 --> 01:12:40.380
[Guest]: that time. So for me, that's why I know it is it's it's coming out of ambition and not

01:12:40.380 --> 01:12:46.540
[Guest]: out of not out of constantly enjoying competition. And in that sense, I get a lot of mental break

01:12:46.540 --> 01:12:51.560
[Guest]: as well between being very, very competitive and not being competitive. So to give you

01:12:51.560 --> 01:12:58.340
[Guest]: an example, to apply for my MBA last year, for example, it was so last year was the worst

01:12:58.340 --> 01:13:03.540
[Guest]: year to apply for an MBA program, because the entire world was applying because a lot

01:13:03.540 --> 01:13:08.700
[Guest]: of people had lost their jobs. And so it was a very, very competitive year to apply for

01:13:08.700 --> 01:13:15.260
[Guest]: a program. And so that naturally meant that you had to ace your entrance exam, which is

01:13:15.260 --> 01:13:19.940
[Guest]: which is the GMAT and you needed to be higher than you would have otherwise been because

01:13:19.940 --> 01:13:25.220
[Guest]: you have to stand out plus we are all applying as Indians. So the colleges want to ensure

01:13:25.220 --> 01:13:28.660
[Guest]: that there's not too many Indians in the class, so they're going to choose the best or whatever

01:13:28.660 --> 01:13:35.180
[Guest]: applications come. So you're competing with Indians and with the world. Apart from the

01:13:35.180 --> 01:13:40.540
[Guest]: profile that you cannot change, you've done what you have all your life. The only thing

01:13:40.540 --> 01:13:46.540
[Guest]: that you can influence is how well you do in that exam. And so I again went into that

01:13:46.540 --> 01:13:51.980
[Guest]: zone where I was literally studying most of my time and trying to get this exam out of

01:13:51.980 --> 01:13:57.660
[Guest]: the way and at a level that I really wanted it. I answered it one time and it wasn't sufficient.

01:13:57.660 --> 01:14:02.820
[Guest]: So I took another couple of months, I answered the exam again, because I knew that I would

01:14:02.820 --> 01:14:11.580
[Guest]: not be happy with the substandard college. And once I got in to a university of my choice,

01:14:11.580 --> 01:14:18.100
[Guest]: now if you look at me, am I very competitive in my class? I'm not. Because now I'm thinking

01:14:18.100 --> 01:14:24.460
[Guest]: of what I want to do afterwards. Now I'm thinking, okay, if I want to do A, B and C things after

01:14:24.460 --> 01:14:33.140
[Guest]: my MBA, do I need to be first in class for that? The answer for my future is no. So then

01:14:33.140 --> 01:14:39.220
[Guest]: you would not see me really burn myself out. I would do everything that's required. I would

01:14:39.220 --> 01:14:44.180
[Guest]: still be slightly competitive. I still don't want to see myself at the bottom of the pack

01:14:44.180 --> 01:14:51.740
[Guest]: or whatever. But you would not see me really work very, very hard to be in the top five

01:14:51.740 --> 01:14:57.060
[Guest]: or 10% because for me, logically doesn't make any sense. So I would say, hey, why should

01:14:57.060 --> 01:15:03.860
[Guest]: I burn myself out then? I would, if I again come across somewhere, some milestone where

01:15:03.860 --> 01:15:12.900
[Guest]: which has to happen on my path. So that for me is then ambition coming sort of together

01:15:12.900 --> 01:15:20.220
[Guest]: with competition. But I cannot constantly be in the competitive zone.

01:15:20.220 --> 01:15:25.300
[Amit Varma]: I think these sort of thoughtful collaborations that you're carrying out, as it were, of how

01:15:25.300 --> 01:15:30.020
[Amit Varma]: competitive you are, come from, again, being very clear in your thinking about what you

01:15:30.020 --> 01:15:35.100
[Amit Varma]: want and what you're optimising for, which I find many people aren't. And certainly,

01:15:35.100 --> 01:15:41.100
[Amit Varma]: I wasn't for a large part of my life. So, you know, it's sort of something that I admire.

01:15:41.100 --> 01:15:45.060
[Amit Varma]: And you know, to get to camaraderie, and even more than that, you'd earlier mentioned about

01:15:45.060 --> 01:15:50.020
[Amit Varma]: how sport changed you, how, you know, all of you in that early volleyball team, you're

01:15:50.020 --> 01:15:54.220
[Amit Varma]: still in touch, you were changed in a different context, you'd mentioned how you find yourself

01:15:54.220 --> 01:15:57.780
[Amit Varma]: different from all the other people around you who didn't play sport at the time, all

01:15:57.780 --> 01:16:03.100
[Amit Varma]: your friends around you. And you also sort of spoke about the influence of that early

01:16:03.100 --> 01:16:07.980
[Amit Varma]: coach Sanjay sir and the kind of regard you held him in and all of that. And I'm guessing

01:16:07.980 --> 01:16:12.780
[Amit Varma]: that that coaching would not, you know, you're not calling him a good coach, because he was

01:16:12.780 --> 01:16:18.740
[Amit Varma]: a strategic genius or a tactical mastermind. There were other elements of mentorship or

01:16:18.740 --> 01:16:24.900
[Amit Varma]: whatever that kind of came into play. So tell me a little bit about how playing sport changed

01:16:24.900 --> 01:16:28.100
[Amit Varma]: you as a person in fundamental ways.

01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:34.940
[Guest]: So I would want to go back, Amit, to the story which I said, you know, started my transformation.

01:16:34.940 --> 01:16:40.900
[Guest]: First of all, when in my sixth standard or seventh standard, I was selected in that volleyball

01:16:40.900 --> 01:16:49.540
[Guest]: team, it was a great time to feel that, hey, I was taller in class. So I got this opportunity,

01:16:49.540 --> 01:16:56.580
[Guest]: I was chosen somewhere, whatever. When that happened, and when we started becoming friends,

01:16:56.580 --> 01:17:00.940
[Guest]: we started valuing friendship. And that's why we started practicing together more and

01:17:00.940 --> 01:17:07.540
[Guest]: not missing practices. And there's one thing that I've always had, that I do not like to

01:17:07.540 --> 01:17:14.580
[Guest]: join something and then start missing it. So that was an inherent thing. Even in school,

01:17:14.580 --> 01:17:18.660
[Guest]: I was not somebody who would bunk school very often. I was not somebody who would be unwell

01:17:18.660 --> 01:17:28.020
[Guest]: too much. So the fact that I would like to be disciplined and show up really helped me.

01:17:28.020 --> 01:17:34.580
[Guest]: And that camaraderie with the seniors in my school, the juniors who came afterwards, and

01:17:34.580 --> 01:17:42.140
[Guest]: then competing together, and then going on shoestring budgets and staying in these small

01:17:42.140 --> 01:17:47.260
[Guest]: government schools and everything just brought our experiences together, it grew us up. All

01:17:47.260 --> 01:17:51.740
[Guest]: of us came from sort of middle class, upper middle class backgrounds, and nobody was carrying

01:17:51.740 --> 01:17:58.980
[Guest]: a lot of money. We never, I don't remember buying a bisleri. I remember, you know, shutting

01:17:58.980 --> 01:18:05.540
[Guest]: all the lights in the room and holding towels and then changing and helping your teammates.

01:18:05.540 --> 01:18:10.980
[Guest]: And then those all those experiences, and I'm sure even Snehal mentioned this in your

01:18:10.980 --> 01:18:16.620
[Guest]: podcast, Snehal Pradhan, that the one time that that your team would get a train ticket

01:18:16.620 --> 01:18:22.580
[Guest]: with a booked berth, everybody was celebrating, it was a day that we've never seen. And I

01:18:22.580 --> 01:18:30.820
[Guest]: had to play like six, seven years for my nationals to happen for us to get a get a train berth

01:18:30.820 --> 01:18:38.540
[Guest]: in sleeper class on our return back to Maharashtra from MP, my nationals were in Rewa. And the

01:18:38.540 --> 01:18:43.220
[Guest]: funny thing is that one time when we were so happy that we have a berth, because all

01:18:43.220 --> 01:18:49.660
[Guest]: other journeys we've done are sat in front of the train toilets with all our bags. And

01:18:49.660 --> 01:18:57.020
[Guest]: there was some sort of a protest going on. And all those guys filled our bogies, they

01:18:57.020 --> 01:19:03.820
[Guest]: took all our berths. And we were eventually 12 of us sitting in the uppermost berth. And

01:19:03.820 --> 01:19:08.660
[Guest]: so it's almost like it's, you know, it's destiny that till the time you're playing the sport,

01:19:08.660 --> 01:19:12.180
[Guest]: you're never going to get a, you know, confirmed berth on a train.

01:19:12.180 --> 01:19:14.300
[Guest]: So only your parents gave birth to you.

01:19:14.300 --> 01:19:21.420
[Guest]: That was the only berth I got. And there's a story in that as well. So when we didn't

01:19:21.420 --> 01:19:27.740
[Guest]: get these berths, and we had to sit on the topmost berth, there was a friend of mine,

01:19:27.740 --> 01:19:33.900
[Guest]: who's a dear friend even now. And she was looking forward to seeing a brother of hers

01:19:33.900 --> 01:19:40.380
[Guest]: who was going to bring pizza on a certain station where the train stopped for 10 minutes.

01:19:40.380 --> 01:19:45.580
[Guest]: And on the 15, during the 15 days of our nationals, I think the Maharashtra team was carrying

01:19:45.580 --> 01:19:55.180
[Guest]: a, like took a cook with them. But we always got like roti and aloo sabzi. And we were,

01:19:55.180 --> 01:20:00.460
[Guest]: we were tired of it, like tired as in we had forgotten what food and taste was like, this

01:20:00.460 --> 01:20:06.940
[Guest]: was December, it was very cold, none of us had seen that kind of cold. And this girl

01:20:06.940 --> 01:20:12.060
[Guest]: was at some point went to the cook and she was like, make something else, make anything

01:20:12.060 --> 01:20:18.560
[Guest]: else. And this guy was like, yeah, yeah, yeah. Ma'am, today we're going to make something

01:20:18.560 --> 01:20:23.260
[Guest]: different. And then she tells everybody today we're going to get something else for dinner.

01:20:23.260 --> 01:20:31.220
[Guest]: And then they serve us aloo sabzi and this chapati. And she's almost crying. She's just,

01:20:31.220 --> 01:20:35.260
[Guest]: she's lost it completely. And she's like, what is different in this? You've told us

01:20:35.260 --> 01:20:39.700
[Guest]: that you're going to make. And he's like, nahi, aaj matar dala hai iske andar. And,

01:20:39.700 --> 01:20:45.660
[Guest]: and she was, she started crying. And then I remember, so few of us, we were like, Disha,

01:20:45.660 --> 01:20:50.900
[Guest]: let's go, we will buy some Cadburys or something. And we were also like, we were also much younger,

01:20:50.900 --> 01:20:55.940
[Guest]: but she was a couple of years younger than us. And then we go into these streets of Rewa

01:20:55.940 --> 01:21:01.460
[Guest]: somewhere in the evening. And then she sees a small tapri somewhere at a distance and

01:21:01.460 --> 01:21:07.820
[Guest]: she runs and she's maybe about 100 meters ahead of us. And she goes to that tapri and

01:21:07.820 --> 01:21:15.260
[Guest]: she speaks to him. And then we are still walking. And then she turns around and she says loudly

01:21:15.260 --> 01:21:20.500
[Guest]: and she's shouting from there. And she's like, this guy does not even know what a dairy milk

01:21:20.500 --> 01:21:26.460
[Guest]: is. She was so disturbed. And so when we, when we were returning, this brother was going

01:21:26.460 --> 01:21:33.700
[Guest]: to bring pizzas for her. And we did not have even an inch of space left. It was in the

01:21:33.700 --> 01:21:43.060
[Guest]: entire bogie. It was full. Amit, this girl just made everybody move. She marched out

01:21:43.060 --> 01:21:49.700
[Guest]: of the train, got the pizza, got into the train again and got upstairs, brought the

01:21:49.700 --> 01:21:55.420
[Guest]: pizza up on the upper berth for all of us. And if you had seen, there was not, there

01:21:55.420 --> 01:22:00.700
[Guest]: was, there were people everywhere in the train. And I have seen how, you know, I remember

01:22:00.700 --> 01:22:08.420
[Guest]: all these moments when, you know, somebody showed you their strength or courage. Because

01:22:08.420 --> 01:22:13.940
[Guest]: I don't know, everybody was saying that she's not going to get her pizza today. And she

01:22:13.940 --> 01:22:22.620
[Guest]: got it and she fed everybody that day, pizza. So all those, all those things happen. And

01:22:22.620 --> 01:22:26.740
[Guest]: then you remember all those things. And I think many years later, when I was in a situation

01:22:26.740 --> 01:22:32.420
[Guest]: where I was traveling for work, and I was put in, put into five star hotels with like

01:22:32.420 --> 01:22:39.700
[Guest]: the slurries and everything. And to date, every time I'm treated well, I really value

01:22:39.700 --> 01:22:45.980
[Guest]: it. Because, because for many, many years, we did not have that. I guess that is something

01:22:45.980 --> 01:22:53.600
[Guest]: that never goes. And, and let me know if I'm digressing from what your question is. But

01:22:53.600 --> 01:22:59.820
[Guest]: I guess in that sense, if you ask me how my sport, how did sport change me? First of all,

01:22:59.820 --> 01:23:04.140
[Guest]: these were the, these were the early growing up experiences that allow you to become much

01:23:04.140 --> 01:23:10.180
[Guest]: more adjusting, but also demand for what you want. Look after your, look after your team.

01:23:10.180 --> 01:23:14.500
[Guest]: Because again, there's benefits of being in a team sport compared to an individual sport

01:23:14.500 --> 01:23:20.540
[Guest]: like tennis. So you look after your teammates, you learn off the court and on the court as

01:23:20.540 --> 01:23:25.060
[Guest]: well. And that's why I keep mentioning that I love the movie Chakde, because there's so

01:23:25.060 --> 01:23:32.020
[Guest]: much going on on the court between seniors and juniors and the politics on the court

01:23:32.020 --> 01:23:39.860
[Guest]: itself. So you learn from all of that. But apart from that, after this whole corruption

01:23:39.860 --> 01:23:45.300
[Guest]: incident that happened with me during 10th, I discovered that I could move, I could do

01:23:45.300 --> 01:23:52.140
[Guest]: well academically or so. One of the tricks that I have developed to be successful in

01:23:52.140 --> 01:23:59.220
[Guest]: smaller endeavors and in large endeavors after that is to fantasize about success. I mean,

01:23:59.220 --> 01:24:04.140
[Guest]: it is my mantra. If I'm on the treadmill, for example, and I have decided so that's

01:24:04.140 --> 01:24:08.660
[Guest]: another thing. And later when I got more into fitness, I used to tell this to my clients

01:24:08.660 --> 01:24:17.500
[Guest]: as well. Do not do anything with no goal whatsoever. Don't get into onto the treadmill, just saying

01:24:17.500 --> 01:24:23.860
[Guest]: that, hey, I'm there to walk. Either you're going to walk because you want to walk at

01:24:23.860 --> 01:24:30.740
[Guest]: a certain speed, or you want to test out a certain incline level, or you want to walk

01:24:30.740 --> 01:24:37.780
[Guest]: for, let's say one hour, which you've not done before. Maybe you walked 55 minutes before,

01:24:37.780 --> 01:24:42.900
[Guest]: but now you want to walk 60 minutes, at least that's a goal. But don't tell me I'm just

01:24:42.900 --> 01:24:48.500
[Guest]: on the treadmill. Tell me what's your goal, why are you on the treadmill? Because if I

01:24:48.500 --> 01:24:57.500
[Guest]: wanted to make you really test yourself and really get the most out of being on the treadmill,

01:24:57.500 --> 01:25:04.820
[Guest]: you can do that in 10 minutes also, you can do that in 60 minutes also. So don't try to

01:25:04.820 --> 01:25:08.940
[Guest]: tell me that because you were on the treadmill for 60 minutes, listening to music and just

01:25:08.940 --> 01:25:16.060
[Guest]: walking, you've exercised a lot. Tell me what did you achieve today? So I don't get onto

01:25:16.060 --> 01:25:21.140
[Guest]: the treadmill if I don't have a goal. And normally I'm trying to run a 5 kilometer or

01:25:21.140 --> 01:25:25.140
[Guest]: something on the treadmill. Like I mentioned, I'm not an early morning person, so I'd end

01:25:25.140 --> 01:25:34.580
[Guest]: up doing some of my runs on the treadmill. And even in a 5 kilometer run, it's very challenging

01:25:34.580 --> 01:25:42.340
[Guest]: because, even if you want to improve by half a minute or let's say 40 seconds or so, it's

01:25:42.340 --> 01:25:48.980
[Guest]: quite an achievement. And it takes strategy. How and at what point are you going to save

01:25:48.980 --> 01:25:56.380
[Guest]: those 40 seconds compared to your last run? And that last run couldn't have been yesterday.

01:25:56.380 --> 01:26:02.300
[Guest]: I have to do something in between the two runs such that I can expect a 40 second less

01:26:02.300 --> 01:26:08.860
[Guest]: timing this time. Part of that strategy is, if I can imagine, if I can fantasize about

01:26:08.860 --> 01:26:14.380
[Guest]: a situation, I mean, sure, I will have improved the running strategy, I may have improved

01:26:14.380 --> 01:26:20.460
[Guest]: my nutrition or I may have done a few practice runs to sprint in the middle or whatever,

01:26:20.460 --> 01:26:27.500
[Guest]: that all strategy is there. But part of it is you are running towards, you have maybe

01:26:27.500 --> 01:26:33.660
[Guest]: the last 5 or 7 minutes left, you're really low on energy. And at that time, you fantasize

01:26:33.660 --> 01:26:39.900
[Guest]: about something, you fantasize that maybe somebody you absolutely love is at the end

01:26:39.900 --> 01:26:48.700
[Guest]: of this run and is really applauding you. Somebody you or maybe a stadium is applauding

01:26:48.700 --> 01:26:53.420
[Guest]: you. Or maybe you are fantasizing, hey, I'm going to take a picture of this treadmill

01:26:53.420 --> 01:26:59.020
[Guest]: when that timing comes so that I can put it up on Facebook or I can put it up on Twitter.

01:26:59.020 --> 01:27:05.620
[Guest]: So I have learned to fantasize. And that helps me. And I use that technique sometimes for

01:27:05.620 --> 01:27:10.300
[Guest]: the short term things like I'm on the treadmill or whatever. But sometimes I will use it for

01:27:10.300 --> 01:27:16.300
[Guest]: a longer term goal as well, like I'm studying for an exam or I'm working on my startup,

01:27:16.300 --> 01:27:21.380
[Guest]: for example. And even startups where you're putting in your own money, you're full of

01:27:21.380 --> 01:27:27.220
[Guest]: doubts. How do you bring in those endorphins? Sometimes you're just sat there and you're

01:27:27.220 --> 01:27:33.940
[Guest]: like you're fantasizing that, hey, maybe 100 people in the US are using my fitness program

01:27:33.940 --> 01:27:39.900
[Guest]: or they may be talking about it. They want to share it on Facebook or somebody sitting

01:27:39.900 --> 01:27:49.380
[Guest]: in other cities in India is using it. So you learn to better fantasize and then use those

01:27:49.380 --> 01:27:56.340
[Guest]: endorphins to get that last bit of success. And that's something I've got from sports

01:27:56.340 --> 01:28:02.940
[Guest]: because you draw from an applause you had enjoyed, you draw from somebody who said something

01:28:02.940 --> 01:28:08.660
[Guest]: nice to you after you did something. That's something I've gotten from sport. And the

01:28:08.660 --> 01:28:17.940
[Guest]: other thing that I have mentioned before is don't take failure personally. Like if you

01:28:17.940 --> 01:28:25.020
[Guest]: failed at something, either you were not very good at it, or circumstances didn't allow

01:28:25.020 --> 01:28:31.380
[Guest]: you to do it. It's how you look at it, or maybe you have to take time off to understand

01:28:31.380 --> 01:28:36.940
[Guest]: if it was just something that you will not be able to do better anymore. So it's you

01:28:36.940 --> 01:28:44.100
[Guest]: in that case, or was it because of circumstances? And in that case, you just reattempt it if

01:28:44.100 --> 01:28:50.740
[Guest]: you can, and this time the circumstances would be different. So for me, I have faced a lot

01:28:50.740 --> 01:29:00.060
[Guest]: of failure at different points, but somehow I have always thought that this wasn't me.

01:29:00.060 --> 01:29:06.300
[Guest]: Something else happened. And so when I'm going to attempt it again, I am pretty sure I'm

01:29:06.300 --> 01:29:13.500
[Guest]: going to do well. So it happened to me in engineering as well. So there's a fairly difficult

01:29:13.500 --> 01:29:18.540
[Guest]: paper in the first year, it's called graphics, if you remember. And I didn't do engineering,

01:29:18.540 --> 01:29:23.660
[Guest]: so I don't remember. But yeah, so graphics and strength of materials are two topics that

01:29:23.660 --> 01:29:27.940
[Guest]: the engineering students are quite scared of in the first year. And graphics is this

01:29:27.940 --> 01:29:33.780
[Guest]: four hour paper where you are with your drafter, and you're trying to draw all kinds of figures

01:29:33.780 --> 01:29:39.980
[Guest]: and 3d figures and come to answers of what angle is what or whatever, and takes fair

01:29:39.980 --> 01:29:45.380
[Guest]: amount of visualization. Somebody has to sort of teach you how to do that. I was taking

01:29:45.380 --> 01:29:51.140
[Guest]: a class for this paper, because everybody does, and you have quite a bit of equipment

01:29:51.140 --> 01:29:56.900
[Guest]: with you and these big books on which you are drawing. And it was I think March or April,

01:29:56.900 --> 01:30:01.700
[Guest]: it was very hot, and this class that I was in had some hundred students packed in a very

01:30:01.700 --> 01:30:10.820
[Guest]: small room. And the ACs were not working. And when the class got over, I took my Activa

01:30:10.820 --> 01:30:16.380
[Guest]: out, I had an Activa at the time, which my father had gifted me because I played this

01:30:16.380 --> 01:30:25.220
[Guest]: national the year before. And I had a big accident. And I don't have memory of what

01:30:25.220 --> 01:30:29.900
[Guest]: happened really, but some people tell me that I was maybe on the side of the road, and there

01:30:29.900 --> 01:30:36.740
[Guest]: was a car parked who opened the door on the driver's side, and then it hit me and I fell

01:30:36.740 --> 01:30:47.820
[Guest]: or something. I don't remember. And then my Activa really sort of was in a bad shape after

01:30:47.820 --> 01:30:55.700
[Guest]: that accident. It was inactiva. It was inactiva, exactly. So because my dad had gifted me this

01:30:55.700 --> 01:31:03.620
[Guest]: Activa after my nationals, and he had taken like a massive loan or so for it, I was very,

01:31:03.620 --> 01:31:10.620
[Guest]: very upset. And I was then upset because this person was running these classes in such a

01:31:10.620 --> 01:31:17.220
[Guest]: small space and putting us through this. And then my Activa was like maybe I think two

01:31:17.220 --> 01:31:21.180
[Guest]: months old or so. So I was very emotional about it. And I was like, I'm not going to

01:31:21.180 --> 01:31:29.300
[Guest]: his class again. And I'm going to try and study at home. And invariably, this is a subject

01:31:29.300 --> 01:31:34.180
[Guest]: that you cannot study at home because somebody has to help you visualize things. And I failed

01:31:34.180 --> 01:31:40.460
[Guest]: it in first year and I hadn't failed I think in any academic, in an academic situation

01:31:40.460 --> 01:31:49.740
[Guest]: before that. And I was, I think I got the result and for some reason, I just felt that

01:31:49.740 --> 01:31:55.500
[Guest]: hey, I know why this happened. And I'm going to answer the exam again. And there's always

01:31:55.500 --> 01:32:00.020
[Guest]: people who will be like, oh, now what will happen to your recruitment and somebody is

01:32:00.020 --> 01:32:05.020
[Guest]: going to see you fail this paper. And none of that bothered me because I never thought

01:32:05.020 --> 01:32:10.020
[Guest]: that I did not understand what was going on. I had to answer that obviously in the next

01:32:10.020 --> 01:32:19.300
[Guest]: semester again. And I probably ended up scoring one of the highest in my batch in my university.

01:32:19.300 --> 01:32:27.700
[Guest]: Because I gave it time and I was in the frame of mind to really answer that paper once again.

01:32:27.700 --> 01:32:31.820
[Guest]: And it turns out that I did better than I would have done the first time just to try

01:32:31.820 --> 01:32:39.500
[Guest]: and pass that subject. So I guess that's something also I draw from sport that hey, failure can

01:32:39.500 --> 01:32:47.560
[Guest]: happen, don't take it personally, unless you think that you cannot do it. So when I do

01:32:47.560 --> 01:32:54.020
[Guest]: face some failure, I don't feel like it's me. I feel like maybe I didn't do well enough.

01:32:54.020 --> 01:32:58.860
[Guest]: Maybe there are other ways of doing it. I have not really explored all those other ways.

01:32:58.860 --> 01:33:05.420
[Guest]: So I cannot conclude that I cannot do it. I'm just taking you through how my mind would

01:33:05.420 --> 01:33:12.580
[Guest]: think in those situations. And then I guess one of the very short points that I would

01:33:12.580 --> 01:33:17.460
[Guest]: like to make about sport is that I don't think sport builds character. I do not think it

01:33:17.460 --> 01:33:24.300
[Guest]: builds character. You just have the character that you have. It can maybe sharpen it in

01:33:24.300 --> 01:33:30.300
[Guest]: some ways because it allows you a lot more experiences to sort of introspect and then

01:33:30.300 --> 01:33:38.300
[Guest]: carry forward. But your character is what it is. And in sport as well, I have seen,

01:33:38.300 --> 01:33:44.340
[Guest]: for example, there was a girl that was a very good volleyball player. And she was much more

01:33:44.340 --> 01:33:50.300
[Guest]: senior to me. And I'm not going to name her, but she was always a gunda. She was always

01:33:50.300 --> 01:33:58.740
[Guest]: a gunda. And everybody was scared of her. And she was always, you would imagine, ends

01:33:58.740 --> 01:34:08.820
[Guest]: up backing people or, you know, getting violent. And she later ended up joining MNS as well.

01:34:08.820 --> 01:34:18.020
[Guest]: And she was, she was leading the youth wing. So you could tell when you were with her during

01:34:18.020 --> 01:34:24.420
[Guest]: the game. But she was a brilliant volleyball player. And we always knew that when we heard

01:34:24.420 --> 01:34:33.060
[Guest]: that this is what she's doing now, none of us were surprised. So at the same time, somehow

01:34:33.060 --> 01:34:41.660
[Guest]: my sports team, my immediate team, we were all the academic types. So most of us ended

01:34:41.660 --> 01:34:47.260
[Guest]: up playing nationals eventually. Some ended up sort of getting to the internationals trials

01:34:47.260 --> 01:34:55.180
[Guest]: and things. But again, we ended up being academically, we did academically very well. So that's also

01:34:55.180 --> 01:35:02.660
[Guest]: something that didn't happen just like that for anybody. We always knew we were like that.

01:35:02.660 --> 01:35:08.860
[Guest]: In terms of, even if you see in sports, all sportsmen don't have the best character, you

01:35:08.860 --> 01:35:15.220
[Guest]: know. So to make these blanket statements like sports builds character. No, it doesn't.

01:35:15.220 --> 01:35:21.100
[Guest]: Look at tennis. Djokovic is very different in terms of how his character is in general

01:35:21.100 --> 01:35:30.860
[Guest]: from Nadal and Federer. You can even take a, I mean, look at how Nick Kyrgios, for example,

01:35:30.860 --> 01:35:37.700
[Guest]: compared to some other younger players who are his competition. So it can, sport can

01:35:37.700 --> 01:35:44.380
[Guest]: at best reveal character, but you are sort of built in a certain way. And I guess that's

01:35:44.380 --> 01:35:50.700
[Guest]: actually why you got into sport or any other activity that you naturally sort of were sucked

01:35:50.700 --> 01:35:56.860
[Guest]: into. So yeah, and I guess I want to travel, I keep wanting to travel because sport introduced

01:35:56.860 --> 01:36:05.220
[Guest]: me to that. And the experiences that I have had through sport are the ones that have allowed

01:36:05.220 --> 01:36:13.260
[Guest]: me to build my best friendships across the world. I have not ended up making friends,

01:36:13.260 --> 01:36:19.340
[Guest]: as good friends outside of sport as I have in sport. So that's a gift of the sport, I

01:36:19.340 --> 01:36:20.340
[Guest]: would say.

01:36:20.340 --> 01:36:25.140
[Amit Varma]: That's a great point about sport revealing character. And I agree with you there. I think

01:36:25.140 --> 01:36:29.300
[Amit Varma]: there's this quote by Steven Pinker about how nature gives you knobs, nurture turns

01:36:29.300 --> 01:36:33.620
[Amit Varma]: them. And in a sense, I guess sport could turn some of those knobs that are already

01:36:33.620 --> 01:36:38.660
[Amit Varma]: within you. You know, if you have a deep competitive sense, maybe hone that. If you are a gunda,

01:36:38.660 --> 01:36:42.780
[Amit Varma]: maybe hone that and take you to MNS. Who knows if she didn't play volleyball, she may not

01:36:42.780 --> 01:36:47.660
[Amit Varma]: have been at MNS. I want to go back to Disha and the pizza. And that's such a fantastic

01:36:47.660 --> 01:36:49.140
[Guest]: story because it also reveals...

01:36:49.140 --> 01:36:51.460
[Guest]: Yeah, we still laugh about it. It was hilarious.

01:36:51.460 --> 01:36:55.700
[Amit Varma]: It also reveals the power of incentives. And who knows, maybe, you know, maybe it helped

01:36:55.700 --> 01:36:59.220
[Amit Varma]: her discover a little bit of herself that no one can mess with her when she really wants

01:36:59.220 --> 01:37:00.220
[Guest]: something she gets.

01:37:00.220 --> 01:37:04.940
[Guest]: Oh, absolutely. Absolutely. And that's what we got out of that story about her. And that's

01:37:04.940 --> 01:37:11.260
[Guest]: what we say to her as well. And you would see that about her even afterwards. If you

01:37:11.260 --> 01:37:17.900
[Guest]: much later when all of us had cars and we were driving now, Disha was absolutely a boss

01:37:17.900 --> 01:37:24.700
[Guest]: on the road. Like she could be stuck in the worst traffic ever and act like, you know,

01:37:24.700 --> 01:37:29.620
[Guest]: you guys are all wrong. I am right. And I'm really cool. And I'm going to turn my car

01:37:29.620 --> 01:37:38.060
[Guest]: around and leave. A lot of people really panic in those situations. And to stay calm and

01:37:38.060 --> 01:37:44.460
[Guest]: really get your... I don't know how this happens, but I don't know. Maybe because all my friends

01:37:44.460 --> 01:37:49.820
[Guest]: come from the sports background or something, but most of my friends are incredible drivers,

01:37:49.820 --> 01:37:54.220
[Guest]: incredible drivers, women. I don't know how that is, but...

01:37:54.220 --> 01:37:58.260
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there might be a little bit of self-selection there in the sense that people who get into

01:37:58.260 --> 01:38:02.660
[Amit Varma]: sport and stay into sport would naturally have things like good hand-eye coordination

01:38:02.660 --> 01:38:07.060
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, that might play a part. I want to double click on something that you

01:38:07.060 --> 01:38:10.700
[Amit Varma]: said earlier about how, like, for example, if you're on a treadmill, you have to have

01:38:10.700 --> 01:38:14.780
[Amit Varma]: a goal. You can't just be there as part of whatever. I mean, I guess Disha could think

01:38:14.780 --> 01:38:21.420
[Amit Varma]: of, I'm going to order a pizza after this hour of running or whatever. But that also

01:38:21.420 --> 01:38:30.100
[Amit Varma]: seems to sort of run parallel to, not necessarily contradictory to, but parallel to the advice

01:38:30.100 --> 01:38:34.860
[Amit Varma]: that one gives all sports people and I, in fact, give my writing students of process

01:38:34.860 --> 01:38:39.100
[Amit Varma]: being more important than goals. Like in his excellent book, Atomic Habits, James Clear

01:38:39.100 --> 01:38:44.820
[Amit Varma]: also talks about how don't focus on goals, focus on processes. And that's something I

01:38:44.820 --> 01:38:49.460
[Amit Varma]: also drive home to my writing students, that what's important is to build a writing habit.

01:38:49.460 --> 01:38:53.260
[Amit Varma]: If you just say that I want to write op-eds and send them off, then once every three months

01:38:53.260 --> 01:38:56.980
[Amit Varma]: you feel like writing something, you'll open your laptop and you'll open a Word doc and

01:38:56.980 --> 01:39:00.420
[Amit Varma]: then you'll struggle like mad because you don't have the habit. It's more important

01:39:00.420 --> 01:39:05.220
[Amit Varma]: to build a habit. And once you have the habit, you can do pretty much anything you want.

01:39:05.220 --> 01:39:09.340
[Amit Varma]: The goals kind of take care of themselves. And this doesn't mean that don't have goals,

01:39:09.340 --> 01:39:14.860
[Amit Varma]: but it just means that processes are all important and you've got to kind of follow them through,

01:39:14.860 --> 01:39:20.060
[Amit Varma]: otherwise the goals won't really materialize. Another way of looking at it is don't think

01:39:20.060 --> 01:39:25.500
[Amit Varma]: of the things you want to do, but think of the person you want to be. So the example

01:39:25.500 --> 01:39:29.820
[Amit Varma]: I give my writing students here is that if you decide you want to read more, you could

01:39:29.820 --> 01:39:33.780
[Amit Varma]: say, okay, every day between seven and eight, I'm going to read, right? And you do it one

01:39:33.780 --> 01:39:37.380
[Amit Varma]: day, you do it two days, but then you fall off the wagon and then it just goes, life

01:39:37.380 --> 01:39:41.820
[Amit Varma]: gets in the way. And then it leads to a vicious cycle where you beat yourself up and say,

01:39:41.820 --> 01:39:46.200
[Amit Varma]: I am not a reading kind of person or I am a Netflix kind of person and everything kind

01:39:46.200 --> 01:39:51.180
[Amit Varma]: of falls apart. But instead of doing this, if you just think about who is the best version

01:39:51.180 --> 01:39:55.820
[Amit Varma]: of you, which is something I think everyone should sit and do anyway, if you just think

01:39:55.820 --> 01:39:59.500
[Amit Varma]: about who is the best version of you, what that person does, which you don't do, what

01:39:59.500 --> 01:40:04.820
[Amit Varma]: that person does not do, which you do and internalize some of that. And then let's say

01:40:04.820 --> 01:40:10.300
[Amit Varma]: then you make yourself image as I am a self-taught person who loves to read. When I am bored,

01:40:10.300 --> 01:40:14.580
[Amit Varma]: I don't reach for my phone, I reach for a book. You know, if you can internalize that

01:40:14.580 --> 01:40:20.020
[Amit Varma]: self-image, then the reading habit automatically flows from there. Even if you don't read on

01:40:20.020 --> 01:40:24.100
[Amit Varma]: a particular day, it doesn't matter because you've internalized that self-image that I

01:40:24.100 --> 01:40:30.500
[Amit Varma]: am a reader and that self-image will sort of drive what you do instead of the other

01:40:30.500 --> 01:40:36.340
[Amit Varma]: way around. And that's incredibly powerful. And I found this sort of powerful in my own

01:40:36.340 --> 01:40:41.860
[Amit Varma]: life not being able to implement it as much as I would like to. But I think that much

01:40:41.860 --> 01:40:46.320
[Amit Varma]: of my youth possibly went thinking too much about goals. In fact, the exact word you use

01:40:46.320 --> 01:40:52.020
[Amit Varma]: fantasizing about goals and not actually building the processes and the habits that would give

01:40:52.020 --> 01:40:57.620
[Amit Varma]: me the ability to actually accomplish these goals. Now, I know that when you spoke of

01:40:57.620 --> 01:41:03.660
[Amit Varma]: having goals, you weren't contradicting this. You were on a parallel track where your point,

01:41:03.660 --> 01:41:07.140
[Amit Varma]: I'm guessing, correct me if I'm wrong, your point was that you have to be clear about

01:41:07.140 --> 01:41:11.780
[Amit Varma]: what you want out of something. Only then can you get the most out of it. You know,

01:41:11.780 --> 01:41:16.380
[Amit Varma]: what are sort of your thoughts on these different tracks?

01:41:16.380 --> 01:41:23.300
[Guest]: So Amit, first of all, when I said fantasizing, I meant using fantasy as one of the tools

01:41:23.300 --> 01:41:30.460
[Guest]: to achieve what you're trying to achieve. I did not mean fantasizing in terms of just

01:41:30.460 --> 01:41:36.500
[Guest]: dreaming away. So I did not mean dreaming away in that sense. So for me, fantasy is

01:41:36.500 --> 01:41:45.100
[Guest]: just a tool you sort of use sometimes to get those extra endorphins to push the last mile.

01:41:45.100 --> 01:41:51.220
[Guest]: And in terms of goals, the reason like, of course, like you said, we want to somehow

01:41:51.220 --> 01:41:59.380
[Guest]: find a way to instruct our mind to have a process. And for everybody that instruction

01:41:59.380 --> 01:42:05.340
[Guest]: works very differently. And so sometimes you ask people to set a goal so that they start

01:42:05.340 --> 01:42:10.460
[Guest]: thinking that, hey, if I am on the treadmill tomorrow, I need to achieve this. So what

01:42:10.460 --> 01:42:17.580
[Guest]: do I need to do today? And sometimes that may be seven days before you get on the treadmill.

01:42:17.580 --> 01:42:21.460
[Guest]: Sometimes it's just tomorrow. Sometimes it is this evening and today morning you're thinking

01:42:21.460 --> 01:42:29.420
[Guest]: about it. But what I feel is I have a problem with pointlessness, especially if you're giving

01:42:29.420 --> 01:42:37.100
[Guest]: time because it can really waste your, I see a lot of people wasting their time in the

01:42:37.100 --> 01:42:45.860
[Guest]: gym with false ideas of, oh, I've spent one hour on the treadmill, so I've done a lot.

01:42:45.860 --> 01:42:51.020
[Guest]: If somebody spent 10 minutes, that may not mean they've done enough. Maybe they've just

01:42:51.020 --> 01:42:59.020
[Guest]: warmed up. That's all not true. So we need to constantly ask ourselves why we are doing

01:42:59.020 --> 01:43:07.180
[Guest]: something that we are doing. And if you try and force people to sort of have a goal, a

01:43:07.180 --> 01:43:13.660
[Guest]: short term goal, then it forces them to ask themselves, what is it that I'm trying to

01:43:13.660 --> 01:43:18.300
[Guest]: achieve here? Then sometimes people will come back and say, no, no, I just want to relax

01:43:18.300 --> 01:43:24.060
[Guest]: on the treadmill and I'm just not going to put myself in that mental pressure. And then

01:43:24.060 --> 01:43:29.940
[Guest]: I say that if that's your goal, then why are you doing it on the treadmill? Go walking,

01:43:29.940 --> 01:43:37.100
[Guest]: listen to some music. Why should it be on the treadmill if you're looking for relaxation?

01:43:37.100 --> 01:43:42.020
[Guest]: If you're looking at being on the treadmill because you want to get fitter, then you have

01:43:42.020 --> 01:43:48.860
[Guest]: to somehow push yourself. So for me, it's really looking at the goal and pushing them

01:43:48.860 --> 01:43:59.420
[Guest]: to form a process behind how will you really reach that goal. And in general, I think you

01:43:59.420 --> 01:44:05.740
[Guest]: are not going to discover yourself if you're not trying to do something specific. If I'm

01:44:05.740 --> 01:44:12.140
[Guest]: just going to go to the gym and say that, hey, I'm going to lift weights today and I'm

01:44:12.140 --> 01:44:17.900
[Guest]: just going to be on the treadmill, then what am I discovering about myself today? Maybe

01:44:17.900 --> 01:44:24.760
[Guest]: I'm going to try and run my fastest five kilometers and I fail. Then even then I have discovered

01:44:24.760 --> 01:44:30.220
[Guest]: something about myself. Maybe I was not in the mood. Maybe evening doesn't work for me.

01:44:30.220 --> 01:44:36.220
[Guest]: Maybe I should try morning. Maybe I've not eaten enough. Maybe I was not feeling well.

01:44:36.220 --> 01:44:41.820
[Guest]: Something it could be just a small thing. But if I did not have a goal in the first

01:44:41.820 --> 01:44:46.220
[Guest]: place, I'm just going to be on the treadmill for an hour without learning anything about

01:44:46.220 --> 01:44:53.100
[Guest]: myself. Forget achieving something great, but I'll have not learned anything about anything.

01:44:53.100 --> 01:44:58.940
[Guest]: Not about fitness, not about myself. Then why not watch a movie instead? So that's how

01:44:58.940 --> 01:45:02.680
[Amit Varma]: I look at it. Yeah, I mean, I get what you're saying from

01:45:02.680 --> 01:45:06.940
[Amit Varma]: a point of view of sort of being clear about what you want. And then once you're clear

01:45:06.940 --> 01:45:11.780
[Amit Varma]: about what you want, you can build the processes that help you get there. But being clear about

01:45:11.780 --> 01:45:17.060
[Amit Varma]: what you want is useful. So, you know, before we, you know, continue with your personal

01:45:17.060 --> 01:45:20.660
[Amit Varma]: journey into engineering and all of that, and before we go there, we'll take a break.

01:45:20.660 --> 01:45:26.700
[Amit Varma]: But before all of that, just wanted to finish talking about your sporting experiences through

01:45:26.700 --> 01:45:30.580
[Amit Varma]: the system that you, you know, you're in the school team, and then you play city level,

01:45:30.580 --> 01:45:34.380
[Amit Varma]: district level, all of that, you go through those motions. Now, it would seem that in

01:45:34.380 --> 01:45:38.820
[Amit Varma]: the case of you or your friends, you enjoyed playing the sport, you were competitive, you

01:45:38.820 --> 01:45:42.380
[Amit Varma]: loved it, you went through all of that. It's obviously a thrill to play at the national

01:45:42.380 --> 01:45:47.140
[Amit Varma]: level. I went through all of that in chess as well. So I totally get it. But all of you

01:45:47.140 --> 01:45:51.560
[Amit Varma]: knew all along that you're not going to be professional volleyball players. This is not

01:45:51.560 --> 01:45:56.960
[Amit Varma]: going to be your life. There are other things that you will do. But for a lot of other people,

01:45:56.960 --> 01:46:01.860
[Amit Varma]: it may not always be the case. There might be people from less privileged socioeconomic

01:46:01.860 --> 01:46:06.920
[Amit Varma]: backgrounds who aren't good at anything else, who don't have other opportunities necessarily

01:46:06.920 --> 01:46:11.600
[Amit Varma]: available to them, but they are bloody good at this one sport. So what is that journey

01:46:11.600 --> 01:46:16.700
[Amit Varma]: for them like? Because I'm assuming that the kind of corruption which you were victim to

01:46:16.700 --> 01:46:20.940
[Amit Varma]: would be endemic in sport, especially in North India, from whatever I hear Delhi, Bihar and

01:46:20.940 --> 01:46:26.340
[Amit Varma]: so on. It would be absolutely endemic and making it hard for talented people to come

01:46:26.340 --> 01:46:31.860
[Amit Varma]: up through the system. What would their incentives be like? Like you begin playing sport, I'm

01:46:31.860 --> 01:46:35.940
[Amit Varma]: guessing where you are dreaming of a future when you're playing for India and you're playing

01:46:35.940 --> 01:46:41.060
[Amit Varma]: in the Olympics and all of that. And then at a certain point in time, you got to temper

01:46:41.060 --> 01:46:46.340
[Amit Varma]: it down and realize that all this is not going to happen. That the best I can hope for is

01:46:46.340 --> 01:46:51.820
[Amit Varma]: a job in services or railways and it's a steady job and that's kind of my life. Right? So

01:46:51.820 --> 01:46:57.360
[Amit Varma]: that kind of facing reality for a person like that can also sort of be pretty heartbreaking.

01:46:57.360 --> 01:47:03.540
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of that landscape. And you were in a sense, part of that landscape,

01:47:03.540 --> 01:47:09.800
[Amit Varma]: but not a prisoner of it because you had other things to do. But a lot of people were much

01:47:09.800 --> 01:47:14.060
[Guest]: more invested in it than you would have been. Yeah, you're right. In that sense, I must

01:47:14.060 --> 01:47:20.100
[Guest]: admit that we came from privileged backgrounds in that sense where we always knew that our

01:47:20.100 --> 01:47:28.460
[Guest]: paths will be fairly academic in whatever directions, science, art, commerce, whatever.

01:47:28.460 --> 01:47:35.940
[Guest]: But people who come from smaller towns, who are from the underprivileged backgrounds,

01:47:35.940 --> 01:47:41.740
[Guest]: they are normally mostly trying to get a job into railways and some of them make it. And

01:47:41.740 --> 01:47:45.700
[Guest]: I would say that's a good scenario for them because at the end of the day, it's a government

01:47:45.700 --> 01:47:54.100
[Guest]: job. If you talk about women per se, I do not know if they really enter with any ambition

01:47:54.100 --> 01:48:00.220
[Guest]: at all. I think it's just that these smaller towns in Maharashtra had a really good sporting

01:48:00.220 --> 01:48:05.740
[Guest]: culture. So we saw a lot of women come out and play volleyball, but at some point they

01:48:05.740 --> 01:48:13.580
[Guest]: got married and that's pretty much the end of it. And there are some that continued and

01:48:13.580 --> 01:48:20.460
[Guest]: they played far too many nationals, got into railways and continue to play the sport and

01:48:20.460 --> 01:48:26.940
[Guest]: do so now as well and played for the international team. But the truth of their life is also

01:48:26.940 --> 01:48:36.660
[Guest]: that they are in railways. And there's not really much above, much to say beyond that

01:48:36.660 --> 01:48:44.540
[Guest]: future, unless some people really desire it. And I do see a place for it, especially for

01:48:44.540 --> 01:48:51.860
[Guest]: people who are coming from smaller towns and those who want to desperately continue playing

01:48:51.860 --> 01:48:57.460
[Guest]: the sport. But at some point, realities of life take over. You want more money because

01:48:57.460 --> 01:49:03.380
[Guest]: now you have a family, you have children perhaps, and it's just not enough. And that's when

01:49:03.380 --> 01:49:08.820
[Guest]: people start dropping off. And I came from the same landscape and I do think that the

01:49:08.820 --> 01:49:15.540
[Guest]: landscape is changing. I would not say that for volleyball it's changed a lot because

01:49:15.540 --> 01:49:22.780
[Guest]: I think more than two or three women that were active during my time are now among the

01:49:22.780 --> 01:49:30.940
[Guest]: top 15 all-time great volleyball players, but we don't know their names unless you were

01:49:30.940 --> 01:49:37.580
[Guest]: following volleyball. So I would not think that they are getting anything out of it besides

01:49:37.580 --> 01:49:41.980
[Guest]: the fact that they're playing for railways and then for the international team. So I

01:49:41.980 --> 01:49:49.340
[Guest]: think in sports such as volleyball, we really need to make a lot more effort so that there

01:49:49.340 --> 01:49:57.100
[Guest]: is enough funding, enough privatization in a sense that allows sportsmen from these sports

01:49:57.100 --> 01:50:04.100
[Guest]: to start making money. And if you look at volleyball as a sport, take any cricket ground,

01:50:04.100 --> 01:50:09.620
[Guest]: a community ground or so, you'll always see a net there. I see a lot of potential for

01:50:09.620 --> 01:50:16.660
[Guest]: volleyball in terms of how exciting it can be for people to watch it. And so, yeah, I

01:50:16.660 --> 01:50:26.220
[Guest]: mean, when Joy said that he is pioneering the league, I was very, very happy because

01:50:26.220 --> 01:50:32.780
[Guest]: I do see that people will be interested in volleyball. I have seen the crowds in smaller

01:50:32.780 --> 01:50:38.540
[Guest]: universities really enjoy the games. And if that privatization happens for games like

01:50:38.540 --> 01:50:43.100
[Guest]: volleyball, we are still waiting for it. We are still quite stuck with cricket, I would

01:50:43.100 --> 01:50:51.220
[Guest]: say in that sense. And why even volleyball? I was among maybe the 10 people that bought

01:50:51.220 --> 01:50:58.420
[Guest]: tickets to the Hockey Premier League back in 2013, I guess 2012 or 2013 for the games

01:50:58.420 --> 01:51:08.780
[Guest]: that happened in Bangalore. And again, I was friends with some hardcore sports fans who

01:51:08.780 --> 01:51:14.220
[Guest]: worked with me. And we were all like, hey, you know what, we are going to buy our friends

01:51:14.220 --> 01:51:17.440
[Guest]: tickets if they don't want to come. We're just going to request them to give us two

01:51:17.440 --> 01:51:23.820
[Guest]: hours of their time. And we are going to ensure that we take at least 10 people and these

01:51:23.820 --> 01:51:30.300
[Guest]: players see at least 10 people in the stands. And we went for all the games and the tickets

01:51:30.300 --> 01:51:35.740
[Guest]: were merely 100 bucks or so. But that was not our idea. Even if the tickets were 500

01:51:35.740 --> 01:51:39.060
[Guest]: bucks, we would have still bought them and we would have ensured that we took a sizable

01:51:39.060 --> 01:51:45.700
[Guest]: crowd to watch the Hockey Premier League because we wanted to support these sports. And this

01:51:45.700 --> 01:51:51.620
[Guest]: is our national game. If we were not able to fill the stands for the national games,

01:51:51.620 --> 01:51:58.260
[Guest]: then what hope do we have, especially from a future for sportsmen point of view, not

01:51:58.260 --> 01:52:06.700
[Guest]: just viewership. So, yeah, I am not particularly bought into the whole idea of sports has a

01:52:06.700 --> 01:52:15.180
[Guest]: future even now. Unless, I would say for individual sports, if your parents are able to afford

01:52:15.180 --> 01:52:21.540
[Guest]: getting you a really good coach and a nutritionist, then I think individually you can still risk

01:52:21.540 --> 01:52:27.220
[Guest]: making sport your career. But otherwise, for team sports and especially non-cricket sports,

01:52:27.220 --> 01:52:32.060
[Guest]: I don't see the landscape very different. And I also think of this from the point of

01:52:32.060 --> 01:52:37.660
[Amit Varma]: view of incentives. You know, I'm glad you mentioned privatisation a few times because

01:52:37.660 --> 01:52:40.980
[Amit Varma]: that is the only way out because when the government runs sport, I mean, cricket is

01:52:40.980 --> 01:52:45.340
[Amit Varma]: practically the only sport which is not completely run by the government. And we've seen what's

01:52:45.340 --> 01:52:49.900
[Amit Varma]: happened there. And, you know, commerce kind of rescued the game in a sense, you know,

01:52:49.900 --> 01:52:54.740
[Amit Varma]: the IPL and all was, yes, done because of the desire to make money. But you make money

01:52:54.740 --> 01:52:58.580
[Amit Varma]: only by giving other people value. And those are great incentives. And that's exactly what

01:52:58.580 --> 01:53:03.260
[Amit Varma]: happened. And it therefore transformed the game. And, you know, Joy's, of course, been

01:53:03.260 --> 01:53:08.320
[Amit Varma]: on the show a couple of times and he's spoken about all the work he's done first when they

01:53:08.320 --> 01:53:12.860
[Amit Varma]: organised the U-17 Football World Cup a few years back and how hard they worked to try

01:53:12.860 --> 01:53:17.820
[Amit Varma]: to build an ecosystem of that. And then, of course, his Volleyball League. And it strikes

01:53:17.820 --> 01:53:23.180
[Amit Varma]: me that that's really what will determine which sports become popular and which don't

01:53:23.180 --> 01:53:28.760
[Amit Varma]: in the future. Because the incentive of the government, any government organisation will

01:53:28.760 --> 01:53:33.900
[Amit Varma]: always be just to do whatever little rent-seeking they can do, just keep things going. The incentive

01:53:33.900 --> 01:53:39.360
[Amit Varma]: is not to think ahead and invest and nurture people and nurture ecosystems. That simply

01:53:39.360 --> 01:53:45.440
[Amit Varma]: doesn't happen. That all fades away in the graveyard of good intentions. And that also

01:53:45.440 --> 01:53:51.340
[Amit Varma]: sort of makes me kind of think about, you know, which sports survive and which sports

01:53:51.340 --> 01:53:55.620
[Amit Varma]: don't. Like one of the reasons that Joy gave for, you know, why volleyball could be a good

01:53:55.620 --> 01:54:00.100
[Amit Varma]: TV sport is that the ball is big and people can follow the ball on TV. Whereas with table

01:54:00.100 --> 01:54:06.020
[Amit Varma]: tennis, you're just kind of seeing a sort of blur. So the one could, you know, argue

01:54:06.020 --> 01:54:09.380
[Amit Varma]: that then golf shouldn't work either. But that's a very big sport.

01:54:09.380 --> 01:54:13.620
[Guest]: But I would, sorry to interject there, but I think there's one more reason why a sport

01:54:13.620 --> 01:54:21.900
[Guest]: like volleyball would survive is because people see the nets around them. Every cricket ground,

01:54:21.900 --> 01:54:26.340
[Guest]: every community ground that you see, there are two poles and a net. It's not so difficult

01:54:26.340 --> 01:54:32.740
[Guest]: to find it. It's not expensive to get one ball among five or six or ten players if you

01:54:32.740 --> 01:54:39.100
[Guest]: can gather them. So accessibility to the equipment. And the other beauty of volleyball, like I

01:54:39.100 --> 01:54:45.540
[Guest]: was telling you earlier at lunches, you can be a volleyball enthusiast who just punches

01:54:45.540 --> 01:54:52.380
[Guest]: the ball and just lets it go to the other side of the net. Or you can really know the

01:54:52.380 --> 01:54:59.140
[Guest]: technicalities of the game and really be passionate about that. But the beauty is that everybody

01:54:59.140 --> 01:55:07.860
[Guest]: can really try playing the game and come across people in and around their communities playing

01:55:07.860 --> 01:55:15.660
[Guest]: it. So if this game is now on the TV as well and whoever feels like, hey, I want to get

01:55:15.660 --> 01:55:21.020
[Guest]: my hands on a volleyball, they actually can. But if you talk about, let's say, a game like

01:55:21.020 --> 01:55:27.380
[Guest]: tennis or even hockey for that matter, it's very difficult to suddenly say, hey, from

01:55:27.380 --> 01:55:31.620
[Guest]: tomorrow I want to play hockey. I don't know where I'm going to go and how I'm going to

01:55:31.620 --> 01:55:38.300
[Guest]: go and start. How am I am I going to gather people who can make any head or tail of how

01:55:38.300 --> 01:55:48.900
[Guest]: to hold a hockey bat and then just even for fun sakes have a game. Tennis for that matter.

01:55:48.900 --> 01:55:54.220
[Guest]: I think tennis is one of the sports. I've tried my hand at a number of sports. And tennis

01:55:54.220 --> 01:56:01.540
[Guest]: is one sport where I feel like unless you understand even the basic swing, you will

01:56:01.540 --> 01:56:09.380
[Guest]: not be able to get the ball on the other side of the net at all. You have to understand

01:56:09.380 --> 01:56:16.940
[Guest]: how that basic forehand swing happens to even be on the court. Otherwise, you'll be like

01:56:16.940 --> 01:56:23.260
[Guest]: I'm hitting balls in the net or just outside the court somewhere. So it's a very technical

01:56:23.260 --> 01:56:30.380
[Guest]: sport in that sense. But I think with volleyball, that's the beauty. That is the beauty. And

01:56:30.380 --> 01:56:36.900
[Guest]: I guess to some extent that is true for basketball as well. And so both of these sports have,

01:56:36.900 --> 01:56:41.540
[Guest]: I think, a good future. And we've always, even for basketball, we've always had really

01:56:41.540 --> 01:56:47.620
[Guest]: good players. My school team, for that matter, was amongst the best in Pune city for the

01:56:47.620 --> 01:56:54.580
[Guest]: men's basketball team that we had. And I've seen some phenomenal matches. And I'm somebody

01:56:54.580 --> 01:57:00.860
[Guest]: who's watched a lot of these sports that I talk about internationally as well. I've gone

01:57:00.860 --> 01:57:08.220
[Guest]: and watched the NBA in the US. I've watched people like Lionel Messi play live. I've watched

01:57:08.220 --> 01:57:14.140
[Guest]: Roger Federer play live. I've seen how these games are set up, what people are enjoying.

01:57:14.140 --> 01:57:21.940
[Guest]: And I would say that if India was able to pick up team sports more and really bring

01:57:21.940 --> 01:57:29.580
[Guest]: more glamour into it in some sense, then people would enjoy these sports as well and would

01:57:29.580 --> 01:57:37.780
[Guest]: pay for them. And I feel that the one thing that we should sort of not do, and I'm making

01:57:37.780 --> 01:57:44.180
[Guest]: this comment as a sportsman and not as somebody who's in the business of sport, in that desperation

01:57:44.180 --> 01:57:50.740
[Guest]: to make that sport known and popular, I don't think we should start bringing the sport to

01:57:50.740 --> 01:57:56.580
[Guest]: the public outside of the courts, you know, like just staging it in malls or anywhere

01:57:56.580 --> 01:58:04.520
[Guest]: else. And I feel like people would not genuinely build love for a sport when you are trying

01:58:04.520 --> 01:58:13.180
[Guest]: to sort of get them to like a sport desperately. So that is my personal opinion. But it is

01:58:13.180 --> 01:58:21.660
[Guest]: like any, you know, classical, passionate person for any subject who tries to have a

01:58:21.660 --> 01:58:24.660
[Guest]: negative opinion about anything anybody is doing. But yeah.

01:58:24.660 --> 01:58:29.620
[Amit Varma]: No, and I agree about the sort of the reasons volleyball could be so popular because I remember,

01:58:29.620 --> 01:58:33.580
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I was 11 or 12, I tried playing a game of tennis. I just tried once. I spent

01:58:33.580 --> 01:58:37.620
[Amit Varma]: 15 minutes. I could not get the ball across the net. You're absolutely right about that.

01:58:37.620 --> 01:58:40.520
[Amit Varma]: So then I said, forget it, you know, I'm not going to. Well, another of my friends was

01:58:40.520 --> 01:58:44.940
[Amit Varma]: watching a lot of tennis on TV, and he saw all the winners are not ones that go through

01:58:44.940 --> 01:58:49.580
[Amit Varma]: the middle, they go on the side. He was saying hit the side of the other court and all of

01:58:49.580 --> 01:58:54.740
[Unknown]: that. I was saying, boss, I can't get it over the net. But the little volleyball I have

01:58:54.740 --> 01:58:57.180
[Guest]: played, I have got it over the net. It is not a big deal.

01:58:57.180 --> 01:59:01.700
[Guest]: Exactly. And which is why it's a wonderful sport to promote because everybody will be

01:59:01.700 --> 01:59:06.540
[Guest]: able to get that instant gratification. Even if they don't know the rules, even if they

01:59:06.540 --> 01:59:10.780
[Guest]: don't know exactly how the ball is hit, even if they're making fouls, they'll at least

01:59:10.780 --> 01:59:16.260
[Guest]: get that instant gratification. And I guess badminton is famous for that particular reason.

01:59:16.260 --> 01:59:20.100
[Guest]: Because even if you've never touched a badminton racket today, I could take you to the court

01:59:20.100 --> 01:59:25.460
[Guest]: and in the next 10 minutes, you'll be like, of the 10 shuttles that I have hit, at least

01:59:25.460 --> 01:59:29.700
[Guest]: four or five went on the other side. So there is that instant gratification.

01:59:29.700 --> 01:59:35.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a fascinating way to think about sport. Like one thinks about sport in terms

01:59:35.060 --> 01:59:39.780
[Amit Varma]: of its qualities based on how we see elite sports people play it. But to think about

01:59:39.780 --> 01:59:44.500
[Amit Varma]: how the common person would take to it and the instant gratification, which I never really

01:59:44.500 --> 01:59:49.100
[Amit Varma]: thought about in this context. A final question before we go into the break, which is that

01:59:49.100 --> 01:59:53.900
[Amit Varma]: it also therefore strikes me that, you know, typically what has happened is that sport

01:59:53.900 --> 01:59:59.580
[Amit Varma]: has been a government thing, right? So sporting bodies that come up everywhere tend to be

01:59:59.580 --> 02:00:04.380
[Amit Varma]: either from the government or they tend to be monopsonies of a sort in the sense that

02:00:04.380 --> 02:00:09.380
[Amit Varma]: any sports person within a country then has really got to be on the good books of that

02:00:09.380 --> 02:00:13.500
[Amit Varma]: particular board or sporting body or whatever, and there's no choice and that bedeviled even

02:00:13.500 --> 02:00:18.820
[Amit Varma]: cricket for a long time. My sense is that a lot of sports don't have a market. They

02:00:18.820 --> 02:00:23.660
[Amit Varma]: would not exist if the government wasn't supporting them. And in some ways, they are artefacts.

02:00:23.660 --> 02:00:27.920
[Amit Varma]: Like when I think of, say, javelin throw or discuss throw or whatever, most people are

02:00:27.920 --> 02:00:32.700
[Amit Varma]: watching those sports once in four years in the Olympics, if at all, you know, they might

02:00:32.700 --> 02:00:37.180
[Amit Varma]: be even watching it in the background while the 100 meters is going on or somebody's flinging

02:00:37.180 --> 02:00:43.140
[Amit Varma]: a spear into the air. But that leads to the question of what should the government's role

02:00:43.140 --> 02:00:47.060
[Amit Varma]: in sport be? Because there are deeper issues here in the sense one issue, of course, is

02:00:47.060 --> 02:00:52.180
[Amit Varma]: the issue of whatever the government does has an opportunity cost. You know, every paisa

02:00:52.180 --> 02:00:57.660
[Amit Varma]: that the government has is acquired by coercion. So there's a moral cost there. And while you

02:00:57.660 --> 02:01:01.060
[Amit Varma]: accept that there are things that the state should do and things that the state should

02:01:01.060 --> 02:01:05.780
[Amit Varma]: not do, I would be one of those who would argue that the state should not fund sports,

02:01:05.780 --> 02:01:10.500
[Amit Varma]: especially in a poor country like India, where you have so many other problems. And you know,

02:01:10.500 --> 02:01:15.760
[Amit Varma]: you have scarce resources. So it almost in a lot of places, it feels like a nationalistic

02:01:15.760 --> 02:01:19.980
[Amit Varma]: vanity program, that we have to have the best team in this or the best team in that and

02:01:19.980 --> 02:01:24.180
[Amit Varma]: the government puts money into it and all of that. And also on the one hand, I have

02:01:24.180 --> 02:01:29.660
[Amit Varma]: like dual instincts. On the one hand, I'd love to see the market determining this, that

02:01:29.660 --> 02:01:35.020
[Amit Varma]: whichever sports get an audience, you know, that much money goes into them and they survive

02:01:35.020 --> 02:01:39.460
[Amit Varma]: and they thrive accordingly. And at the same time, entrepreneurs everywhere like Joy is

02:01:39.460 --> 02:01:45.620
[Amit Varma]: doing with the Volleyball League can, you know, use their creativity and skills at innovation

02:01:45.620 --> 02:01:50.100
[Amit Varma]: to bring sports in front of the public and create that demand if they feel that the sport

02:01:50.100 --> 02:01:54.820
[Amit Varma]: is inherently worth it. But if there's no market for watching javelin throwers apart

02:01:54.820 --> 02:02:01.480
[Amit Varma]: from once in four years, I'm like, okay with that, right? Sad as it is. That's one aspect.

02:02:01.480 --> 02:02:08.420
[Amit Varma]: But on a contrary note, I also feel that there is a romantic charm to having these artifacts

02:02:08.420 --> 02:02:12.580
[Amit Varma]: around, to having these sports. For example, I believe that Test cricket would not survive

02:02:12.580 --> 02:02:16.980
[Amit Varma]: today if not for the IPL. It's very sad and Test cricket is a great game. I am a cricket

02:02:16.980 --> 02:02:21.100
[Amit Varma]: tragic when it comes to Test cricket. But equally, I love the IPL and all of that. And

02:02:21.100 --> 02:02:25.580
[Amit Varma]: one of the reasons I love the IPL is that it's actually subsidizing the other forms

02:02:25.580 --> 02:02:30.500
[Amit Varma]: of the game and keeping them alive. So, whereas, you know, on the one hand, you could say that

02:02:30.500 --> 02:02:34.420
[Amit Varma]: just let the market dictate if no one wants to watch Test, that's what it is. But what

02:02:34.420 --> 02:02:38.980
[Amit Varma]: I actively recommend is that we keep subsidizing Test cricket for what it is. So, I'm kind

02:02:38.980 --> 02:02:45.180
[Amit Varma]: of torn between these two instincts at a purely rational level. I don't see that why a sport

02:02:45.180 --> 02:02:50.980
[Amit Varma]: which is watched by no one should be funded by the hard-earned money of taxpayers, you

02:02:50.980 --> 02:02:57.460
[Amit Varma]: know, which could be put to other good uses. But on the other hand, I do see sort of the

02:02:57.460 --> 02:03:02.700
[Amit Varma]: point that, you know, there is much richness there and variety there which we don't necessarily

02:03:02.700 --> 02:03:06.820
[Amit Varma]: want to lose. So, what are sort of your thoughts on this?

02:03:06.820 --> 02:03:12.500
[Guest]: So I agree with you. I can see why somebody would say that, hey, I'm not a Javelin fan

02:03:12.500 --> 02:03:19.100
[Guest]: and why is my money being used to fund this. But it's also, Amit, sort of a chicken and

02:03:19.100 --> 02:03:24.740
[Guest]: egg question whether we create the audience or whether the audience exists. And I guess

02:03:24.740 --> 02:03:31.660
[Guest]: the only sport where in India the answer is clear is for cricket. And so, for everything

02:03:31.660 --> 02:03:38.900
[Guest]: else, we need to create the audience. Because in that sense, if you think about it and if

02:03:38.900 --> 02:03:44.380
[Guest]: I'm being very cribby, then I'm going to say that we haven't even invested in other sports

02:03:44.380 --> 02:03:50.460
[Guest]: enough for people to decide if they like the sport or not. Do I not go for a basketball

02:03:50.460 --> 02:03:54.780
[Guest]: match because I don't like basketball or because I don't know about basketball? And then whose

02:03:54.780 --> 02:03:59.940
[Guest]: responsibility is it to make me aware about whether I like watching basketball or not

02:03:59.940 --> 02:04:06.860
[Guest]: or volleyball? So, in that sense, I definitely think it's the government's responsibility

02:04:06.860 --> 02:04:11.700
[Guest]: to bring these sports to us. And like I said to you, when we were playing state and national

02:04:11.700 --> 02:04:18.660
[Guest]: tournaments in smaller villages, we used to have big crowds. So, start there, come to

02:04:18.660 --> 02:04:27.220
[Guest]: the city, maybe slowly. These sports are definitely helping smaller cities and the youth in those

02:04:27.220 --> 02:04:33.940
[Guest]: cities find focus, find a certain ambition, watch with their own eyes people who they

02:04:33.940 --> 02:04:40.620
[Guest]: can idolize in that sense. I mean, watching a Neeraj Chopra on national TV is very different

02:04:40.620 --> 02:04:47.460
[Guest]: from watching somebody being cheered in front of your eyes and them winning a national medal

02:04:47.460 --> 02:04:52.740
[Guest]: or a state level medal. And for you to be able to go to them and say, hey, I really

02:04:52.740 --> 02:04:58.700
[Guest]: thought you were very good. And think about somebody from a smaller village looking at

02:04:58.700 --> 02:05:05.100
[Guest]: that, that person at that time is Neeraj Chopra for them. And so, we need to multiply those

02:05:05.100 --> 02:05:13.500
[Guest]: Neeraj Chopras in that sense. And when it comes to athletics that you specifically mentioned,

02:05:13.500 --> 02:05:21.500
[Guest]: a market has to be created for them as sports that are clubbed together, discus throw, javelin,

02:05:21.500 --> 02:05:27.360
[Guest]: all those sports, long jump, short jump. And to be honest, Commonwealth Games come every

02:05:27.360 --> 02:05:33.740
[Guest]: two years. And so, why should the government really do something else for you to go and

02:05:33.740 --> 02:05:40.940
[Guest]: watch that sport? I guess they are, in that sense, being supported when it comes to showcasing.

02:05:40.940 --> 02:05:47.380
[Guest]: I think Commonwealth Games do get enough attention from everybody. People go and watch it, buy

02:05:47.380 --> 02:05:52.740
[Guest]: tickets, talk about the wins at the Commonwealth Games, as well as they talk about our Olympic

02:05:52.740 --> 02:06:00.620
[Guest]: Games. So, I wouldn't say that we need to do something very different to platform these

02:06:00.620 --> 02:06:06.140
[Guest]: sports more. And the other thing is, if you really ask me about audiences and what they

02:06:06.140 --> 02:06:13.380
[Guest]: enjoy, I definitely think that you should start with team games. Because there's a lot

02:06:13.380 --> 02:06:20.760
[Guest]: more dynamics that's being displayed when a team game is being played versus sports

02:06:20.760 --> 02:06:26.900
[Guest]: like badminton and tennis, where what's going on in the sportsman's mind is really anybody's

02:06:26.900 --> 02:06:32.900
[Guest]: guess. But with team games, you will see drama, you will see the interaction with the coach,

02:06:32.900 --> 02:06:37.420
[Guest]: you will see the interaction between players, you will see the fights. With basketball,

02:06:37.420 --> 02:06:44.020
[Guest]: you're going to definitely see some random fouls and everything. So, if I purely look

02:06:44.020 --> 02:06:49.180
[Guest]: at it from a commercial point of view, all that can be done. I was super, super excited

02:06:49.180 --> 02:06:59.060
[Guest]: when the Superfight League was launched. Also in, I guess, 2016 was, 2017, January or February

02:06:59.060 --> 02:07:06.900
[Guest]: was the first time it was held. And it had, so it had MMA, all kinds of mixed martial

02:07:06.900 --> 02:07:15.980
[Guest]: arts. And you actually then saw a lot of the wrestlers, even women, who may or may not

02:07:15.980 --> 02:07:22.680
[Guest]: be doing as well as aiming for an Olympic medal, but who had the skills for a mixed

02:07:22.680 --> 02:07:28.100
[Guest]: martial arts. And then, you know, there was the stage of Superfight League again, available

02:07:28.100 --> 02:07:36.700
[Guest]: to them. And coincidentally, I think the Delhi Dawns, or I don't remember, Delhi Super Dawns

02:07:36.700 --> 02:07:41.900
[Guest]: or something, something like that was the name of the team that won. And the captain

02:07:41.900 --> 02:07:51.420
[Guest]: of that team, 2-3 days before he came to Delhi, was doing Muay Thai in Phuket with me. And

02:07:51.420 --> 02:07:57.500
[Guest]: he was, so of course, I was a beginner, he was in the advanced category. And somebody

02:07:57.500 --> 02:08:03.980
[Guest]: stopped by and said, hey, there's an Indian fighter here as well. He's training at Tiger,

02:08:03.980 --> 02:08:11.860
[Guest]: where I was training as well. And then I spoke to him and Jason Solomon, his name is. And

02:08:11.860 --> 02:08:17.100
[Guest]: he was like, yeah, yeah, I'm going now. And he was like, I have all these personal training

02:08:17.100 --> 02:08:22.220
[Guest]: tickets that I got because I'm sponsored, but now I cannot because I have been called

02:08:22.220 --> 02:08:25.900
[Guest]: to the Superfight League. And then he left me all his personal training tickets, and

02:08:25.900 --> 02:08:32.820
[Guest]: I did a lot of personal classes. But it was very interesting to watch the Superfight League.

02:08:32.820 --> 02:08:39.500
[Guest]: And I hear that it's going to happen again, or it happened, I think, one more year. And

02:08:39.500 --> 02:08:46.620
[Guest]: it attracted a lot of crowd. And I don't think I've seen a more technical game than MMA.

02:08:46.620 --> 02:08:51.540
[Guest]: You know, the little experience that I have had with Jiu Jitsu and Muay Thai and basics

02:08:51.540 --> 02:08:57.460
[Guest]: of wrestling, you find out things about the body that you did not know. Like you would

02:08:57.460 --> 02:09:04.860
[Guest]: not know what little movement I can do in your body that can choke you. You do not know

02:09:04.860 --> 02:09:11.780
[Guest]: how I can lock your body in a second. You learn so much about these things. And I'm

02:09:11.780 --> 02:09:18.660
[Guest]: happy to see that these attempts are being made. I want to see them happen more regularly.

02:09:18.660 --> 02:09:24.460
[Guest]: So I think we are moving in that direction. I see the intent. I'm sure that they have

02:09:24.460 --> 02:09:31.940
[Guest]: sponsors and people are trying to bring these sports to us. But it has to be much more consistent.

02:09:31.940 --> 02:09:36.300
[Guest]: And like I said to you, it has to begin with team sports.

02:09:36.300 --> 02:09:41.100
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, all wise thoughts. And I agree with you, except that I think I'd love to see civil

02:09:41.100 --> 02:09:46.380
[Amit Varma]: society and individuals and companies take the initiative to do all of this. I think

02:09:46.380 --> 02:09:50.820
[Amit Varma]: the government has pretty much broadly failed over the last few decades. But that is sort

02:09:50.820 --> 02:09:57.660
[Amit Varma]: of just kind of where I come from. And I said that was a final question, but I can't help

02:09:57.660 --> 02:10:02.860
[Amit Varma]: this follow up. Like I've gotten into different sports at different points in time. Me too.

02:10:02.860 --> 02:10:08.100
[Amit Varma]: Cycling is my latest drug. But me as a watcher, you as a doer. So there is a difference. Like

02:10:08.100 --> 02:10:11.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, Neil Simon once said in his play Barefoot in the Park, there are two kinds

02:10:11.060 --> 02:10:15.220
[Amit Varma]: of people in the world, watchers and the doers. And the watchers sit around watching the doers

02:10:15.220 --> 02:10:19.780
[Amit Varma]: do. So, you know, you're the doer, I'm the watcher. But among the sports I got into very

02:10:19.780 --> 02:10:24.340
[Amit Varma]: briefly was boxing. And this was around the time Lennox Lewis was at his peak. And, you

02:10:24.340 --> 02:10:28.700
[Amit Varma]: know, so and obviously, I entered that rabbit hole. And the guy was such a technical genius

02:10:28.700 --> 02:10:34.780
[Amit Varma]: and just a brilliant boxer. But then later, I began to just be repelled by boxing. It

02:10:34.780 --> 02:10:39.620
[Amit Varma]: seemed to me like a barbaric sport. Like I seriously think it shouldn't exist. Like what

02:10:39.620 --> 02:10:45.020
[Amit Varma]: fun can you get from watching people, you know, beat each other up in brutal ways. And

02:10:45.020 --> 02:10:49.740
[Amit Varma]: I'm sorry if I sound like a bit of a sissy. I mean, I wouldn't want to box myself. And

02:10:49.740 --> 02:10:53.860
[Amit Varma]: I get the technical aspects of it and all of that. But those are there in every sport,

02:10:53.860 --> 02:10:58.780
[Amit Varma]: right? And but that just seems to me like one sport that is both an artifact and something

02:10:58.780 --> 02:11:03.900
[Amit Varma]: that you know, so and I'm not saying ban it because why, you know, consenting adults as

02:11:03.900 --> 02:11:08.740
[Amit Varma]: a market for it, all of that is great. But my personal feeling is that I just feel repelled.

02:11:08.740 --> 02:11:13.420
[Amit Varma]: I feel that is where sport crosses the line from being healthy to something not so much.

02:11:13.420 --> 02:11:19.780
[Guest]: So what I know, it's it's really funny. I mean, I can I can completely see why you would

02:11:19.780 --> 02:11:28.860
[Guest]: think that. See, for me, I accidentally learned a bit of boxing because there was a point.

02:11:28.860 --> 02:11:34.380
[Guest]: I mean, it's a it's a long story. Do you want me to get into it? Okay, so so I had just

02:11:34.380 --> 02:11:42.140
[Guest]: I had just quit my eight year long stint with Shell in the later part of 2016. And I had

02:11:42.140 --> 02:11:48.340
[Guest]: this startup idea and I wanted to put my money into it and launch my startup and it was in

02:11:48.340 --> 02:11:54.260
[Guest]: the field of fitness. But you know, you go through a period after you worked with a company

02:11:54.260 --> 02:11:59.020
[Guest]: like Shell for eight years, you go, you quit and while you're quitting, you have all kinds

02:11:59.020 --> 02:12:06.860
[Guest]: of great feelings about how courageous you are to quit your dream job and all of that.

02:12:06.860 --> 02:12:13.060
[Guest]: But then reality strikes you for a few months after that and you have basically in all these

02:12:13.060 --> 02:12:20.700
[Guest]: years started defining your, you've associated your identity with the company you work for,

02:12:20.700 --> 02:12:26.060
[Guest]: which a lot of people fall victim to. And that happens with somebody who's worked with

02:12:26.060 --> 02:12:32.300
[Guest]: Google, with Facebook, whoever's the, I mean, whichever is the top company in your field.

02:12:32.300 --> 02:12:40.140
[Guest]: And I did not know where to sort of get rid of that anxiety that I've quit now, I must

02:12:40.140 --> 02:12:46.740
[Guest]: put money where my mouth is. And some of my friends from Dubai had been to these sports

02:12:46.740 --> 02:12:51.700
[Guest]: schools in Thailand and Thailand is very famous for its sports schools. And they had been

02:12:51.700 --> 02:12:57.900
[Guest]: there and I said, okay, I've never done a solo trip in my life. I'm going to find out

02:12:57.900 --> 02:13:03.340
[Guest]: about one of these sports schools. And I was already doing quite a lot of sport, but I

02:13:03.340 --> 02:13:10.620
[Guest]: said, okay, I'm going to go there. And I had never done any contact sport before this.

02:13:10.620 --> 02:13:14.140
[Guest]: And there were all these schools have a fitness element as well, fitness classes. And I was

02:13:14.140 --> 02:13:19.500
[Guest]: like, yeah, maybe those are the classes I will do. And then I already, I booked like

02:13:19.500 --> 02:13:25.980
[Guest]: a month of training in this school called Tiger Muay Thai, which is in Phuket. And it's

02:13:25.980 --> 02:13:33.620
[Guest]: one of the world's best school to train in mixed martial arts. So some of the topmost

02:13:33.620 --> 02:13:40.700
[Guest]: players currently are sponsored by Tiger Muay Thai. So the world's second best female champion

02:13:40.700 --> 02:13:47.780
[Guest]: right now, Valentina Shevchenko represents Tiger Muay Thai. A lot of other MMA current

02:13:47.780 --> 02:13:54.460
[Guest]: stars are sponsored by them. So I didn't know all of this. I just knew that the school was

02:13:54.460 --> 02:13:58.540
[Guest]: popular came up in my Google search. And I was like, okay, I'm going to risk it. And

02:13:58.540 --> 02:14:03.180
[Guest]: I'm going to do my first solo trip. And I had never been to Phuket before that. And

02:14:03.180 --> 02:14:11.020
[Guest]: I land in Phuket and it's it pretty much looks like Goa. And it's just these small lanes

02:14:11.020 --> 02:14:18.620
[Guest]: and you Tiger had put me up in in one of the little hotels near near it. And these are

02:14:18.620 --> 02:14:24.780
[Guest]: all really rooms because all you do is you are working out like dogs the entire day and

02:14:24.780 --> 02:14:31.860
[Guest]: coming back to shower and sleep. And I get into the room and I'm freaking out. And I

02:14:31.860 --> 02:14:39.020
[Guest]: was like, okay, I've noticed the school on my way to the hotel. And, and the entire street

02:14:39.020 --> 02:14:48.340
[Guest]: called, I forgot the name of the street, but so I tie it. That's what the street is called.

02:14:48.340 --> 02:14:55.100
[Guest]: It's about 800 meters and it has over 10 or 20 sports schools. And you go through that

02:14:55.100 --> 02:15:01.780
[Guest]: street to your hotel and all you're seeing is men and women with six packs and tattoos.

02:15:01.780 --> 02:15:09.580
[Guest]: And here you are. And you're like, okay, have I literally booked classes among these people?

02:15:09.580 --> 02:15:15.860
[Guest]: And so I'm freaking out. I get to my room. I go to the school. I say, okay, I've booked

02:15:15.860 --> 02:15:20.300
[Guest]: this package. And they're like, yeah, you can take as many fitness classes as you want

02:15:20.300 --> 02:15:28.020
[Guest]: and as many MMA classes as you want. So MMA had different classes, Muay Thai, Boxing,

02:15:28.020 --> 02:15:37.060
[Guest]: Jiu Jitsu, and it had Krabi Kabong and all those things. And I didn't know where to start.

02:15:37.060 --> 02:15:40.540
[Guest]: And I was like, okay, fine, I'm going to muster the courage and I'm going to just go for this

02:15:40.540 --> 02:15:45.940
[Guest]: boxing class. I have never done boxing. I go to the coach and before the class, I'm like,

02:15:45.940 --> 02:15:49.900
[Guest]: what do I need to buy? And then he tells me about the wraps and the gloves and the sizes

02:15:49.900 --> 02:15:56.540
[Guest]: and I get them. And I forget to ask him what's the level of this class. And it was a Friday

02:15:56.540 --> 02:16:01.660
[Guest]: and it was a sparring class. So that's when you actually fight. They don't teach you skills

02:16:01.660 --> 02:16:08.700
[Guest]: on that day. And there I am and the class starts and I get punched so badly. There's

02:16:08.700 --> 02:16:14.540
[Guest]: this Canadian girl who's already a boxer or whatever. I get punched really badly. But

02:16:14.540 --> 02:16:21.260
[Guest]: I finished the class and I'm in pain after the class. The next day I wake up and I'm

02:16:21.260 --> 02:16:27.620
[Guest]: like, I want to do this again. This time I'm like, I want to learn how to do this. This

02:16:27.620 --> 02:16:35.020
[Guest]: was interesting. So you were talking about whether you... So there's obviously a cult

02:16:35.020 --> 02:16:40.660
[Guest]: audience that follows these sports because maybe they are also trying it out on the side

02:16:40.660 --> 02:16:47.940
[Guest]: or understand the details of the sport. And then there is an element which purely enjoys

02:16:47.940 --> 02:16:55.020
[Guest]: people beating each other up. But if you ask me personally, I would end up following MMA

02:16:55.020 --> 02:17:00.380
[Guest]: and I ended up following it only after I had respect for the sport. And that is pretty

02:17:00.380 --> 02:17:04.260
[Guest]: much how I function, whether I'm talking to certain people or not, whether I'm watching

02:17:04.260 --> 02:17:09.820
[Guest]: something or not. For me, that's how I do it. That person or that sport or that thing

02:17:09.820 --> 02:17:16.540
[Guest]: that I'm doing has to win my respect for me to give my time to it. But so I can see why

02:17:16.540 --> 02:17:24.140
[Guest]: people feel all this adrenaline when they see these sports. But if you found boxing

02:17:24.140 --> 02:17:31.780
[Guest]: so violent in a way, then you would absolutely not like Muay Thai because Muay Thai was the

02:17:31.780 --> 02:17:39.020
[Guest]: old form of martial arts that... It's the national game of Thailand and it was used

02:17:39.020 --> 02:17:46.660
[Guest]: in war. So they were actually creating soldiers who basically used no guards, nothing. And

02:17:46.660 --> 02:17:52.220
[Guest]: with boxing and kickboxing, there's a lot of dunking and jumping around and all of that.

02:17:52.220 --> 02:17:59.060
[Guest]: But Muay Thai is very classical. It's like, I am here, punch me or I'm going to punch

02:17:59.060 --> 02:18:03.140
[Guest]: you. So you don't have any jumping around and dodging and everything. It's literally

02:18:03.140 --> 02:18:08.940
[Guest]: there and people are going to hit you and you're going to have to hit back. But then

02:18:08.940 --> 02:18:14.140
[Guest]: you develop respect for the skill that you're using and you trust the fact that the opponent

02:18:14.140 --> 02:18:19.580
[Guest]: is playing by rules. But having said that, it needs a lot of courage. I don't know if

02:18:19.580 --> 02:18:25.620
[Guest]: I'll ever get to a point where I'll even play a friendly match. Right now, I only do classes.

02:18:25.620 --> 02:18:31.220
[Guest]: But I think it's the endorphins that people really want to watch these games for. And

02:18:31.220 --> 02:18:37.300
[Guest]: imagining themselves, you know, kahi na kahi humare mann mein thoda sa wo hota hai, that

02:18:37.300 --> 02:18:43.820
[Guest]: sort of anger, pent up anger, whatever, that feeling of getting adrenaline. Some people

02:18:43.820 --> 02:18:48.580
[Guest]: will go and do skydiving, some people will do scuba diving, like that. Some people will

02:18:48.580 --> 02:18:56.020
[Guest]: be like, okay, I want to, you know, get to try this new sport that challenges me. And

02:18:56.020 --> 02:19:03.220
[Guest]: sometimes it may start by watching it and feeling like, okay, you know, this is interesting.

02:19:03.220 --> 02:19:10.020
[Guest]: So or how do these people do it? I would probably also watch boxing just to see how, like, okay,

02:19:10.020 --> 02:19:16.420
[Guest]: I want to see if this person gets punched so many times, how is he still standing? So

02:19:16.420 --> 02:19:21.260
[Guest]: yeah, I think it could be multiple reasons, I would say. But I can see, I think your question

02:19:21.260 --> 02:19:25.860
[Guest]: is very valid. I don't know why people would want to watch such violence in a sense.

02:19:25.860 --> 02:19:30.660
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, for me, it's really like for any sport I'm drawn to, it's an intellectual challenge

02:19:30.660 --> 02:19:36.540
[Amit Varma]: also figuring out what's happening inside someone's head, what are the strategic aspects,

02:19:36.540 --> 02:19:40.340
[Amit Varma]: what are the tactical aspects and all that. And recently, I watched this video, I think,

02:19:40.340 --> 02:19:45.140
[Amit Varma]: as usual on Twitter, somebody posted it of this ex British boxing champion, I forget

02:19:45.140 --> 02:19:49.340
[Amit Varma]: the name, if I find it, I'll link it in the show notes, this ex British boxing champion

02:19:49.340 --> 02:19:53.780
[Amit Varma]: who was working as a bouncer in a nightclub. So they had, I think, the CCTV or mobile phone

02:19:53.780 --> 02:19:58.940
[Amit Varma]: camera footage that he's outside and there's some other random guy who is arguing and behaving

02:19:58.940 --> 02:20:04.980
[Amit Varma]: obnoxiously and all of that. And this guy's fellow bouncers are trying to handle him.

02:20:04.980 --> 02:20:09.540
[Amit Varma]: But at one point, he just gets too obnoxious. So this guy goes and just gives him one punch

02:20:09.540 --> 02:20:13.660
[Amit Varma]: and he's out flat. Yeah. And I rewinded and watched that moment some 20 times because

02:20:13.660 --> 02:20:17.380
[Amit Varma]: it is such a thrilling moment. Like one, of course, it is good versus bad, the asshole

02:20:17.380 --> 02:20:23.380
[Amit Varma]: gets punched, right? But the other aspect, it is surely some kind of primal thing, you

02:20:23.380 --> 02:20:27.660
[Amit Varma]: know? Yes, it is. And as I'm rewinding and watching it, I'm also asking myself that why

02:20:27.660 --> 02:20:33.300
[Amit Varma]: do you find this moment so thrilling? As someone who has never punched anyone, right? I run

02:20:33.300 --> 02:20:38.420
[Amit Varma]: away from violence as fast as I can. But so why is it so thrilling that you're rewinding

02:20:38.420 --> 02:20:42.860
[Amit Varma]: and watching it? And it's a madly viral video. And it's that moment which is viral. You know,

02:20:42.860 --> 02:20:46.620
[Amit Varma]: there's a lot of calm, he's just standing there calmly, calmly, calmly, calmly, then

02:20:46.620 --> 02:20:52.540
[Guest]: suddenly walk up and whack. But you know, conversely, Amit, the funny thing is now because

02:20:52.540 --> 02:20:57.420
[Guest]: I have been to Tiger many times and spent a lot of time there and seen some world class

02:20:57.420 --> 02:21:05.620
[Guest]: fighters, a lot of them. The funny thing is, these fighters who you see in these fights

02:21:05.620 --> 02:21:13.380
[Guest]: really going at each other within the rules of the game, but really with power, with,

02:21:13.380 --> 02:21:18.820
[Guest]: you know, you are sometimes looking at the spot and thinking, oh my God, this is so violent.

02:21:18.820 --> 02:21:24.540
[Guest]: If you actually meet these people in person, you will notice that some of these people

02:21:24.540 --> 02:21:30.220
[Guest]: are the kindest and the most soft spoken people you'll meet. And sometimes you're not able

02:21:30.220 --> 02:21:34.900
[Guest]: to make that connection. You know, it's easier to make that connection with a Roger Federer,

02:21:34.900 --> 02:21:39.740
[Guest]: with a Rafael Nadal and all of that. But you look at these people and some of them are

02:21:39.740 --> 02:21:47.900
[Guest]: full of, you know, like tattoos all around and really aggressive entry to the arena and

02:21:47.900 --> 02:21:54.420
[Guest]: all of this. But if you meet them, otherwise, I have seen that some of them are the warmest,

02:21:54.420 --> 02:22:00.260
[Guest]: most kindest, accommodating people. I don't know if that happens because they just have

02:22:00.260 --> 02:22:09.260
[Guest]: a better understanding of their body and their mind and controlling it as well. I think controlling

02:22:09.260 --> 02:22:14.900
[Guest]: it and controlling yourself and staying within the rules when you're doing something as provocative

02:22:14.900 --> 02:22:22.000
[Guest]: as a contact sport, I think that takes a lot of character. I do feel so. And when I have

02:22:22.000 --> 02:22:27.220
[Guest]: also tried to do wrestling or something and you're doing all these exercises, and some

02:22:27.220 --> 02:22:35.580
[Guest]: of these exercises are ones where you're taught how to take someone down. Now, if I am walking

02:22:35.580 --> 02:22:42.660
[Guest]: or if I am in a match with you and you bring me down, all of that are times when I'm falling

02:22:42.660 --> 02:22:48.460
[Guest]: down when I don't know it. But when you're doing exercises and when you're learning and

02:22:48.460 --> 02:22:56.380
[Guest]: you know that, okay, Shruti, Amit stand like this, this is how this takedown is, I'm allowing

02:22:56.380 --> 02:23:01.820
[Guest]: you to take me down. And then when you get it right, when you get that technique right,

02:23:01.820 --> 02:23:07.460
[Guest]: even though I know you're going to make me fall down now, flat on my back, it happens

02:23:07.460 --> 02:23:13.020
[Guest]: in a second because you've got the technique right. And when you fall down, you feel the

02:23:13.020 --> 02:23:19.540
[Guest]: chills all the way from your spine to your brain. And to put yourself in those situations

02:23:19.540 --> 02:23:25.520
[Guest]: again and again and again and then learn how to do it. And then slowly your technique improves

02:23:25.520 --> 02:23:30.140
[Guest]: and then you realize, oh my God, if this technique is so powerful that I can take down somebody

02:23:30.140 --> 02:23:36.900
[Guest]: twice my height or size, because you understood in terms of the human body where those trigger

02:23:36.900 --> 02:23:45.420
[Guest]: points are, what you have to push or pull. And when you get that feeling that, hey, I

02:23:45.420 --> 02:23:51.740
[Guest]: have overcome this fear of falling down and feeling those chills, and then you show up

02:23:51.740 --> 02:23:56.980
[Guest]: for training the next day as well, you learn something about yourself. A, because you want

02:23:56.980 --> 02:24:03.700
[Guest]: to experience the thrill of it, you want to get, you want to feel the endorphins of being

02:24:03.700 --> 02:24:10.140
[Guest]: courageous once again. So that is that is that cycle in a way. So I can understand it

02:24:10.140 --> 02:24:14.760
[Guest]: from the point of view of players or people who've tried it, that they are big fans of

02:24:14.760 --> 02:24:19.100
[Guest]: the sport. And for everyone else, it's a spectacle.

02:24:19.100 --> 02:24:23.140
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. And I'll actually double click on that. But we'll do it after the break.

02:24:23.140 --> 02:24:28.060
[Amit Varma]: And then we'll, you know, get back to your personal trajectory, where I think we're still

02:24:28.060 --> 02:24:31.860
[Amit Varma]: early in the story. So that's after a quick break.

