[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Shruti Jagirdar about her fascinating

02:25:43.060 --> 02:25:47.980
[Amit Varma]: life and what the impact sport has had on her life and also later on in the show her

02:25:47.980 --> 02:25:53.420
[Amit Varma]: insights on nutrition, health, the human body, so on and so forth. I want to pick up from

02:25:53.420 --> 02:25:58.900
[Amit Varma]: the schools in Thailand where one of the points that you made was that, you know, many of

02:25:58.900 --> 02:26:05.020
[Amit Varma]: these MMA fighters, contrary to stereotype, they end up being really gentle people. And

02:26:05.020 --> 02:26:11.320
[Amit Varma]: there are two possible reasons for this. One would be that the distribution of gentleness

02:26:11.320 --> 02:26:15.620
[Amit Varma]: within MMA fighters is the same as in the general public. But you just notice it more

02:26:15.620 --> 02:26:18.580
[Amit Varma]: when you meet them because you don't expect them to be like that. And they are the ones

02:26:18.580 --> 02:26:25.420
[Amit Varma]: you remember. But the other one is that the sport, the nature of the sport, genuinely

02:26:25.420 --> 02:26:30.640
[Amit Varma]: changes people, maybe by making them more aware of their power, maybe by making them

02:26:30.640 --> 02:26:36.540
[Amit Varma]: just changing them in different fundamental ways. So before we continue sort of with your

02:26:36.540 --> 02:26:43.540
[Amit Varma]: Thailand experience, that's sort of a question that I also want to get into, that earlier

02:26:43.540 --> 02:26:50.060
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about the different ways in which sport changed you as a person. But more specifically,

02:26:50.060 --> 02:26:55.900
[Amit Varma]: you know, what did sport teach you, for example, about your own body? What did it teach you

02:26:55.900 --> 02:27:01.020
[Amit Varma]: about the limits of what you can do and what you cannot do? And in what ways did it shape

02:27:01.020 --> 02:27:09.860
[Guest]: your attitude towards other people? That's a very good question, Amit, because

02:27:09.860 --> 02:27:16.200
[Guest]: I don't think I learned so much about my body when I was a volleyball player. But because

02:27:16.200 --> 02:27:22.980
[Guest]: I enjoy sport and because I enjoy putting myself in challenging situations, I have,

02:27:22.980 --> 02:27:28.820
[Guest]: like I said, tried my hand at a lot of sport and I continue to do it. And part of that

02:27:28.820 --> 02:27:37.260
[Guest]: exploration happened because as I went into engineering and into corporate, it was very

02:27:37.260 --> 02:27:42.260
[Guest]: difficult to find women volleyball players. And everywhere I have gone, I have played

02:27:42.260 --> 02:27:48.580
[Guest]: a little bit of volleyball, etc. But you couldn't find continuity. So you start exploring other

02:27:48.580 --> 02:27:57.860
[Guest]: sports. And the things that I have learned about my body is really, first of all, putting

02:27:57.860 --> 02:28:03.940
[Guest]: yourself out there and testing yourself against something. Instead of imagining you'll not

02:28:03.940 --> 02:28:10.360
[Guest]: be able to do it. And not letting others tell you what you can do and what you cannot do.

02:28:10.360 --> 02:28:17.820
[Guest]: Because you know, this thing happened with me back in 2009 or 10. I had just joined Shell

02:28:17.820 --> 02:28:27.000
[Guest]: and there's a lot of beautiful treks around Bangalore and in Karnataka. And my company

02:28:27.000 --> 02:28:35.080
[Guest]: had a bunch of very, very interested folk who formed a group and who would go trekking

02:28:35.080 --> 02:28:41.900
[Guest]: every two months. And I've ended up trekking a lot around Bangalore and some of the most

02:28:41.900 --> 02:28:49.020
[Guest]: challenging treks around Bangalore I've done with them. And at one point, there was a trek

02:28:49.020 --> 02:28:55.000
[Guest]: that was organized to Brahmagiri. And Brahmagiri is this trek that normally people would end

02:28:55.000 --> 02:29:03.540
[Guest]: up doing over two days. And a group of our batchmates from Shell, they all went for this

02:29:03.540 --> 02:29:11.180
[Guest]: trek. And the way this trek is, is you climb a mountain, which takes you about six, seven

02:29:11.180 --> 02:29:17.420
[Guest]: hours, eight hours or so. And then there is five kilometers of grassland before you reach

02:29:17.420 --> 02:29:26.060
[Guest]: the peak itself. And the grasslands have short, dense forests in the middle. They're called

02:29:26.060 --> 02:29:34.640
[Guest]: Sholas. And that's where you have wild cats and you have elephants and other things. So

02:29:34.640 --> 02:29:40.760
[Guest]: you have to scale those grasslands and then you come to the peak, which is about 700 meters

02:29:40.760 --> 02:29:48.840
[Guest]: or so, but which has a 70 degree incline. So this group of our colleagues who went and

02:29:48.840 --> 02:29:56.320
[Guest]: they could not get to, they all got to the peak, but the group was found it so difficult

02:29:56.320 --> 02:30:02.720
[Guest]: that half of them just couldn't climb the peak. And some people who were helping others

02:30:02.720 --> 02:30:07.880
[Guest]: were not able to scale the peak and then they had to come back or so. And then four, five

02:30:07.880 --> 02:30:13.880
[Guest]: of them said that, we want to do this again because we didn't complete the trek. And this

02:30:13.880 --> 02:30:17.880
[Guest]: was around the time when one of them asked me, oh, do you want to go to this trek? I

02:30:17.880 --> 02:30:23.920
[Guest]: hadn't been to the first expedition. And they were like, no, no, we want to do Brahmagiri

02:30:23.920 --> 02:30:30.920
[Guest]: in one day. And I had not done, I had done trekking around Pune as well and some challenging

02:30:30.920 --> 02:30:35.960
[Guest]: treks, but many years before that. And I was like, okay, fine, let's do it. And then I

02:30:35.960 --> 02:30:44.600
[Guest]: go and I, then the five of us get to the top of the peak by four in the evening. And we

02:30:44.600 --> 02:30:49.920
[Guest]: had started climbing at around six or seven in the morning. And then what happens is,

02:30:49.920 --> 02:30:54.720
[Guest]: so there's a funny story there as well. We get there at four o'clock and it was a very

02:30:54.720 --> 02:31:01.440
[Guest]: difficult trek. The whole point of the trek was that once you scale the peak, you come

02:31:01.440 --> 02:31:08.240
[Guest]: back to the guest house that the forest, the whatever the forest officers have set up for

02:31:08.240 --> 02:31:14.800
[Guest]: trekkers and all that. And so at four, there's dusk in the, up in the hills and in the mountains

02:31:14.800 --> 02:31:19.600
[Guest]: and it starts getting dark. And we were so tired, we were still up the peak. And then

02:31:19.600 --> 02:31:24.400
[Guest]: there's a guide who takes you because there are wild cats in the area. And he, our guide

02:31:24.400 --> 02:31:31.040
[Guest]: was like, okay, we have to hurry up. And once the light starts dwindling, then everything

02:31:31.040 --> 02:31:36.920
[Guest]: that's moving seems to feel like it's coming at you. And we come down the peak and there's

02:31:36.920 --> 02:31:45.960
[Guest]: a group of elephants and they start moving. And, you know, it's so different to see elephants

02:31:45.960 --> 02:31:50.760
[Guest]: in the wild compared to just thinking of them as domesticated animals or animals that we

02:31:50.760 --> 02:31:56.720
[Guest]: sort of understand. And this guide is like, we have to start running because we have to

02:31:56.720 --> 02:32:01.320
[Guest]: at least cross these five kilometers of the grasslands of the forest. And then we enter

02:32:01.320 --> 02:32:06.360
[Guest]: the forest and we're smelling the water, near the water, we're smelling the wild cats. And

02:32:06.360 --> 02:32:11.720
[Guest]: I have never focused on running as much as I have behind that guide because it was so

02:32:11.720 --> 02:32:16.840
[Guest]: dark and we were so sure there are wild cats behind us. But so anyway, that was a side

02:32:16.840 --> 02:32:21.320
[Guest]: story. We did that trek, we were very happy that we did it in a day and not a lot of people

02:32:21.320 --> 02:32:28.960
[Guest]: do it. And then in my office, there were some people who were forming a team for the first

02:32:28.960 --> 02:32:35.400
[Guest]: urban stampede, which was a relay race where four people are in a team and each team member

02:32:35.400 --> 02:32:41.240
[Guest]: runs five kilometers. And the condition is that there should be one girl in the team.

02:32:41.240 --> 02:32:46.880
[Guest]: Now I work for a petroleum engineering company, which means there are fewer girls in general.

02:32:46.880 --> 02:32:54.120
[Guest]: And so everybody is trying to hunt for a team member and a girl to join the team. And there's

02:32:54.120 --> 02:33:00.960
[Guest]: this one guy who was on the trek with me and his friend in the company, who's now my best

02:33:00.960 --> 02:33:08.520
[Guest]: friend, was looking for a girl to join. And then this person, Nidhan, who was on the trek

02:33:08.520 --> 02:33:15.200
[Guest]: with me, tells Amit, my friend's name is Amit, that Shruti will run five kilometers, you

02:33:15.200 --> 02:33:20.960
[Guest]: ask her. And at that time, I was a little bit bigger. So my friend Amit, he's from Haryana

02:33:20.960 --> 02:33:28.160
[Guest]: and he's like big into sports. And he tells me much later, he's like, I came around your

02:33:28.160 --> 02:33:31.840
[Guest]: desk just to see who she is, because I was a new recruit and they were senior to me,

02:33:31.840 --> 02:33:38.960
[Guest]: so they hadn't met me before. And then he went back to Nidhan and he said, ye toh nahi

02:33:38.960 --> 02:33:45.600
[Guest]: hai. So and then later he told me that Nidhan told him that agar koi 5 kilometer bhaagega

02:33:45.600 --> 02:33:50.560
[Guest]: toh yeh ladki bhaagegi. And I had never done a 5 kilometer. I was not, I was a sportsman,

02:33:50.560 --> 02:33:56.120
[Guest]: but I was not an athlete in that sense, not a runner or whatever. So Amit then approached

02:33:56.120 --> 02:34:01.040
[Guest]: me and he was like, we are forming this team, do you want to do a 5K? And I was like, okay,

02:34:01.040 --> 02:34:05.760
[Guest]: fine. And then he said, okay, next tomorrow we are meeting 5 kilometer, tomorrow we are

02:34:05.760 --> 02:34:12.320
[Guest]: meeting at 5am and running 5 kilometers and I want to see how you do. And he's going to

02:34:12.320 --> 02:34:17.680
[Guest]: be jogging with me and all that. And then he's like the first day itself, when we did

02:34:17.680 --> 02:34:24.640
[Guest]: that 5 kilometer, you did not stop at all. You didn't walk for a minute and you had never

02:34:24.640 --> 02:34:30.920
[Guest]: run 5 kilometers in your life. And that day I just knew I was like, okay, this is the

02:34:30.920 --> 02:34:36.000
[Guest]: girl who's going to be in my team. And then I did much better when I practiced and finally

02:34:36.000 --> 02:34:43.360
[Guest]: I did it. But that first 5 kilometers was me testing myself, that I am not an athlete.

02:34:43.360 --> 02:34:48.880
[Guest]: Can I run a 5 kilometer or not without walking? So again, this was the first time I was doing

02:34:48.880 --> 02:34:54.800
[Guest]: a 5 kilometer, but I didn't in my mind allow myself to say ki main chal lungi beech mein.

02:34:54.800 --> 02:34:59.760
[Guest]: And I've seen this a lot with people. If you really can't, your body will tell you that

02:34:59.760 --> 02:35:03.760
[Guest]: you have to walk. Why do you have to start running by thinking ki mujhse nahi hoga toh

02:35:03.760 --> 02:35:09.680
[Guest]: mein chal lungi. So in my mind, that was the thing, that I'm not going to walk no matter

02:35:09.680 --> 02:35:14.880
[Guest]: what. And I didn't. So this is how I first noticed that, okay, now I can run. And from

02:35:14.880 --> 02:35:19.120
[Guest]: then on, I have improved. Every time I'm running 5 kilometers, I'm trying to do something

02:35:19.120 --> 02:35:24.800
[Guest]: different. I'm trying to run differently. And there are many, every time you run, you

02:35:24.800 --> 02:35:30.160
[Guest]: get, you have a new experience. You discover something new about yourself. The second time

02:35:30.160 --> 02:35:36.800
[Guest]: I really pushed myself and I noticed something about myself was when I was in Dubai. Like

02:35:36.800 --> 02:35:41.640
[Guest]: I was just telling you, I spent a couple of years in Dubai. And conversely, I mean, when

02:35:41.640 --> 02:35:46.280
[Guest]: you think of Dubai or the Gulf in general, everybody is like bohot Indians hai waha pe.

02:35:46.280 --> 02:35:51.200
[Guest]: And you see a lot of Indians everywhere. They're almost like citizens there, even though we

02:35:51.200 --> 02:36:00.080
[Guest]: never get citizenship, but they're everywhere. And then I was in Dubai and I registered with

02:36:00.080 --> 02:36:06.000
[Guest]: my team, with a team of my colleagues who were ex-New Zealand military. They were also

02:36:06.000 --> 02:36:11.040
[Guest]: in Shell and they wanted to form a seven member team to participate in the Desert Warrior

02:36:11.040 --> 02:36:17.520
[Guest]: back in 2015. And they used to, so Desert Warrior is 10 kilometer run in the October

02:36:17.520 --> 02:36:24.640
[Guest]: heat in Dubai, in the sand with 22 obstacles. And that sort of test you. There can be slides,

02:36:24.640 --> 02:36:32.080
[Guest]: there can be jumping over walls, there can be, you can imagine that. And I was like,

02:36:32.080 --> 02:36:37.120
[Guest]: okay, fine. I was already doing fitness, but nothing at the level that they were doing.

02:36:37.120 --> 02:36:45.360
[Guest]: And they were, these military guys were setting our workouts. So we would end up doing a lot

02:36:45.360 --> 02:36:54.000
[Guest]: of really challenging workouts. And then during one workout, in 40 minutes, I had to climb

02:36:54.000 --> 02:37:05.600
[Guest]: 92 floors of nine flights of stairs and swim about 75 meters or so, 100 pushups and a two

02:37:05.600 --> 02:37:12.000
[Guest]: kilometer run or so. We were doing that in rounds. So we were, the gym of the building

02:37:12.000 --> 02:37:18.640
[Guest]: was on the 30th floor. So we had to go down, climb 30 floors and whatever. And the idea

02:37:18.640 --> 02:37:25.600
[Guest]: was that in 40 minutes, this is how much you can do the max. And you have to finish it.

02:37:25.600 --> 02:37:29.120
[Guest]: And otherwise, we are going to stop the clock anyways, like nobody's putting pressure on

02:37:29.120 --> 02:37:33.280
[Guest]: you if you didn't finish all the rounds or whatever, but this is the max you could do.

02:37:33.280 --> 02:37:39.960
[Guest]: And I ended up finishing it. You did 90 floors. 92 floors. Yeah. And I still, it shows up

02:37:39.960 --> 02:37:45.120
[Guest]: on my Facebook memories sometimes and I'm like, Oh my God, how did we end up doing this?

02:37:45.120 --> 02:37:51.520
[Guest]: But so, so that's another time when I realized that both willpower and, and your ability

02:37:51.520 --> 02:37:59.040
[Guest]: to do sport coming together, you can still do a lot of things. And then on the day of

02:37:59.040 --> 02:38:06.680
[Guest]: the Desert Warrior, right? It was the first time in Dubai where I went to the spot where

02:38:06.680 --> 02:38:16.360
[Guest]: the race was starting. No Indian, no Indian and no Pakistani. In Dubai, you will see everywhere,

02:38:16.360 --> 02:38:21.760
[Guest]: but in this race, you won't see anywhere. The same with Thailand. I've been to Thailand

02:38:21.760 --> 02:38:26.280
[Guest]: many, many times. And we, every time I'm in Thailand, we work out like four or five hours

02:38:26.280 --> 02:38:32.400
[Guest]: a day. And then the day gets over pretty early. You don't see a lot of fighters and everybody,

02:38:32.400 --> 02:38:36.040
[Guest]: you know, just drinking away the night or whatever. Maybe on a Saturday night, because

02:38:36.040 --> 02:38:43.000
[Guest]: Sunday the school is off. But on the days, everybody's fairly disciplined and no Indian

02:38:43.000 --> 02:38:47.560
[Guest]: again. Like I have, I've been there many times and you see one or two Indians, it's becoming

02:38:47.560 --> 02:38:53.360
[Guest]: more popular to go there now. And sometimes I've heard some South Indian actors and stuff

02:38:53.360 --> 02:38:58.960
[Guest]: go there, but otherwise I've hardly met. Poore Thailand mein itne Indians ja rahe hote hain,

02:38:58.960 --> 02:39:05.280
[Guest]: but in the sports schools, you'll never see anybody. So during Desert Warrior is when,

02:39:05.280 --> 02:39:10.800
[Guest]: when those military workouts that were set were sort of made me realize that, okay, I

02:39:10.800 --> 02:39:17.920
[Guest]: can push myself in these directions as well. And what you learn every time is how much

02:39:17.920 --> 02:39:24.120
[Guest]: you are able to push yourself. That learning was okay for me. Like I knew that I can push

02:39:24.120 --> 02:39:30.760
[Guest]: myself and I'm able to sort of really, maybe I don't want to fail in a sense. So you, you

02:39:30.760 --> 02:39:37.240
[Guest]: set those goals, all that was great. But when I went to Thailand is where I really, really

02:39:37.240 --> 02:39:43.840
[Guest]: realized that you, first of all, you are in a company of hardcore sportsmen, a lot of

02:39:43.840 --> 02:39:50.800
[Guest]: people from Germany, Canada, and a lot of them are fighters. And even the ones who have

02:39:50.800 --> 02:39:55.480
[Guest]: a different career or whatever, have actually been fighting for a very long time, even if

02:39:55.480 --> 02:40:01.600
[Guest]: they don't have fighting as their career. And you're literally like a tiny person there,

02:40:01.600 --> 02:40:07.720
[Guest]: amid all these people that are like super fit. And you're not really unfit, but you're

02:40:07.720 --> 02:40:13.640
[Guest]: looking at them, you're underestimating yourself. And then you start going to the classes and

02:40:13.640 --> 02:40:18.720
[Guest]: you're like, yeah, whatever happens, I'm going to show up. And then you start realizing that

02:40:18.720 --> 02:40:23.600
[Guest]: you're able to keep up with, with even, even if the level of the workouts is very high.

02:40:23.600 --> 02:40:29.440
[Guest]: There are some things you can't do, but then there are a lot of things you can do. And

02:40:29.440 --> 02:40:35.320
[Guest]: like I said, when it came to trying and learning even a little bit of the Jiu Jitsu or the

02:40:35.320 --> 02:40:42.000
[Guest]: wrestling and Muay Thai that I have done, for me was not about me now picking this sport

02:40:42.000 --> 02:40:48.720
[Guest]: up or something, it was about me constantly being courageous. Because you are bruised,

02:40:48.720 --> 02:40:53.840
[Guest]: you are tired, you have, you're working out five or six hours a day, you are hoping that

02:40:53.840 --> 02:41:00.560
[Guest]: your body is recovering. And those, those are the things that teach you something more

02:41:00.560 --> 02:41:05.320
[Guest]: about yourself. And like I said, it made me more aware of our body in general, human body

02:41:05.320 --> 02:41:14.640
[Guest]: in general. And the most important thing was also that it was the first time that in Thailand

02:41:14.640 --> 02:41:21.680
[Guest]: that I saw women really push themselves. I had been doing sport, I had seen fit women.

02:41:21.680 --> 02:41:25.960
[Guest]: And yes, of course, the women in the Olympics in India, and I'm not saying that Indian women

02:41:25.960 --> 02:41:31.800
[Guest]: weren't really pushing boundaries. But back in 2016, gymming and all that really women

02:41:31.800 --> 02:41:38.880
[Guest]: pushing themselves on, and you seeing them in gyms around you, all that was not as common.

02:41:38.880 --> 02:41:45.120
[Guest]: And I go there, and I'm in like this group class, and there are women lifting 100 kilos

02:41:45.120 --> 02:41:51.280
[Guest]: deadlifts. And I have, by then I had not even studied fitness sciences. So and I wasn't

02:41:51.280 --> 02:41:56.040
[Guest]: into weightlifting. And I'm just looking at this with these women and I'm like, ladkiya

02:41:56.040 --> 02:42:01.920
[Guest]: yeh kar sakti hai. And this is me who's been in sports being completely taken aback by

02:42:01.920 --> 02:42:08.960
[Guest]: how how easily women were loading 100 kilos on the deadlift. And, you know, after that

02:42:08.960 --> 02:42:15.480
[Guest]: one month in 2016, I was like, Oh, my God, I have just not tested myself enough. And

02:42:15.480 --> 02:42:21.840
[Guest]: we've been to, I mean, in India, the only weights that I had seen was doing some dumbbells

02:42:21.840 --> 02:42:28.600
[Guest]: before that. And then I think after I came back, I have every single time I have been

02:42:28.600 --> 02:42:32.920
[Guest]: in the gym, I have really tried to push myself. Like I was telling you earlier on, I was like,

02:42:32.920 --> 02:42:39.400
[Guest]: man, what do I need to eat so that I can lift 100 kilos. And I like in Thailand, I saw women

02:42:39.400 --> 02:42:45.880
[Guest]: that lifted like 190 kilo deadlift. I haven't seen guys doing that. And I had just not seen

02:42:45.880 --> 02:42:52.040
[Guest]: such strong women forget. I mean, they had six packs or not all that is different. I

02:42:52.040 --> 02:42:56.600
[Guest]: had just not seen that kind of strength. I had not seen Indian women with that kind of

02:42:56.600 --> 02:43:02.200
[Guest]: strength, at least with my personal. Personally, I had not seen it. You can see a Malleshwari

02:43:02.200 --> 02:43:07.800
[Guest]: or you can see, you know, you can find out about the weightlifters or whatever in India,

02:43:07.800 --> 02:43:13.080
[Guest]: but I had not with my own eyes seen it and it had such an impact with me. I was like,

02:43:13.080 --> 02:43:19.640
[Guest]: Oh, my God, you've been holding yourself back for so long, and really not pushing your limits.

02:43:19.640 --> 02:43:28.680
[Guest]: And so that fear of, you know, that women show in the gyms in India as well. No, no,

02:43:28.680 --> 02:43:33.480
[Guest]: I will, you know, this is a deadlift, I will just try 40 kilos, I will just try 30 kilos.

02:43:33.480 --> 02:43:39.000
[Guest]: And that's what I keep telling people who at least ask me about how they should improve.

02:43:39.000 --> 02:43:45.440
[Guest]: I will tell them that, hey, just work on your technique so that you don't get injured. But

02:43:45.440 --> 02:43:55.440
[Guest]: do not hold back from lifting more weights. And the high of just allowing yourself to

02:43:55.440 --> 02:44:01.520
[Guest]: test your limits transcends into your work, transcends into what else you do outside of

02:44:01.520 --> 02:44:08.680
[Guest]: the gym, because it builds your courage, your risk taking ability, your, in case of women

02:44:08.680 --> 02:44:14.440
[Guest]: to some extent, the aggression that they need to assert themselves even outside of, I mean

02:44:14.440 --> 02:44:19.840
[Guest]: even at work and outside of the gym. I think all that you use, you know, you learn doing

02:44:19.840 --> 02:44:24.800
[Guest]: all of that. If you purely speak about learning from sport, I mean, I don't mean that these

02:44:24.800 --> 02:44:30.920
[Guest]: qualities can't be learned outside of sports. But because we are talking about my experiences,

02:44:30.920 --> 02:44:37.960
[Guest]: these are the things I learned. And I am quite grateful that I'm so greedy for experiences.

02:44:37.960 --> 02:44:43.400
[Guest]: Most of, to be honest, Amit, most of the money that I have earned, I've spent in traveling

02:44:43.400 --> 02:44:51.540
[Guest]: and gaining experiences because they stay with you. And like I said, when you're thinking

02:44:51.540 --> 02:44:59.280
[Guest]: about how can I succeed or when you're not doing your best, there's just this whole bag

02:44:59.280 --> 02:45:04.200
[Guest]: of experiences you have and it doesn't even take you a minute to find something that's

02:45:04.200 --> 02:45:11.560
[Guest]: relevant to that situation. And so I completely believe in building experiences, just go out

02:45:11.560 --> 02:45:23.000
[Guest]: there. Even going to Thailand as my first solo trip by itself was a courageous decision

02:45:23.000 --> 02:45:27.640
[Guest]: because it wasn't like four day of Bangkok or something like that. It was booking 30

02:45:27.640 --> 02:45:35.920
[Guest]: days. It was booking a hardcore fitness school. It was booking alone and just hoping that

02:45:35.920 --> 02:45:43.640
[Guest]: you end up meeting people and the kind of people I met, oh my God, I would do that over

02:45:43.640 --> 02:45:49.800
[Guest]: and over and again, no matter what country I have to go to get those kinds of experiences.

02:45:49.800 --> 02:45:54.800
[Amit Varma]: And the fantastic lesson here is not just a sporting one, that lesson applies to everything,

02:45:54.800 --> 02:45:58.580
[Amit Varma]: which is that don't make assumptions about what your limits are. Just keep kind of testing

02:45:58.580 --> 02:46:04.060
[Amit Varma]: them and going outside your comfort zone. I have a running story. It's a slightly embarrassing

02:46:04.060 --> 02:46:09.400
[Amit Varma]: running story, but I'll share it nevertheless. Now, around three years back, I was 25 kgs

02:46:09.400 --> 02:46:13.760
[Amit Varma]: lighter. I was on keto plus intermittent fasting, like I told you, in which you're an expert

02:46:13.760 --> 02:46:18.560
[Amit Varma]: in and we'll come to that later as well, your learnings on nutrition. And I was running.

02:46:18.560 --> 02:46:22.600
[Amit Varma]: So I was running to a point where I would get up every day in the morning at 5.30, go

02:46:22.600 --> 02:46:28.980
[Amit Varma]: out and run for an hour. I ran a 10k, have a photo of me biting my medal. Happy times.

02:46:28.980 --> 02:46:34.600
[Amit Varma]: And one day I was in Bangalore for a bunch of recordings. And my good friend, Mohit Satyanand,

02:46:34.600 --> 02:46:41.440
[Amit Varma]: who's been a guest on the show also happened to be there. And Mohit just turned 66 recently.

02:46:41.440 --> 02:46:46.600
[Amit Varma]: And he, I think around the time he was 60, got into fitness and he's run triathlons and

02:46:46.600 --> 02:46:50.920
[Guest]: all that. So he... Bangalore has a huge community of triathlons

02:46:50.920 --> 02:46:53.920
[Amit Varma]: and runners. He's actually based in Delhi, but he happened

02:46:53.920 --> 02:46:59.000
[Amit Varma]: to be in Bangalore at that time. But he got hardcore into that, ran triathlons. I think

02:46:59.000 --> 02:47:03.800
[Amit Varma]: he spent some time in Greece because he was doing a specialist course in swimming, swimming

02:47:03.800 --> 02:47:08.360
[Amit Varma]: techniques and all of that. So really hardcore. So I was chatting on the phone with him one

02:47:08.360 --> 02:47:12.360
[Amit Varma]: evening and I was there for recordings. He was there for something else. And he said,

02:47:12.360 --> 02:47:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Amit, I hear you're really into running. Let's go running tomorrow. So I said, okay, let's

02:47:16.000 --> 02:47:21.280
[Amit Varma]: go running tomorrow. So he said, okay, 5.30, Kaban Park or whatever the time was.

02:47:21.280 --> 02:47:24.720
[Amit Varma]: It's a beautiful park. It's an amazing park. Bombay people should

02:47:24.720 --> 02:47:29.000
[Amit Varma]: be incredibly jealous. But anyway, so I did a 10K in Kaban as well.

02:47:29.000 --> 02:47:34.120
[Amit Varma]: I was staying right next to Kaban. So I said, okay, so 5.30 I go there and he's there and

02:47:34.120 --> 02:47:38.440
[Amit Varma]: he greets me and then he says, Amit, let's run. Okay. Now I got to set the scene. This

02:47:38.440 --> 02:47:43.200
[Amit Varma]: is a moment where the camera kind of pulls back slowly and you're setting the scene around.

02:47:43.200 --> 02:47:49.360
[Amit Varma]: There are something like 32 men, 18 women and three dogs in the vicinity. Right. And

02:47:49.360 --> 02:47:52.440
[Amit Varma]: they're all doing different things. They're doing pushups or they're lounging or they're

02:47:52.440 --> 02:47:57.280
[Amit Varma]: chilling or they're running or whatever. The moment Mohit starts running, they stop what

02:47:57.280 --> 02:48:01.520
[Amit Varma]: they're doing and they turn and they look at him with their mouths open. It's like a

02:48:01.520 --> 02:48:06.040
[Amit Varma]: freeze frame. For a couple of the dogs, the tongue comes out because a man is running

02:48:06.040 --> 02:48:12.280
[Amit Varma]: like a gazelle. It is the most beautiful balletic thing I have ever seen. It is like an angel

02:48:12.280 --> 02:48:16.960
[Amit Varma]: is jogging through the clouds. Right. It's like that. And he has just said, let's run

02:48:16.960 --> 02:48:23.840
[Amit Varma]: Amit. So I have to go with him. So like an ungainly beast, I'm like, you know, kind of

02:48:23.840 --> 02:48:28.720
[Amit Varma]: running behind him. And at some point I run out of breath and he notices and he stops

02:48:28.720 --> 02:48:35.080
[Amit Varma]: and he says, okay, Amit, I have run enough. Now I will watch. You will run. So from one

02:48:35.080 --> 02:48:39.040
[Amit Varma]: pocket of his track pants, he whips out a notebook from another pocket. He whips out

02:48:39.040 --> 02:48:43.360
[Amit Varma]: a pen and he says, okay, run. Now I got to tell you at this point that whenever I get

02:48:43.360 --> 02:48:48.360
[Amit Varma]: into something, I get really geeky about it. Right. So I have read every book on running

02:48:48.360 --> 02:48:52.920
[Amit Varma]: that there is at this point. I have watched all the videos. I know my form is good. I

02:48:52.920 --> 02:48:57.800
[Amit Varma]: don't land on my heel. You know, I have taken close up videos of my feet running and everything.

02:48:57.800 --> 02:49:03.360
[Amit Varma]: I have like nailed everything. Right. So I'm assuming that there are no notes to take.

02:49:03.360 --> 02:49:08.720
[Amit Varma]: So I run for a bit and I go back and then he's got some 32 points that your ankle is

02:49:08.720 --> 02:49:14.440
[Amit Varma]: coming at this angle and so and so. And he tells me or he takes me through each of those.

02:49:14.440 --> 02:49:20.480
[Amit Varma]: And that day I decide, you know what, I'm going to take a break for a week from running.

02:49:20.480 --> 02:49:26.320
[Guest]: And then I never got back to it. Oh, no. I would have imagined that that sort of motivated

02:49:26.320 --> 02:49:31.080
[Guest]: you. But yeah, that's that's interesting. Right. When somebody geeks out on you, what

02:49:31.080 --> 02:49:36.040
[Amit Varma]: impact that would have on you? I'm actually partly kidding. I totally appreciate this

02:49:36.040 --> 02:49:40.840
[Amit Varma]: way of going in depth and thinking about this thing. And it's actually a correlation, not

02:49:40.840 --> 02:49:44.840
[Amit Varma]: a causation. I had a slight crick in my knee and I thought, let me rest it for a few days

02:49:44.840 --> 02:49:49.320
[Amit Varma]: and I never got back. But this event happened around that time. But I swear to you, man,

02:49:49.320 --> 02:49:53.880
[Amit Varma]: the way the way that gentleman ran and he's like a little taller than me is tall, slim

02:49:53.880 --> 02:50:01.400
[Guest]: and the park just froze. That's amazing. I would I would I mean, definitely look him

02:50:01.400 --> 02:50:06.760
[Guest]: up maybe if he has like a page or talks about his experiences. But these people don't have

02:50:06.760 --> 02:50:11.800
[Amit Varma]: time to be to be active on any social media. He's got a lovely newsletter, which I'll link

02:50:11.800 --> 02:50:15.560
[Amit Varma]: from the show notes. So I don't think he's written about his running there. But if you

02:50:15.560 --> 02:50:21.880
[Amit Varma]: happen to be in Delhi, I'll introduce you guys. But let's sort of get back to your story.

02:50:21.880 --> 02:50:27.240
[Amit Varma]: And let's in fact, chronologically get a look. But before that I have one running story too.

02:50:27.240 --> 02:50:33.400
[Guest]: And it's really funny because it's not a running running story. When I launched my startup,

02:50:33.400 --> 02:50:41.520
[Guest]: which was which which is like a fitness platform. You know how there is this compulsion of putting

02:50:41.520 --> 02:50:46.040
[Guest]: these before and after pictures and you know, it's it's almost like a compulsion, you have

02:50:46.040 --> 02:50:53.600
[Guest]: to do it, it doesn't matter if it if you believe in it or not. And I myself had a big transformation

02:50:53.600 --> 02:51:01.040
[Guest]: at some point. And I had these before and after pictures. And then I made a very impressive

02:51:01.040 --> 02:51:07.480
[Guest]: before and after pic where I look quite big in one and the picture I had where I look

02:51:07.480 --> 02:51:12.960
[Guest]: quite big was a running picture. And it was again one of those urban stampede. I've done

02:51:12.960 --> 02:51:18.600
[Guest]: quite a few of them. It's one of those. And then on the right side of the collage was

02:51:18.600 --> 02:51:26.040
[Guest]: me who had become quite fit during my time in Dubai and all that. And then of course,

02:51:26.040 --> 02:51:31.800
[Guest]: I put it and I launched my startup and all that is happening. And then one day I'm talking

02:51:31.800 --> 02:51:37.440
[Guest]: to a friend of mine and I'm telling him, I'm like, you know what, this, this pic on the

02:51:37.440 --> 02:51:43.840
[Guest]: left side when I'm doing this five kilometers on an urban stampede was my fastest run ever.

02:51:43.840 --> 02:51:49.200
[Guest]: Like all of my friends could not believe I got the timing that I did. And I was at my

02:51:49.200 --> 02:51:55.520
[Guest]: heaviest at that time. And I have just found this picture to pair it up with a picture

02:51:55.520 --> 02:52:01.760
[Guest]: where I had lost a lot of weight. And yeah, I was doing I was fitter in other areas. But

02:52:01.760 --> 02:52:07.000
[Guest]: if you really ask me, this is not a before and after story because I was very I was doing

02:52:07.000 --> 02:52:11.960
[Guest]: very well when I was bigger and I was doing very well on the right side when I had lost

02:52:11.960 --> 02:52:20.360
[Guest]: weight. So I do, I sometimes laugh about the compulsions that our jobs make us do, you

02:52:20.360 --> 02:52:29.760
[Guest]: know, like, or our professions make us do, because you have to sort of make up things

02:52:29.760 --> 02:52:36.800
[Guest]: that you have to let people assume things based on what you put up on social media,

02:52:36.800 --> 02:52:41.480
[Guest]: but the story could be really different. But then sometimes when I'm talking to, or I used

02:52:41.480 --> 02:52:45.300
[Guest]: to when I used to counsel clients for nutrition or so and sometimes I used to bring up my

02:52:45.300 --> 02:52:50.400
[Guest]: own story because it helps them to open up when you've shared your own. That time I used

02:52:50.400 --> 02:52:55.440
[Guest]: to tell them that, hey, you know what, I don't care the size that you are at, because it

02:52:55.440 --> 02:53:01.000
[Guest]: is not a reflection of your ability, because you could have some natural abilities that

02:53:01.000 --> 02:53:08.720
[Guest]: allow you to excel at the size that you are at. And so we need to find that we need to

02:53:08.720 --> 02:53:16.120
[Guest]: find what is it that really gets you going regardless of your size. And I guess then

02:53:16.120 --> 02:53:22.240
[Guest]: I would explain to them that, yeah, I mean, look at your fat loss journey as a fat loss,

02:53:22.240 --> 02:53:26.920
[Guest]: but it does not mean that whatever size you are at, you are not able to perform, you could

02:53:26.920 --> 02:53:33.960
[Guest]: really excel if you found what you like. And if sometimes we found what they like, then

02:53:33.960 --> 02:53:38.720
[Guest]: they could focus their fitness journey on that, because you since day one, you have

02:53:38.720 --> 02:53:42.520
[Guest]: the gratification of having hit your goals in that sense.

02:53:42.520 --> 02:53:48.040
[Amit Varma]: So let me ask you a related question coming off from this, that I'm fascinated with the

02:53:48.040 --> 02:53:53.960
[Amit Varma]: process of how people kind of get comfortable in their own skins, because we're always so

02:53:53.960 --> 02:53:58.240
[Amit Varma]: sort of struck through life by the anxiety of what other people think of us and how they

02:53:58.240 --> 02:54:03.200
[Amit Varma]: perceive us, which is largely pointless, because no one is thinking of anyone but themselves,

02:54:03.200 --> 02:54:08.960
[Amit Varma]: right? But it's still an anxiety that is there. And it's still there with me, you know, every

02:54:08.960 --> 02:54:11.960
[Amit Varma]: day, like, if I put on a t shirt, I'll be thinking about, you know, will my pawn show

02:54:11.960 --> 02:54:18.620
[Amit Varma]: in this and why don't they have Indian sizes and all of that. So did sports make that process

02:54:18.620 --> 02:54:24.720
[Amit Varma]: easier and not just in a physical sense of the way you look, but even at a sense of kind

02:54:24.720 --> 02:54:30.140
[Amit Varma]: of who you are just being like, like, like, for me, I'm comfortable in my own skin in

02:54:30.140 --> 02:54:35.600
[Amit Varma]: other non physical ways, in terms of the things I know, or what my accent might be or what

02:54:35.600 --> 02:54:43.100
[Amit Varma]: my weaknesses might be and all of those. And, you know, but both physically and in terms

02:54:43.100 --> 02:54:46.800
[Amit Varma]: of the people they are and the things they like and the things they want. I think many

02:54:46.800 --> 02:54:53.240
[Amit Varma]: people find it hard at one margin or the other to kind of get that comfort with themselves.

02:54:53.240 --> 02:54:59.680
[Amit Varma]: So how was that process for you? And since you counsel so many people, you know, and

02:54:59.680 --> 02:55:04.160
[Amit Varma]: speak to them, how do you see that process playing out in others? Is this an anxiety

02:55:04.160 --> 02:55:08.280
[Amit Varma]: that kind of needs to be fought? How do you get past it?

02:55:08.280 --> 02:55:15.600
[Guest]: So first talking about myself, Amit, you just learn to deal with it. It's like I think it's

02:55:15.600 --> 02:55:21.200
[Guest]: like you being in the field of acting or modelling where you have to, you know, you're being

02:55:21.200 --> 02:55:27.040
[Guest]: perceived in a certain way all the time and you're expected to look a certain way, which

02:55:27.040 --> 02:55:31.480
[Guest]: is of course slowly changing. But when it comes to sport as well, people judge your

02:55:31.480 --> 02:55:36.040
[Guest]: ability based on how you're looking. I'd like I just gave you the example of me getting

02:55:36.040 --> 02:55:40.760
[Guest]: into running and somebody looking at me on my desk and being like, oh, she's she cannot

02:55:40.760 --> 02:55:48.720
[Guest]: run. And I went through that myself as well. And there are some things that are to do with

02:55:48.720 --> 02:55:53.400
[Guest]: your weight. But then there are a lot of things that have to do with your height. What are

02:55:53.400 --> 02:55:58.280
[Guest]: you going to do about that? I was in volleyball. And of course, if there are people who are

02:55:58.280 --> 02:56:07.080
[Guest]: taller than me, who are competing with me in trials or so, then you do have a disadvantage

02:56:07.080 --> 02:56:13.760
[Guest]: and you have to sort of get over it. Sometimes you lose out. Apart from that, when it comes

02:56:13.760 --> 02:56:19.760
[Guest]: to being comfortable in my skin, I have cycles and I think everybody should accept that you

02:56:19.760 --> 02:56:27.160
[Guest]: have cycles. Unless your money is coming from how fit you look all the time, nobody is a

02:56:27.160 --> 02:56:37.800
[Guest]: hundred percent fit perineally. And in a sense, that is real. It's authentic. It's how it

02:56:37.800 --> 02:56:43.280
[Guest]: is because your life goes through phases. Your focus goes through phases unless you're

02:56:43.280 --> 02:56:50.640
[Guest]: a sportsman or whatever. And that's going to show on your body. And so long as by and

02:56:50.640 --> 02:56:54.840
[Guest]: large you understand that this is a phase and by and large, you know that at some point

02:56:54.840 --> 02:57:03.360
[Guest]: you have to make an effort to remain fit and happy. And if you're exercising for the endorphins

02:57:03.360 --> 02:57:10.320
[Guest]: of it, like for example, right now I live in Berlin and the weather is very, I mean,

02:57:10.320 --> 02:57:20.800
[Guest]: the sun rises at 4am. So many times it impacts your sleep. It's setting at 10 or in the winters,

02:57:20.800 --> 02:57:26.000
[Guest]: the sunset is at 4 and you've not even started your day. You've probably ended work or classes

02:57:26.000 --> 02:57:32.440
[Guest]: in my case and you still have a lot to do. How do you train your mind to be sharp after

02:57:32.440 --> 02:57:38.560
[Guest]: that time? So I would now sometimes go and exercise because I want to feel really fresh

02:57:38.560 --> 02:57:44.520
[Guest]: because I have a lot to do and not really because I want muscles or I'm, you know, wanting

02:57:44.520 --> 02:57:51.960
[Guest]: to be very fit. So I think allowing yourself those phases is really important. And however

02:57:51.960 --> 02:57:58.280
[Guest]: that shows up on your body. But the only one thing that I am quite cautious of is this

02:57:58.280 --> 02:58:08.000
[Guest]: whole idea of blanket statements like be comfortable in your body. And I'm completely for body

02:58:08.000 --> 02:58:13.400
[Guest]: positivity. And I have just given you many examples of no matter the size of the body,

02:58:13.400 --> 02:58:19.040
[Guest]: you could have many things that are going for you. But having said that, there are some

02:58:19.040 --> 02:58:26.440
[Guest]: very, very specific things that are related to carrying a lot of body fat or in terms

02:58:26.440 --> 02:58:36.320
[Guest]: of not being fit. And to gloss over them because of body positivity or not having a PS statement

02:58:36.320 --> 02:58:43.320
[Guest]: or saying that I'm comfortable in my skin is actually being very, very untrue to science

02:58:43.320 --> 02:58:50.880
[Guest]: in that sense. I mean, it's important to be comfortable in your skin. But it's also important

02:58:50.880 --> 02:58:57.800
[Guest]: to be brutally honest about your health, at least with yourself. And if you have understood

02:58:57.800 --> 02:59:06.720
[Guest]: that, then reciprocate that in the messaging that you are putting out. So yeah, it's just

02:59:06.720 --> 02:59:16.720
[Guest]: a minor statement on the side that waves about messaging around body positivity have to be

02:59:16.720 --> 02:59:23.640
[Amit Varma]: also very cautious. And do you see this in the people around you,

02:59:23.640 --> 02:59:29.160
[Amit Varma]: the people you counsel, the people around you and so on? Is it a problem that you see?

02:59:29.160 --> 02:59:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Because part of my earlier observation about a lot of people not doing enough self-reflection

02:59:35.240 --> 02:59:40.480
[Amit Varma]: is also this, that many of those people who don't do enough self-reflection are also people

02:59:40.480 --> 02:59:44.680
[Amit Varma]: who are at some level not comfortable in their skin just because they haven't thought about

02:59:44.680 --> 02:59:48.480
[Amit Varma]: it enough. And this just doesn't mean the physical aspect of it, somebody's too fat

02:59:48.480 --> 02:59:54.360
[Amit Varma]: or too short or whatever. But even otherwise, people keep pointing out to me when I can't

02:59:54.360 --> 02:59:58.380
[Amit Varma]: pronounce a word properly. Like I said, that instead of, you know, THAT, how it's supposed

02:59:58.380 --> 03:00:01.720
[Amit Varma]: to be. And I'm completely comfortable with that because yeah, that's what I do. So what

03:00:01.720 --> 03:00:05.680
[Amit Varma]: people know what I mean. But there might be other aspects where I'm not so comfortable.

03:00:05.680 --> 03:00:10.600
[Amit Varma]: But I see a lot of people around me who are in a sense, pretending not just to the world

03:00:10.600 --> 03:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: around themselves, but even to themselves, that they are something other than they are.

03:00:16.280 --> 03:00:23.440
[Guest]: Is this something you've noticed? I think, Amit, the larger perspective on behaving

03:00:23.440 --> 03:00:32.360
[Guest]: like that is finding excuses not to face the reality, right? And I think this is a deeper

03:00:32.360 --> 03:00:40.080
[Guest]: issue that goes beyond, like you said, beyond body positivity or anything for that matter

03:00:40.080 --> 03:00:47.120
[Guest]: that you may think is different about you or the world notices about you, but not in

03:00:47.120 --> 03:00:55.720
[Guest]: the most complimentary way. I guess it has to do with people not accepting that there

03:00:55.720 --> 03:01:02.560
[Guest]: is, if at all, a problem or at least within themselves, within their mind saying that,

03:01:02.560 --> 03:01:06.920
[Guest]: hey, is this a problem or is this not? And if your mind is going to accept that it is

03:01:06.920 --> 03:01:13.000
[Guest]: a problem, then automatically, at some point, you're going to accept that you have to do

03:01:13.000 --> 03:01:20.400
[Guest]: something to change it. If you're going to constantly avoid facing the reality, then

03:01:20.400 --> 03:01:26.080
[Guest]: it could be your weight, it could be addictions, it could be anything that you want to change

03:01:26.080 --> 03:01:32.080
[Guest]: at all, if at all, and you're not going to get to it. And I think that's why, that was

03:01:32.080 --> 03:01:39.680
[Guest]: my thought behind putting the bell hooks quote the other day on Twitter, which said that

03:01:39.680 --> 03:01:48.880
[Guest]: you have to learn to be solitary and happy in your own space, because otherwise you start

03:01:48.880 --> 03:01:56.840
[Guest]: using other people as escape because you want distractions. And in that sense, your relationships

03:01:56.840 --> 03:02:04.160
[Guest]: or your outings are going to be meaningless, because you cannot stand to be by yourself

03:02:04.160 --> 03:02:10.400
[Guest]: in a room without any distractions. And that's true for all of us, to some extent for all

03:02:10.400 --> 03:02:15.160
[Guest]: of us, because even if I'm sitting in a room by myself, if I'm distracting myself with

03:02:15.160 --> 03:02:23.000
[Guest]: my phone, or I can't imagine sitting by myself without my phone and with just a book, or

03:02:23.000 --> 03:02:30.720
[Guest]: if I am not going to be watching some Netflix, or drinking or something, then I'm actually

03:02:30.720 --> 03:02:37.880
[Guest]: not yet in that zone where I'm comfortable with myself. And for many people, and I have

03:02:37.880 --> 03:02:45.760
[Guest]: seen a lot of such type of people who constantly want to hang out with others, because they

03:02:45.760 --> 03:02:50.560
[Guest]: just don't know how to be by themselves. And being by, let's face it, being by yourself

03:02:50.560 --> 03:02:57.440
[Guest]: is not easy. Even those that are managing to do some of that, it comes with its fair

03:02:57.440 --> 03:03:07.960
[Guest]: share of doubting yourself or being just bored out of your mind, or sort of going down the

03:03:07.960 --> 03:03:15.720
[Guest]: rabbit hole of your own negative thoughts. It's not easy. But if you are able to sort

03:03:15.720 --> 03:03:21.200
[Guest]: of face that and be by yourself, then at some point, the self-reflection, the acceptance

03:03:21.200 --> 03:03:26.480
[Guest]: of the things that you want to change about yourself or not change, that sort of starts

03:03:26.480 --> 03:03:28.520
[Guest]: revealing itself.

03:03:28.520 --> 03:03:32.120
[Amit Varma]: I loved that Bell Hooks quote, so I'll just read it out for the benefit of listeners.

03:03:32.120 --> 03:03:37.200
[Amit Varma]: Knowing how to be solitary is central to the art of loving. When we can be alone, we can

03:03:37.200 --> 03:03:42.560
[Amit Varma]: be with others without using them as a means of escape. And that's a profound thought in

03:03:42.560 --> 03:03:48.440
[Amit Varma]: the sense that it also, I think, acknowledges the tendency that when we are with others,

03:03:48.440 --> 03:03:52.480
[Amit Varma]: we are playing a part. There is always a filter, there is always this consciousness of how

03:03:52.480 --> 03:03:58.400
[Amit Varma]: we are perceived. Whereas if we are just with oneself, we are what we are. Like there's

03:03:58.400 --> 03:04:03.560
[Amit Varma]: an excellent book I read by Seth Stevens, Davidowitz, which I'll link from the show

03:04:03.560 --> 03:04:10.960
[Amit Varma]: notes where what he essentially did was, his thesis was that people are most themselves

03:04:10.960 --> 03:04:14.520
[Amit Varma]: when a, they are alone and b, when they're searching for stuff on the internet. Because

03:04:14.520 --> 03:04:19.360
[Amit Varma]: that's what reveals their true desires and what they really want and all of that. So

03:04:19.360 --> 03:04:24.240
[Amit Varma]: he got anonymized data from Google, Facebook, and I think a bunch of others and wrote an

03:04:24.240 --> 03:04:28.560
[Amit Varma]: entire book about what people are really like, what they really want, what they really care

03:04:28.560 --> 03:04:34.320
[Amit Varma]: about, what turns them on and so on and so forth. So I kind of found that a very illuminating

03:04:34.320 --> 03:04:38.560
[Amit Varma]: approach and obviously anonymized data. So there's another quote you posted recently

03:04:38.560 --> 03:04:43.240
[Amit Varma]: from one of my favorite poets, Mary Oliver, which goes this way, quote, tell me what is

03:04:43.240 --> 03:04:47.740
[Amit Varma]: it you plan to do with your one wild and precious life, stop quote, which is a lovely question

03:04:47.740 --> 03:04:54.880
[Amit Varma]: that I think anyone of any age can, you know, pause and think about. And so when you look

03:04:54.880 --> 03:04:59.000
[Guest]: back on your life and you I find it a very difficult question to answer.

03:04:59.000 --> 03:05:04.280
[Guest]: I mean, the reason I posted it was because I was like, who is able to answer this at

03:05:04.280 --> 03:05:11.000
[Guest]: what point? You can have ideas, but sorry to cut you off, but that was my thought behind

03:05:11.000 --> 03:05:14.240
[Amit Varma]: posting it. No, it's a great question. And the reason

03:05:14.240 --> 03:05:19.520
[Amit Varma]: I said that anybody of any age can think about it is that people assume that after you reach

03:05:19.520 --> 03:05:25.760
[Amit Varma]: a certain age, surely you have answered this question. And that is not the case. Most adults

03:05:25.760 --> 03:05:30.320
[Amit Varma]: are winging it, you know, adulthood is winging it better than, you know, when you were not

03:05:30.320 --> 03:05:36.880
[Amit Varma]: an adult. So it's a difficult question, even for me, but to sort of use this as a way to

03:05:36.880 --> 03:05:42.480
[Amit Varma]: segue into your past life. So when you were sort of going through school, and about to

03:05:42.480 --> 03:05:45.360
[Amit Varma]: enter college, and you're, of course, playing volleyball, and you love sport, but you're

03:05:45.360 --> 03:05:49.640
[Amit Varma]: not going to be a professional and you don't want a job in railways. And you opt for sort

03:05:49.640 --> 03:05:55.960
[Amit Varma]: of engineering. What was your conception of yourself then? And what was driving you? Like,

03:05:55.960 --> 03:06:00.040
[Amit Varma]: did you fall in love with engineering, which is why you did it? Or, you know, I just smiled

03:06:00.040 --> 03:06:03.800
[Amit Varma]: as I said that, because I can't imagine anyone falling in love with engineering, but that

03:06:03.800 --> 03:06:11.400
[Amit Varma]: is just my arts-wala bias, as it were. Or, you know, were you just sort of following

03:06:11.400 --> 03:06:16.840
[Amit Varma]: a particular template that, okay, good students do engineering, and let me do this or whatever.

03:06:16.840 --> 03:06:23.200
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about, you know, your motivations and why you did the things you did back then.

03:06:23.200 --> 03:06:30.720
[Guest]: So to be honest, becoming an engineer was somewhere in my, in the back of my mind since

03:06:30.720 --> 03:06:37.960
[Guest]: I was six, maybe. I'm not saying this because I feel very passionate about engineering or

03:06:37.960 --> 03:06:42.720
[Guest]: to say that I was feeling very passionate back then. But I must have heard it somewhere

03:06:42.720 --> 03:06:54.080
[Guest]: and it stuck in my mind. And that's, to be honest, I didn't grow up in my schooling days

03:06:54.080 --> 03:06:59.920
[Guest]: thinking about, oh my God, what am I going to be? But like I said, because I got into

03:06:59.920 --> 03:07:05.440
[Guest]: sport because of a few other things that happened that made me more, much more confident as

03:07:05.440 --> 03:07:15.800
[Guest]: a person, that I think doing something good in sports or excelling in sport, in my case,

03:07:15.800 --> 03:07:23.380
[Guest]: made me feel valued. And because like I said, I was not like a topper in class or something,

03:07:23.380 --> 03:07:27.800
[Guest]: but then once you are a state and national player, you're valuable to the school. You

03:07:27.800 --> 03:07:32.640
[Guest]: can see that the school, your colleagues, everybody knows that, hey, this is her thing,

03:07:32.640 --> 03:07:37.280
[Guest]: this is her skill set. And I used to really enjoy that feeling. And I guess that's what

03:07:37.280 --> 03:07:46.320
[Guest]: I sort of was chasing as a school kid. And then the rest of my 10th and 11th and 12th,

03:07:46.320 --> 03:07:51.600
[Guest]: I guess I just wanted to do well, continue playing volleyball. And then when it came

03:07:51.600 --> 03:07:58.200
[Guest]: to choosing, I had a brief moment in 11th and you went to Ferguson Arts and who is not

03:07:58.200 --> 03:08:05.000
[Guest]: interested in Ferguson Arts. And with my background as well, there was a moment when I sort of

03:08:05.000 --> 03:08:11.040
[Guest]: wanted to rebel and I took admission to science in 11th, but I wanted to move to arts in the

03:08:11.040 --> 03:08:17.080
[Guest]: 12th. And like I said, my parents were always very supportive and they said that, okay,

03:08:17.080 --> 03:08:23.080
[Guest]: if you wanted to really do it, you should. But I have to be honest with you, I came from

03:08:23.080 --> 03:08:28.840
[Guest]: a middle-class family and I had absolutely no examples of my colleagues who studied arts

03:08:28.840 --> 03:08:40.520
[Guest]: at the time, whose family was not very well-to-do. They were all absolutely very well-to-do and

03:08:40.520 --> 03:08:50.480
[Guest]: could allow their children the choice to join arts, the indulgence. And to be fair to these

03:08:50.480 --> 03:08:55.480
[Guest]: examples that I had in front of my eyes at the time, they were all extremely intelligent

03:08:55.480 --> 03:09:04.960
[Guest]: people and later on were gold medalists in Ferguson Arts as well. But they had the freedom

03:09:04.960 --> 03:09:14.560
[Guest]: to choose at the time arts and for people like me, we made peace with the fact that

03:09:14.560 --> 03:09:19.560
[Guest]: arts can be done later on or you can join and change your field and all of that. So

03:09:19.560 --> 03:09:28.120
[Guest]: I followed and then of the choices available to me, engineering seemed to be the most natural

03:09:28.120 --> 03:09:34.880
[Guest]: for me. And the only thing that I knew when I was choosing engineering was I knew what

03:09:34.880 --> 03:09:40.840
[Guest]: I didn't want to do. And it was to do with all kinds of IT and computer engineering.

03:09:40.840 --> 03:09:46.440
[Guest]: And I wanted to do mechanical engineering and also at the time it was really more about

03:09:46.440 --> 03:09:54.680
[Guest]: what felt interesting rather than me having thought about it in depth. And then with a

03:09:54.680 --> 03:10:01.640
[Guest]: combination of a university or a college that ranked well. And then I didn't get mechanical

03:10:01.640 --> 03:10:11.160
[Guest]: and at that time some students from the petroleum engineering department were living in my building

03:10:11.160 --> 03:10:19.880
[Guest]: and they told me about this branch that only MIT offered. And what I really, really liked

03:10:19.880 --> 03:10:27.240
[Guest]: about petroleum and I know the industry doesn't have a great name in this moment, but I wasn't

03:10:27.240 --> 03:10:32.000
[Guest]: thinking about all of that. I was thinking about what do I like to do and whether it

03:10:32.000 --> 03:10:36.560
[Guest]: will have prospects because you're coming from a middle class background. It's very

03:10:36.560 --> 03:10:43.200
[Guest]: easy for you to have saved up a little money and sit here now in your mid thirties and

03:10:43.200 --> 03:10:49.520
[Guest]: look back and judge your decisions. But for me at that time it was about what is unique,

03:10:49.520 --> 03:10:56.000
[Guest]: what is creative. And petroleum was the only engineering course that allowed me to study

03:10:56.000 --> 03:11:06.000
[Guest]: geology, which is anyway between creativity and science and also engineering subjects

03:11:06.000 --> 03:11:10.840
[Guest]: along with it and mechanical engineering. Half of the first two years were mechanical

03:11:10.840 --> 03:11:17.080
[Guest]: and I already knew I was interested in it. And then I was going to study geology, paleontology,

03:11:17.080 --> 03:11:26.240
[Guest]: I was going to study fluid flow and that combination of and the uniqueness of petroleum engineering

03:11:26.240 --> 03:11:32.960
[Guest]: is because all the oil and gas fields are hundreds of kilometers wide. No company ever

03:11:32.960 --> 03:11:37.800
[Guest]: has enough data. There's only one or two wells that are drilled and you have data in

03:11:37.800 --> 03:11:43.320
[Guest]: a certain radius. And then we used to have to build those 3D models with that little

03:11:43.320 --> 03:11:52.240
[Guest]: data over 100 and 200 kilometers and extrapolate that data. And it's really a mix of physics

03:11:52.240 --> 03:11:59.520
[Guest]: and creativity and imagination. And to then put it all together logically, I found that

03:11:59.520 --> 03:12:06.440
[Guest]: very interesting about petroleum. And that's how I ended up joining it. Throughout this

03:12:06.440 --> 03:12:12.440
[Guest]: whole journey, there was really no long term goal that mujhe ye banna hai, wo banna hai.

03:12:12.440 --> 03:12:21.960
[Guest]: And continued to be very active outside of, I mean, in things outside of academics. And

03:12:21.960 --> 03:12:27.760
[Guest]: then eventually all of that came together in getting a job with Shell, which was a dream

03:12:27.760 --> 03:12:35.320
[Guest]: job because it was at the time the topmost company on the Fortune 500 in 2008. I would

03:12:35.320 --> 03:12:43.240
[Guest]: say I thoroughly enjoyed that journey. I guess I've followed my gut all the time. What is

03:12:43.240 --> 03:12:48.800
[Guest]: it that I'm really going to enjoy doing on a day to day basis, not in terms of principles

03:12:48.800 --> 03:12:54.080
[Guest]: and all of that. At the age of 18, I was not thinking about all of that for sure. But on

03:12:54.080 --> 03:12:58.720
[Guest]: a day to day basis, what am I going to do? And that is something that I did and I really

03:12:58.720 --> 03:13:06.920
[Guest]: enjoyed it. Definitely, I think even my background with sport allowed me to take that risk because

03:13:06.920 --> 03:13:11.880
[Guest]: petroleum in the petroleum engineering class, there were only three girls, and the rest

03:13:11.880 --> 03:13:19.320
[Guest]: of them were boys. And, and people would scare you when you would make that choice. Rig pe

03:13:19.320 --> 03:13:25.640
[Guest]: jaana padta hai, wahan pe ladkiyon ke liye kuchh hota nahi hai. And then you may not

03:13:25.640 --> 03:13:31.080
[Guest]: be treated very well. And all these things, people would tell you and you still go ahead

03:13:31.080 --> 03:13:36.120
[Guest]: and choose that branch and then you have a flourishing career afterwards. And because

03:13:36.120 --> 03:13:42.120
[Guest]: I have had, because I was in petroleum, most of my life and most of my career, I have been

03:13:42.120 --> 03:13:49.360
[Guest]: in, in rooms, meeting rooms and in situations where there's hardly any women in the first

03:13:49.360 --> 03:13:54.080
[Guest]: place. And I guess because, because I came from the background that I did, I was fairly

03:13:54.080 --> 03:13:59.200
[Guest]: independent and I was quite risk taking in that sense. And so it never bothered me. I

03:13:59.200 --> 03:14:05.720
[Guest]: have never really, of course, I mean, I agree with the whole idea of women not being given

03:14:05.720 --> 03:14:12.360
[Guest]: a platform and a voice. But if you put me in a room where I am the only girl sitting

03:14:12.360 --> 03:14:17.600
[Guest]: with a lot of men, I would not find it very weird. Because that's the experience I've

03:14:17.600 --> 03:14:23.840
[Guest]: had ever since I joined engineering. But yeah, I didn't have a very long term plan.

03:14:23.840 --> 03:14:29.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I wouldn't at all be apologetic about the petroleum industry like you half

03:14:29.680 --> 03:14:34.680
[Amit Varma]: were because it's one of the engines of the modern world. So, you know, whatever might

03:14:34.680 --> 03:14:39.960
[Amit Varma]: be the case now and how situations may have changed. So post engineering, you said at

03:14:39.960 --> 03:14:43.380
[Amit Varma]: one point you quit, you wanted to do your startup. And at that point, you also kind

03:14:43.380 --> 03:14:48.800
[Amit Varma]: of went to Thailand and all this stuff happening. So what's, what's happening in your life through

03:14:48.800 --> 03:14:54.420
[Amit Varma]: this period? Like you joined Shell, you were presumably, you know, how was that experience

03:14:54.420 --> 03:14:58.760
[Amit Varma]: for you of actually being a petroleum engineer? And what was your relationship with sport

03:14:58.760 --> 03:15:03.800
[Amit Varma]: through this time? And then at what point did you decide that you want to strike out?

03:15:03.800 --> 03:15:08.560
[Amit Varma]: And what was it that you intended to do when you went on your own?

03:15:08.560 --> 03:15:15.360
[Guest]: So when I joined Shell, in terms of sport, like I said to you, I did a lot of trekking

03:15:15.360 --> 03:15:21.560
[Guest]: with the group that I had because Shell in India was a young company, they had just launched

03:15:21.560 --> 03:15:29.560
[Guest]: a technology center in about 2007 or so. And the interesting thing about that was that

03:15:29.560 --> 03:15:38.280
[Guest]: they were recruiting about groups of 40 people or so from these IITs and then from MIT Pune.

03:15:38.280 --> 03:15:43.960
[Guest]: And they had only started doing that in 2007. So that means the whole building, I joined

03:15:43.960 --> 03:15:51.360
[Guest]: in 2008. So there were maybe two batches before me. So the entire building was of the age

03:15:51.360 --> 03:15:58.280
[Guest]: group of 21, 22, 23, which is very unique compared to joining an IT company. And then

03:15:58.280 --> 03:16:04.160
[Guest]: there were a few expats who were in their late 50s or early 50s or so, and some Indians

03:16:04.160 --> 03:16:09.480
[Guest]: who were brought in from ONGC, who were our managers, who are also much more senior, but

03:16:09.480 --> 03:16:16.440
[Guest]: that number was very small. And so there was a lot of scope to continue doing sport because

03:16:16.440 --> 03:16:25.360
[Guest]: we did a lot of running in those days, I did a lot of trekking. And I played a lot of badminton

03:16:25.360 --> 03:16:32.800
[Guest]: because Shell used to book these courts for us. And we had a great group and I got really

03:16:32.800 --> 03:16:39.000
[Guest]: good at badminton in those days. I used to play it since I was a child, but I really

03:16:39.000 --> 03:16:46.520
[Guest]: I think honed my skill in those days. So continued doing things, participated in corporate tournaments

03:16:46.520 --> 03:16:51.920
[Guest]: and things like that, but nothing like really, really competitive as such. But that was about

03:16:51.920 --> 03:16:57.160
[Guest]: it. And then, like I said, in Dubai, I was with these colleagues who were ex-New Zealand

03:16:57.160 --> 03:17:05.280
[Guest]: military and we participated in this Desert Warrior. So that's how it was, I was active.

03:17:05.280 --> 03:17:11.840
[Guest]: In terms of career, so in Shell, I was a reservoir engineer. So what reservoir engineers do is

03:17:11.840 --> 03:17:19.000
[Guest]: when a couple of wells, exploration wells are drilled on oil and gas fields and data

03:17:19.000 --> 03:17:27.560
[Guest]: is collected. So initially seismic surveys and all are done and then these surveys go

03:17:27.560 --> 03:17:35.160
[Guest]: to the geologists and another group of people called petrophysicists who then give us an

03:17:35.160 --> 03:17:40.480
[Guest]: idea of what are the rocks, where is the oil found. And normally oil is found in carbonates

03:17:40.480 --> 03:17:49.280
[Guest]: or sandstones and how the formation looks, how big is the field and what is the porosity,

03:17:49.280 --> 03:17:57.080
[Guest]: what is the permeability, can we get it out. And then they make some models and then as

03:17:57.080 --> 03:18:03.600
[Guest]: reservoir engineers, we had to basically use those models and model the fluid flow. So

03:18:03.600 --> 03:18:09.480
[Guest]: we look at the viscosity of the fluid, the pressure under which it is, the saturation

03:18:09.480 --> 03:18:16.640
[Guest]: of the liquid. And we have to eventually, if the oil field has produced before, then

03:18:16.640 --> 03:18:22.960
[Guest]: we have to bring our model closer to what oil and gas it has produced before and then

03:18:22.960 --> 03:18:28.480
[Guest]: forecast how much it will produce later and then come up with the number of wells that

03:18:28.480 --> 03:18:34.400
[Guest]: we want to drill to bring that much oil out. And so our job was to find the locations from

03:18:34.400 --> 03:18:41.360
[Guest]: our 3D modelling of how can we get the most out by drilling the fewest number of wells.

03:18:41.360 --> 03:18:45.840
[Guest]: And then there is various challenges, there is fractures in the rock, there is places

03:18:45.840 --> 03:18:52.600
[Guest]: you can't get to, then the types of wells you have to drill. And so that was mainly

03:18:52.600 --> 03:18:57.600
[Guest]: my job and then I was looking at the business planning as well. I was in my last posting

03:18:57.600 --> 03:19:03.280
[Guest]: in Dubai, I was working on the oil field in Iraq which is called Majnoon, which is currently

03:19:03.280 --> 03:19:07.760
[Guest]: the world's second biggest oil field. Yeah, I pretty much worked on oil and gas fields

03:19:07.760 --> 03:19:14.200
[Guest]: across the world. And then after having done that for 8 years in 2016, I was like, it's

03:19:14.200 --> 03:19:18.960
[Guest]: time to move on. By then you, of course, think that you don't want to be associated for

03:19:18.960 --> 03:19:30.480
[Guest]: too long, you're wiser, you've probably come to a point where you've sort of supported

03:19:30.480 --> 03:19:35.680
[Guest]: your family, the things that you immediately needed your job to do as a youngster has been

03:19:35.680 --> 03:19:41.800
[Guest]: taken care of and you're in a risk-taking position. And I was always interested in fitness

03:19:41.800 --> 03:19:46.920
[Guest]: and sport and then, like I said, in Dubai I really took it a notch higher and then around

03:19:46.920 --> 03:19:53.000
[Guest]: that time I had my start-up idea and I came back to India and then I decided that I want

03:19:53.000 --> 03:19:58.600
[Guest]: to now quit. And I was about 29-30 then and I was like, this is when I'm going to take

03:19:58.600 --> 03:20:05.560
[Guest]: a risk, this is a good time to risk doing something different. And that's how I ended

03:20:05.560 --> 03:20:13.640
[Guest]: up quitting. I took about 6 months off and then in 2017 I went on to study sports nutrition

03:20:13.640 --> 03:20:20.680
[Guest]: and personal training from the K11 Institute of Fitness Sciences in Pune. And then I launched

03:20:20.680 --> 03:20:24.280
[Guest]: my start-up and it was a whole new journey because as a petroleum engineer I didn't know

03:20:24.280 --> 03:20:30.640
[Guest]: how to build tech platforms and all of that. So then I started a new journey after that.

03:20:30.640 --> 03:20:35.880
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about this journey of actually learning about fitness and learning about

03:20:35.880 --> 03:20:41.680
[Amit Varma]: nutrition and so on because one of the things that, one of the rabbit holes I kind of went

03:20:41.680 --> 03:20:48.400
[Amit Varma]: into was just how everything we knew about nutrition not too long ago was completely

03:20:48.400 --> 03:20:55.000
[Amit Varma]: wrong. There are great books by Gary Taubes and Nina Teicholz and all that. I'll sort

03:20:55.000 --> 03:20:57.200
[Guest]: of link those from the show notes and Jason Fung.

03:20:57.200 --> 03:21:03.280
[Amit Varma]: I love those. I think Nina Teicholz is really good. Gary Taubes is really good. I was going

03:21:03.280 --> 03:21:08.160
[Guest]: to gift you one of those books by the way. I didn't find it in Crossword and I didn't

03:21:08.160 --> 03:21:09.440
[Guest]: have enough time to order it on Amazon.

03:21:09.440 --> 03:21:12.840
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I have of course read them all digitally and you did give me a lovely book on running

03:21:12.840 --> 03:21:18.800
[Amit Varma]: by Murakami. So thank you for that. I'll use that to inspire myself and one of my realizations

03:21:18.800 --> 03:21:25.280
[Amit Varma]: looking into that was that for decades we have demonized fat and exculpated carbs and

03:21:25.280 --> 03:21:31.200
[Amit Varma]: especially sugar and that many of the studies that blamed fat for many of the misfortunes

03:21:31.200 --> 03:21:35.480
[Amit Varma]: that we go through like heart disease and so on were funded by the sugar lobby and these

03:21:35.480 --> 03:21:39.680
[Amit Varma]: books have great details of the politics behind it and the economics behind it and the incentives

03:21:39.680 --> 03:21:45.700
[Amit Varma]: at play and I think in the late 70s the US Health Association or some US government body

03:21:45.700 --> 03:21:50.280
[Amit Varma]: came out with their dietary guidelines which essentially caused the obesity epidemic in

03:21:50.280 --> 03:21:55.280
[Amit Varma]: America because they were like sugar is completely fine, carbs are fine, fat is evil.

03:21:55.280 --> 03:21:59.800
[Amit Varma]: And today we know the opposite is true. That sugar is poison. As you pointed out earlier

03:21:59.800 --> 03:22:05.180
[Amit Varma]: during lunch, sugar is like cocaine. It is a dangerous addictive drug and I have of course

03:22:05.180 --> 03:22:09.160
[Amit Varma]: been on keto plus intermittent fasting a couple of years back and found the benefits of it

03:22:09.160 --> 03:22:13.960
[Amit Varma]: and with your kind guidance now, though I started keto three days ago again before we

03:22:13.960 --> 03:22:19.740
[Amit Varma]: met but you've guided many people into keto and I'll take your advice on this as well.

03:22:19.740 --> 03:22:23.260
[Amit Varma]: But what struck me through all of this, through reading up on all of this and entering these

03:22:23.260 --> 03:22:29.680
[Amit Varma]: rabbit holes was how the conventional wisdom on this is so incredibly wrong and therefore

03:22:29.680 --> 03:22:36.280
[Amit Varma]: even when you speak with people who are professionals in this, whether they are doctors or nutritionists,

03:22:36.280 --> 03:22:40.840
[Amit Varma]: they are actually giving you bad advice because they are practitioners who learned their theory

03:22:40.840 --> 03:22:47.460
[Amit Varma]: at a time before the science changed, so to say, before we knew what we know now and therefore

03:22:47.460 --> 03:22:54.020
[Amit Varma]: many of their ideas are actively dangerous and sort of wrong. And what I also realized

03:22:54.020 --> 03:22:59.240
[Amit Varma]: during this time is that we assume that all of this knowledge which is in these guidebooks

03:22:59.240 --> 03:23:04.180
[Amit Varma]: and government organizations, give it out into bullet point format and all of that,

03:23:04.180 --> 03:23:08.980
[Amit Varma]: it has a ring of science about it. But the science of nutrition, it seems to me, is really

03:23:08.980 --> 03:23:15.040
[Amit Varma]: at a very early stage. It's where, you know, other medicine possibly was in the 19th century.

03:23:15.040 --> 03:23:19.540
[Amit Varma]: We don't really understand what's going on. And it's, you know, only with time that we

03:23:19.540 --> 03:23:27.160
[Amit Varma]: are getting more and more knowledge of it. So tell me about your journey of understanding

03:23:27.160 --> 03:23:31.440
[Amit Varma]: nutrition, understanding how the field had evolved, not just at the point in time where

03:23:31.440 --> 03:23:36.120
[Amit Varma]: you actually, you know, take the course and start learning about it. But even before that

03:23:36.120 --> 03:23:41.120
[Amit Varma]: as a sports person and so on, you've obviously been thinking deeply about that stuff. So,

03:23:41.120 --> 03:23:45.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, tell me about that journey of just learning all of this.

03:23:45.280 --> 03:23:53.040
[Guest]: So Amit, first of all, when I was in school and university and when I was playing competitively,

03:23:53.040 --> 03:23:59.200
[Guest]: there was literally no understanding or discussion about nutrition. I mean, yeah, for sure people

03:23:59.200 --> 03:24:03.920
[Guest]: would be like, oh, wazan kam karo, all of that would happen. But then nobody would tell

03:24:03.920 --> 03:24:08.280
[Guest]: you what to do about it. And coming from like middle class backgrounds, we weren't really

03:24:08.280 --> 03:24:12.400
[Guest]: thinking about, oh, there are nutritionists, so people actually go to them. Actually, I

03:24:12.400 --> 03:24:18.680
[Guest]: think going to a nutritionist has become mainstream in the last five or six years, I guess. And

03:24:18.680 --> 03:24:24.400
[Guest]: some of the digital startups are also sort of have helped that whole journey because

03:24:24.400 --> 03:24:30.000
[Guest]: they made it more affordable. But so when I was growing up, there was really not much

03:24:30.000 --> 03:24:35.640
[Guest]: knowledge about nutrition. There was just the understanding that, hey, you should eat

03:24:35.640 --> 03:24:42.480
[Guest]: less so that your weight doesn't go up, you know, that's about it. I think after I studied

03:24:42.480 --> 03:24:49.680
[Guest]: nutrition and the reason I studied it is because I wanted to launch an online tech platform

03:24:49.680 --> 03:24:56.080
[Guest]: that did like video workouts and personalized nutrition and all of that. But for me, it

03:24:56.080 --> 03:25:02.720
[Guest]: was about, hey, how am I going to know or understand the quality of my product if I

03:25:02.720 --> 03:25:08.680
[Guest]: haven't certified myself in the first place? So you can think of it like an engineer's

03:25:08.680 --> 03:25:13.760
[Guest]: mindset that, hey, I have to know scientifically how these things work, even if I can employ

03:25:13.760 --> 03:25:18.360
[Guest]: other nutritionists or personal trainers, because how do I know the quality of my product?

03:25:18.360 --> 03:25:22.520
[Guest]: Nobody could be telling me anything, but I'll have no opinion about it. So that's how I

03:25:22.520 --> 03:25:29.920
[Guest]: started the course in personal training and nutrition. And thankfully, and the reason

03:25:29.920 --> 03:25:35.640
[Guest]: I joined K-11 in Pune was because even though there are a lot of international courses,

03:25:35.640 --> 03:25:45.280
[Guest]: there are very few that go into the scientific detail of nutrition as much as K-11 does.

03:25:45.280 --> 03:25:50.920
[Guest]: And that is because it was founded by Kaizad Kapadia, who's no more, unfortunately we lost

03:25:50.920 --> 03:25:57.480
[Guest]: him last year during COVID, but who I immensely admire. You can easily call him the father

03:25:57.480 --> 03:26:05.680
[Guest]: of fitness in India, because he is the only person who went into so much depth of nutrition

03:26:05.680 --> 03:26:16.480
[Guest]: in India and created a course that was highly, highly scientific, open to debate, that it

03:26:16.480 --> 03:26:23.880
[Guest]: allowed us to understand why a keto diet or why some other diet, why something works,

03:26:23.880 --> 03:26:34.080
[Guest]: why something doesn't. And so long as you're learning by asking why and getting a scientific

03:26:34.080 --> 03:26:40.480
[Guest]: answer, I would say, regardless of where we are in our understanding of nutrition, you

03:26:40.480 --> 03:26:50.720
[Guest]: are in good hands. But most often than not, people will not ask why. And for me, that

03:26:50.720 --> 03:27:01.280
[Guest]: journey was, first of all, because I met Kaizad and I was convinced that he was a science

03:27:01.280 --> 03:27:06.720
[Guest]: inclined person and not just somebody doing fitness courses. Otherwise, it wouldn't have

03:27:06.720 --> 03:27:15.360
[Guest]: kept me engaged. So I learned a lot from him. He was the one who told us about the books

03:27:15.360 --> 03:27:22.800
[Guest]: that you mentioned earlier from Nina Teicholz and Gary Taubes. And then we read those books

03:27:22.800 --> 03:27:32.040
[Guest]: and Nina Teicholz is a health investigative journalist. And if you would want to find

03:27:32.040 --> 03:27:39.040
[Guest]: out about proofs for what we are saying nowadays, then you go into these books. So there were

03:27:39.040 --> 03:27:43.000
[Guest]: some things that were introduced to me in my sports nutrition course, but again, the

03:27:43.000 --> 03:27:47.920
[Guest]: course is like six or seven months. So the questions that you have, you also try to answer

03:27:47.920 --> 03:27:54.280
[Guest]: them by reading these books by these people. There is also a wonderful book that I read

03:27:54.280 --> 03:28:02.120
[Guest]: that's called The Wheat Belly. And that literally goes into how the wheat that we eat today

03:28:02.120 --> 03:28:14.520
[Guest]: isn't even wheat. It's like some 100-200 strain of some plant that has come out of sort of

03:28:14.520 --> 03:28:22.360
[Guest]: experimenting with the original wheat plant, because we need to meet the demand and supply.

03:28:22.360 --> 03:28:27.920
[Guest]: And the original wheat plant, for example, was five feet tall. And today, the wheat plant

03:28:27.920 --> 03:28:35.840
[Guest]: is very short, because a lot of the produce was being lost because of the winds, and the

03:28:35.840 --> 03:28:44.120
[Guest]: demand was growing. And slowly, we started changing how the wheat plant could produce

03:28:44.120 --> 03:28:50.840
[Guest]: more. And what we have today is so altered from the original that we don't even know

03:28:50.840 --> 03:28:57.600
[Guest]: if it is called wheat anymore, how many strains of the original plant are there. And so you

03:28:57.600 --> 03:29:03.480
[Guest]: start reading all of this and you start thinking about, hey, what makes sense to me the most?

03:29:03.480 --> 03:29:09.680
[Guest]: And if I'm going to convince somebody on how they should eat or how they shouldn't, can

03:29:09.680 --> 03:29:14.360
[Guest]: I back myself up? That was pretty much my journey. And that's why I have gone on to

03:29:14.360 --> 03:29:21.440
[Guest]: read these books. Because you're asking, especially when it comes to a ketogenic diet, and given

03:29:21.440 --> 03:29:29.040
[Guest]: that there is so much information and misinformation online, you're going to have to really talk

03:29:29.040 --> 03:29:34.280
[Guest]: to people and explain to them why you're doing what you're doing. And at the same time, you

03:29:34.280 --> 03:29:42.160
[Guest]: want to educate yourself enough to let people go who do not let you function with your scientific

03:29:42.160 --> 03:29:48.840
[Guest]: beliefs. Because you're going to have clients who are going to hold very strong opinions.

03:29:48.840 --> 03:29:54.860
[Guest]: And you don't want to get into circular discussions with them. Because this kind of discussion

03:29:54.860 --> 03:30:02.000
[Guest]: can keep going on. You can engage genuine questions and answer them. But for me, it's

03:30:02.000 --> 03:30:08.440
[Guest]: like if somebody is coming to you with a religious or a strong belief, then they are not the

03:30:08.440 --> 03:30:11.920
[Guest]: people you're going to try and convince because they have a certain belief system. This is

03:30:11.920 --> 03:30:17.720
[Guest]: not to do with science. Then I'm going to be like, okay, follow whatever you want. If

03:30:17.720 --> 03:30:22.440
[Guest]: you're a Brahmin or a vegetarian, because you are a religious person, then what is the

03:30:22.440 --> 03:30:27.320
[Guest]: point of discussing science? You're eating a vegetarian diet because of that. So that's

03:30:27.320 --> 03:30:37.600
[Guest]: fine. Then in my mind, I'm like, okay, that's fine. But I have a problem when people just

03:30:37.600 --> 03:30:44.120
[Guest]: go on propagating diets, for example, vegan diets by just saying that, hey, this is healthy,

03:30:44.120 --> 03:30:49.920
[Guest]: so I'm doing it. If you're doing it because you feel for animals, that's wonderful. I'm

03:30:49.920 --> 03:30:58.480
[Guest]: not going to debate that. But don't try and say that, hey, this is a very healthy diet.

03:30:58.480 --> 03:31:03.480
[Guest]: Because scientifically, it's very difficult to prove that with a vegan diet, you're getting

03:31:03.480 --> 03:31:10.600
[Guest]: the kind of first class proteins that you need. And then trying to convince people that

03:31:10.600 --> 03:31:19.000
[Guest]: pea protein is very good. I am not very sold on those things, because I just cannot stand

03:31:19.000 --> 03:31:24.120
[Guest]: the scientific backing that these things have at this moment.

03:31:24.120 --> 03:31:28.680
[Amit Varma]: Like I understand what you mean about there being no point in discussing something with

03:31:28.680 --> 03:31:32.320
[Amit Varma]: people. And there's this lovely essay Paul Graham had written called the four quadrants

03:31:32.320 --> 03:31:37.520
[Amit Varma]: of conformism. And one of these four categories was a type called the aggressively conventional

03:31:37.520 --> 03:31:43.280
[Amit Varma]: minded ones. And you run into them all the time, right? And in this context, also, I've

03:31:43.280 --> 03:31:48.480
[Amit Varma]: run into them when I talk about sugar being poison and how it's dangerous and all of that.

03:31:48.480 --> 03:31:54.760
[Amit Varma]: And these are people who would have been taught in school that fat is a problem, that dietary

03:31:54.760 --> 03:31:58.800
[Amit Varma]: cholesterol is a problem, and so on and so forth. And that eggs are bad. I mean, there

03:31:58.800 --> 03:32:02.200
[Amit Varma]: are actually people who have egg white omelets and think they're eating something healthy,

03:32:02.200 --> 03:32:06.880
[Amit Varma]: but they're not eating the healthiest part of the egg. And there's no point arguing with

03:32:06.880 --> 03:32:13.080
[Amit Varma]: them because what happens with people, conventional people, what happens with everyone is that

03:32:13.080 --> 03:32:17.560
[Amit Varma]: we look for frames to explain the world. And for many of us, there is a frame we adopt,

03:32:17.560 --> 03:32:21.720
[Amit Varma]: which is a conventional frame, which has been handed down to us, which could include things

03:32:21.720 --> 03:32:26.200
[Amit Varma]: like fat is bad, or India's problem is its population, and so on and so forth. Another

03:32:26.200 --> 03:32:30.000
[Amit Varma]: margin on which I face resistance when I say our population is not a problem, people are

03:32:30.000 --> 03:32:31.000
[Guest]: brains not stomachs.

03:32:31.000 --> 03:32:33.720
[Guest]: I completely believe that. I think population is a strength.

03:32:33.720 --> 03:32:39.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, people are brains, not stomachs. But again, I get enormous pushback. And the reason

03:32:39.080 --> 03:32:43.960
[Amit Varma]: for that pushback, the reason aggressively conventional minded people exist, is I think

03:32:43.960 --> 03:32:50.280
[Amit Varma]: aggressively conventional minded people, I love Graham's formulation here, are either

03:32:50.280 --> 03:32:55.720
[Amit Varma]: lazy or stupid. Because once they get that get a framework that explains the world to

03:32:55.720 --> 03:33:00.160
[Amit Varma]: them, they simply do not want to reconsider it because it takes intellectual effort or

03:33:00.160 --> 03:33:05.800
[Amit Varma]: intellectual honesty, or even intellectual ability to be able to, you know, hold multiple

03:33:05.800 --> 03:33:10.440
[Amit Varma]: thoughts in one's head simultaneously. And these are really the kind of people who irritate

03:33:10.440 --> 03:33:15.320
[Amit Varma]: me the most on Twitter, who will come at you and be aggressive, with a completely conventional

03:33:15.320 --> 03:33:19.400
[Amit Varma]: point of view, and think that, you know, they are independent thinkers of some sort, or

03:33:19.400 --> 03:33:24.400
[Amit Varma]: they've really kind of figured it out. But that is a sort of a pet peeve I have. And

03:33:24.400 --> 03:33:30.220
[Amit Varma]: let's not kind of go into that. But so when it sort of came to nutrition, you've pointed

03:33:30.220 --> 03:33:34.800
[Amit Varma]: out your journey in terms of weight as well, you know, you have your before and after picture,

03:33:34.800 --> 03:33:40.280
[Amit Varma]: and you also lost a lot of weight and all of that. So when you started learning about

03:33:40.280 --> 03:33:44.780
[Amit Varma]: fitness and nutrition, at one level, some of it would have corresponded with what you

03:33:44.780 --> 03:33:50.120
[Amit Varma]: already knew from experience, or kind of deepen that or back that up. And some of it might

03:33:50.120 --> 03:33:54.320
[Amit Varma]: have been new to you and sort of challenged the way you thought about it. And then in

03:33:54.320 --> 03:33:58.440
[Amit Varma]: the second category, I'm guessing that you would have said, okay, let me do this. If

03:33:58.440 --> 03:34:02.720
[Amit Varma]: I am going to recommend this diet to other people, let me do it and let me see how I

03:34:02.720 --> 03:34:08.260
[Amit Varma]: feel. So tell me a little bit about that sort of journey. And, you know, is that the reason

03:34:08.260 --> 03:34:12.440
[Amit Varma]: for for example, weight loss or whatever, or you know, what was

03:34:12.440 --> 03:34:18.720
[Guest]: No, so my my weight loss journey happened even before I studied nutrition. But that

03:34:18.720 --> 03:34:26.040
[Guest]: was just me following another trainer's plan, exercise and then keep your calories, calorie

03:34:26.040 --> 03:34:34.360
[Guest]: count and stuff. When I actually learned nutrition, then I realized what is the what are the functions

03:34:34.360 --> 03:34:43.400
[Guest]: of proteins, fats and carbs in our body. And so when we say eat 1200 calories a day 1300

03:34:43.400 --> 03:34:48.880
[Guest]: calories a day, now I don't talk in calories. Now I now I don't just don't talk in terms

03:34:48.880 --> 03:34:54.400
[Guest]: of calories, I talk in terms of what is the quality of food that you're eating. So that

03:34:54.400 --> 03:34:59.800
[Guest]: was a big change. Why am I eating a lot more fat? Or why am I eating a lot more protein,

03:34:59.800 --> 03:35:07.720
[Guest]: I learned that I could have a low calorie intake, but and I could have seen becoming

03:35:07.720 --> 03:35:14.720
[Guest]: fitter. But I could really optimize it if I knew that my my first class protein intake,

03:35:14.720 --> 03:35:21.020
[Guest]: for example, was very low. As a vegetarian, I have to make extra effort, of course. But

03:35:21.020 --> 03:35:26.020
[Guest]: so my learning was that that what are what are proteins, fats and carbs really doing

03:35:26.020 --> 03:35:33.800
[Guest]: on my plate and for me. And when I studied that, and I started applying that on my fitness

03:35:33.800 --> 03:35:39.920
[Guest]: routine, what then I started noticing was, first of all, you start getting a lot more

03:35:39.920 --> 03:35:48.560
[Guest]: stronger. And I could see that happen in the gym as well. And I did end up getting to a

03:35:48.560 --> 03:35:55.480
[Guest]: point where I was lifting 90 and 100 kilos. And if you looked at me, I look fairly lean,

03:35:55.480 --> 03:36:00.720
[Guest]: not not a very thin person, but also built, but you can't see the muscle kind of a thing.

03:36:00.720 --> 03:36:06.520
[Guest]: And you could see it when I'm exercising in the gym. And then I started seeing that I

03:36:06.520 --> 03:36:10.560
[Guest]: could do new new things that people couldn't and people who look cleaner than me in the

03:36:10.560 --> 03:36:15.400
[Guest]: gym, I'm, I was able to do things that they are not able to do, for example, pistol squats

03:36:15.400 --> 03:36:25.560
[Guest]: or squatting on a single leg. So that came from my nutrition, but also from exercising

03:36:25.560 --> 03:36:33.120
[Guest]: with pure science behind you. I mean, purely keeping science in mind when you are even

03:36:33.120 --> 03:36:40.080
[Guest]: planning your fitness regime, and then backing it up with nutrition so that you you get you

03:36:40.080 --> 03:36:46.360
[Guest]: see that that improvement. And so that was the difference. Initially, when I lost weight,

03:36:46.360 --> 03:36:53.600
[Guest]: it was purely calorie counting low fat. And I mean, I was happy doing it. In general,

03:36:53.600 --> 03:36:59.120
[Guest]: I was a lot more active. I was in Dubai. So you end up walking a lot. And I was very,

03:36:59.120 --> 03:37:06.160
[Guest]: I was doing volleyball very, very regularly when I was in Dubai. So lots and lots of exercising

03:37:06.160 --> 03:37:11.520
[Guest]: as such I was walking to work and walking back. So I guess all of that came together.

03:37:11.520 --> 03:37:19.960
[Guest]: So I became fitter. But it's only after I studied it that I saw gains in that sense

03:37:19.960 --> 03:37:26.440
[Guest]: of in my strength in my energy levels. So that was the difference a lot more educated

03:37:26.440 --> 03:37:28.440
[Guest]: approach.

03:37:28.440 --> 03:37:34.560
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that must be incredibly empowering. Because with everything else that I do, I

03:37:34.560 --> 03:37:39.240
[Amit Varma]: like to understand why the output is related to the input that I am doing this and therefore

03:37:39.240 --> 03:37:45.280
[Amit Varma]: something happens. And I feel for most of us with our own bodies. It is mysterious.

03:37:45.280 --> 03:37:49.200
[Amit Varma]: We don't know what's going on in there. We don't it absolutely is. Yeah, like, I was

03:37:49.200 --> 03:37:54.640
[Amit Varma]: diagnosed with type two diabetes last year. So recently, I got a continuous glucose monitor

03:37:54.640 --> 03:37:59.640
[Amit Varma]: from Freestyle Libra. And I was trying that out. And, you know, and my intention was always

03:37:59.640 --> 03:38:02.800
[Amit Varma]: that okay, I'm going to reverse this, I'm going to get back to keto and intermittent

03:38:02.800 --> 03:38:08.960
[Amit Varma]: and you can work out more and I can, as you've told me, but what gave me the ultimate Philip

03:38:08.960 --> 03:38:13.540
[Amit Varma]: to it was putting that continuous glucose monitor and just seeing that I have two slices

03:38:13.540 --> 03:38:20.400
[Amit Varma]: of toast and my blood sugar explodes. And, and I have a wholesome meal of bacon and eggs

03:38:20.400 --> 03:38:25.760
[Guest]: and lots of cheese. And I compared it, right? I compared it and my blood sugar didn't move.

03:38:25.760 --> 03:38:31.880
[Amit Varma]: The needle didn't move when I had a full packet of bacon and three eggs and lots of cheese

03:38:31.880 --> 03:38:37.200
[Amit Varma]: and the needle did not move when I have one slice of toast and the needle shoots up. Yeah.

03:38:37.200 --> 03:38:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And and it's so useful to be able to sort of, are you an optimist as I certainly am

03:38:42.640 --> 03:38:48.040
[Amit Varma]: about this kind of biohacking? Because I just... It's not biohacking though. Keto is not biohacking.

03:38:48.040 --> 03:38:51.720
[Amit Varma]: No, but I mean, things like CGM. So you get information about what's happening in your

03:38:51.720 --> 03:38:55.920
[Amit Varma]: own body and all of that. Maybe I use the wrong term. I don't know what's a good term

03:38:55.920 --> 03:39:02.400
[Guest]: for it. For experimenting with yourself. I mean, let's just call it that. Biohacking

03:39:02.400 --> 03:39:08.520
[Amit Varma]: in general, it can be quite a, quite a rabbit hole. Okay. So it's a fancy phrase like blockchain

03:39:08.520 --> 03:39:14.920
[Guest]: and so on. Yeah. Yeah. I mean, I guess biohacking is just you being open with your body and

03:39:14.920 --> 03:39:20.240
[Amit Varma]: testing things on your body. I mean, for example, another thing that I do, which the aggressively

03:39:20.240 --> 03:39:25.800
[Amit Varma]: conventional minded people argue about is I have Modafinil, right? I use it a lot. It's

03:39:25.800 --> 03:39:31.800
[Amit Varma]: like, it's a cognitive drug. It's like slightly more advanced, the next generation after Adderall

03:39:31.800 --> 03:39:35.920
[Amit Varma]: and so on. But I researched it heavily, went into Google Scholar, read all the papers,

03:39:35.920 --> 03:39:40.320
[Amit Varma]: realized it was completely safe. And now I use it on days where I really need to focus

03:39:40.320 --> 03:39:44.080
[Amit Varma]: and don't want to lose concentration, like today, because I have a recording. And I find

03:39:44.080 --> 03:39:49.240
[Amit Varma]: it is so way better than something like coffee. Coffee is an incredibly blunt tool. And Modafinil

03:39:49.240 --> 03:39:54.440
[Amit Varma]: just keeps your mind so alert and sharp, even when you're physically tired. And it's miraculous.

03:39:54.440 --> 03:39:58.520
[Amit Varma]: But whenever, but you know, when I mentioned I'm using it, one in four people will say,

03:39:58.520 --> 03:40:02.160
[Amit Varma]: oh, it is, it must be so dangerous and this and that. Sorry, carry on.

03:40:02.160 --> 03:40:10.080
[Guest]: Yeah, no, by I mean, people who are not quite used to people who do biohacking or experiments.

03:40:10.080 --> 03:40:15.400
[Guest]: And, you know, honestly, the people who are doing these experiments or who are biohacking

03:40:15.400 --> 03:40:21.400
[Guest]: and testing it on themselves are the most well informed. And I know a few others as

03:40:21.400 --> 03:40:28.360
[Guest]: well who have tested things on themselves, and they reveal things about their body. So

03:40:28.360 --> 03:40:35.120
[Guest]: honestly, like no comments on that. It's like a personal decision that people find something

03:40:35.120 --> 03:40:42.080
[Guest]: that works for them and probably research and convince themselves that it's safe enough.

03:40:42.080 --> 03:40:49.200
[Guest]: But when it comes to, for example, a keto diet, I would say that it's far too established

03:40:49.200 --> 03:40:53.960
[Amit Varma]: now to call it biohacking. I wasn't referring to keto, I was referring it to my getting

03:40:53.960 --> 03:40:59.160
[Guest]: my numbers about my blood sugar constantly. Exactly. And then coming to measuring each

03:40:59.160 --> 03:41:06.000
[Guest]: and everything. If you personally ask me, if you're generally convinced about the science,

03:41:06.000 --> 03:41:10.320
[Guest]: you don't have to measure anything every day, if it gives you some sort of a kick to measure

03:41:10.320 --> 03:41:16.360
[Guest]: it every day. And I would say I have friends who've experimented with a variety of food

03:41:16.360 --> 03:41:22.920
[Guest]: items and tested their blood glucose level and they wanted to see. I'm sure at some point

03:41:22.920 --> 03:41:27.800
[Guest]: of time, you would see that these results are not repeating themselves, you learned

03:41:27.800 --> 03:41:35.440
[Guest]: what you should. There is about 10 or 20 items that you end up eating in a week or two, typically,

03:41:35.440 --> 03:41:39.400
[Guest]: and you've tested all of them and then you've measured your blood glucose and at some point

03:41:39.400 --> 03:41:44.160
[Guest]: that whole energy level will be like, okay, I know this. You know, at that point, you

03:41:44.160 --> 03:41:50.720
[Guest]: can say that that glucometer has served its purpose. And it has taught you. It does. So

03:41:50.720 --> 03:41:58.040
[Guest]: I am completely for you learning or teaching yourself in the way that that works for you.

03:41:58.040 --> 03:42:04.160
[Guest]: Because I don't think that anybody is able to follow anything at all, regardless of nutrition,

03:42:04.160 --> 03:42:08.680
[Guest]: but any plan, if they have not questioned it enough, if they've not tested it enough,

03:42:08.680 --> 03:42:14.040
[Guest]: and if they have not grown their knowledge from where it was. And if I'm going to act

03:42:14.040 --> 03:42:17.920
[Guest]: like an instructor, and I'm going to give you a plan that's in the dark, and I'm going

03:42:17.920 --> 03:42:22.960
[Guest]: to be like, hey, just follow this plan. And then magically at the end of a month, you'll

03:42:22.960 --> 03:42:29.160
[Guest]: have seen some results. But if you if somebody else was to ask you, Amit, you're losing weight,

03:42:29.160 --> 03:42:32.720
[Guest]: what are you doing? And you're like, I don't know, my nutritionist gave me this plan. That's

03:42:32.720 --> 03:42:41.080
[Guest]: the worst outcome. In that sense. So I sort of feel quite passionate about the teaching

03:42:41.080 --> 03:42:48.640
[Guest]: part of nutrition than me writing a plan for somebody. Because it's easy to find a plan

03:42:48.640 --> 03:42:53.400
[Guest]: on the internet. It's not easy to find somebody who you can ask all your questions and for

03:42:53.400 --> 03:43:00.120
[Guest]: that person to be able to connect with you enough to explain the science behind it to

03:43:00.120 --> 03:43:04.400
[Guest]: you. And I guess that's why we end up paying nutritionists. We don't pay them because they're

03:43:04.400 --> 03:43:11.880
[Guest]: going to give some unique diet plan. And that's true for all famous nutritionists, everybody,

03:43:11.880 --> 03:43:16.120
[Guest]: people would, you know, really pay, find some amazing nutritionists and be like, okay, I'm

03:43:16.120 --> 03:43:20.040
[Guest]: going to pay her because I'm going to pay her 1 lakh rupees, 10 lakh rupees, 8 lakh

03:43:20.040 --> 03:43:28.080
[Guest]: rupees, whatever it is, she does some magic. No, the body works on science. And she doesn't

03:43:28.080 --> 03:43:35.160
[Guest]: have any magic pill. What differentiates one person from the other is who you connect with

03:43:35.160 --> 03:43:41.040
[Guest]: the most, who your personality connects with the most. Because when then that person is

03:43:41.040 --> 03:43:46.520
[Guest]: going to tell you what you should do, you're more likely to receive it. And when you're

03:43:46.520 --> 03:43:50.720
[Guest]: in that mindset, then you're going to follow it and then you're going to see results. I

03:43:50.720 --> 03:43:56.400
[Guest]: mean, that's my thought process about and then in terms of measuring, I think that the

03:43:56.400 --> 03:44:00.600
[Guest]: first month people end up measuring however many things they can measure. But once they

03:44:00.600 --> 03:44:04.560
[Guest]: start seeing some changes, then they are just convinced that all this is working and I'm

03:44:04.560 --> 03:44:11.040
[Guest]: not going to measure as much. Having said that, I would definitely say that people who

03:44:11.040 --> 03:44:19.000
[Guest]: are desperate to take fat burners, who are desperate to get on to creatine in the gym.

03:44:19.000 --> 03:44:24.560
[Guest]: These people need some more guidance and that these kinds of things are definitely not for

03:44:24.560 --> 03:44:33.560
[Guest]: everybody. And they are dosage specific and who can take them. For example, fat burners

03:44:33.560 --> 03:44:38.960
[Guest]: that are coffee based are not good for people who have heart conditions. They are not good

03:44:38.960 --> 03:44:46.320
[Guest]: for people who are on depression medication. And so when it comes to those kind of things,

03:44:46.320 --> 03:44:50.560
[Guest]: I would definitely say people need much more guidance.

03:44:50.560 --> 03:44:55.160
[Amit Varma]: And do you find people pushing back sometimes when you give some of this guidance because

03:44:55.160 --> 03:44:59.320
[Amit Varma]: some of it would, again, as we discussed, be contrary to what they would have learned

03:44:59.320 --> 03:45:01.320
[Amit Varma]: or even what their doctor would tell them?

03:45:01.320 --> 03:45:08.320
[Guest]: Yeah, they definitely push back and the unfortunate thing is everybody who comes to you already

03:45:08.320 --> 03:45:14.600
[Guest]: thinks that they know a lot of things. So you first have to listen to them. And then

03:45:14.600 --> 03:45:20.600
[Guest]: you have to slowly start explaining to them. Some of them might have the right notions

03:45:20.600 --> 03:45:25.840
[Guest]: as well. So you sort of say that, okay, these are the four or five things that I agree with

03:45:25.840 --> 03:45:30.160
[Guest]: you on. These are the four or five things that I have a different opinion on, without

03:45:30.160 --> 03:45:37.040
[Guest]: really saying that I disagree with what you believe in. And then there are some people

03:45:37.040 --> 03:45:44.080
[Guest]: who will sort of buy into what you have just said. I have a very long process of going

03:45:44.080 --> 03:45:49.400
[Guest]: into the science and I'm sort of trying to understand the people who've come to me

03:45:49.400 --> 03:45:54.200
[Guest]: and their patience levels and their interest levels. Because if they are not going to be

03:45:54.200 --> 03:45:59.720
[Guest]: in the mindset to learn, then there is no way I can write a plan for them that they

03:45:59.720 --> 03:46:04.680
[Guest]: are going to follow or really connect with or whatever. So sometimes I let people go

03:46:04.680 --> 03:46:11.740
[Guest]: as well. Sometimes people come with preconceived notions and then there have been times when

03:46:11.740 --> 03:46:17.280
[Guest]: people have come to me and said, oh, no, no, but all this is fine. But then we know somebody

03:46:17.280 --> 03:46:25.280
[Guest]: who gives this powder or whatever, and people have lost weight on that. And sometimes when

03:46:25.280 --> 03:46:28.800
[Guest]: I see that they're too convinced on this, and they're trying to give you this example

03:46:28.800 --> 03:46:35.480
[Guest]: because you're charging too much according to them. And then sometimes I tell them, okay,

03:46:35.480 --> 03:46:41.880
[Guest]: no. And then invariably they'll come back to me in a worse condition three months later.

03:46:41.880 --> 03:46:52.200
[Guest]: And of course, you don't say I told you so, but you did. So that makes your job even more

03:46:52.200 --> 03:46:57.120
[Guest]: difficult in that sense, because they've now come back to you at a worse point than

03:46:57.120 --> 03:46:59.880
[Amit Varma]: they were before. Since everybody listens to this podcast, they

03:46:59.880 --> 03:47:08.120
[Guest]: just heard you say I told you so. I know I did. No, it's true. And I find difficult

03:47:08.120 --> 03:47:12.800
[Guest]: this point very difficult when people come to us because people nowadays that are actually

03:47:12.800 --> 03:47:20.000
[Guest]: making the effort to come to your office and pay you a lot of money to get a diet plan,

03:47:20.000 --> 03:47:25.720
[Guest]: which perhaps is available on the internet, are actually coming to you for reasons way

03:47:25.720 --> 03:47:32.560
[Guest]: beyond that diet plan. And those reasons are that they don't have anybody to talk to. And

03:47:32.560 --> 03:47:37.880
[Guest]: the everything that's showing up on their body is actually a reason, is because of something

03:47:37.880 --> 03:47:46.040
[Guest]: else. And your job is really to make them comfortable and allow them to tell you what's

03:47:46.040 --> 03:47:57.760
[Guest]: bothering them. And I have had so many younger audiences, young adults who are on depression

03:47:57.760 --> 03:48:03.320
[Guest]: medication. And of course, you know, their psychiatrists or psychologists have told them

03:48:03.320 --> 03:48:08.640
[Guest]: that you know, start exercising, it will help you with your moods, it will help you to become

03:48:08.640 --> 03:48:16.200
[Guest]: fitter. Maybe it allows you to improve your self perception. It's like these side activities.

03:48:16.200 --> 03:48:23.160
[Guest]: But so this was the most revealing thing to me when I became a sports nutritionist, because

03:48:23.160 --> 03:48:28.980
[Guest]: I did not know that I signed up to partly become a counselor. I guess I accidentally

03:48:28.980 --> 03:48:34.440
[Guest]: got into it. Initially, I used to think that people are going to come and they're going

03:48:34.440 --> 03:48:38.960
[Guest]: to be like, okay, I've tried so and so things and I'm really confused because nothing's

03:48:38.960 --> 03:48:46.480
[Guest]: working. What is your advice, but it wasn't like that. So I've had I have had clients

03:48:46.480 --> 03:48:55.080
[Guest]: who have come to me and said that I cannot speak to my parents about my desires about

03:48:55.080 --> 03:49:02.560
[Guest]: my future. They're pushing me to be a CA, I want to be a filmmaker. And this is this

03:49:02.560 --> 03:49:10.640
[Guest]: is like 22, 21 year olds, and that friction in the house is causing a lot of pain in that

03:49:10.640 --> 03:49:17.200
[Guest]: relationship. And then the kid spends a lot of time outside, he's obviously depressed,

03:49:17.200 --> 03:49:27.280
[Guest]: he's also consuming a lot of food as a like we said, sugar is a is a addictive drug in

03:49:27.280 --> 03:49:34.800
[Guest]: that sense. And so it's not surprising that people turn to food when they are low. And

03:49:34.800 --> 03:49:39.260
[Guest]: then the parents at some point say that, okay, okay, now I'm going to take you spend a lot

03:49:39.260 --> 03:49:44.200
[Guest]: of money and take you to this nutritionist because you need to get fitter. And then you

03:49:44.200 --> 03:49:48.720
[Guest]: slowly start listening to them and you start realizing that these people's problems are

03:49:48.720 --> 03:49:55.040
[Guest]: something else, the whole exercise plan and all that they will follow. But the source

03:49:55.040 --> 03:50:00.280
[Guest]: of their pain, the whatever is showing up on their body is something else. And how do

03:50:00.280 --> 03:50:06.520
[Guest]: you sort of get through that person, tell them that, hey, I understand. But let's focus

03:50:06.520 --> 03:50:14.120
[Guest]: on the fitness at this moment, and then try and build trust with them. And I have also

03:50:14.120 --> 03:50:19.920
[Guest]: had, for example, a mother brought her her son to me two, three years ago, and he was

03:50:19.920 --> 03:50:27.440
[Guest]: 24 years old. And he was some 101 kilos or something like that. He didn't look very large,

03:50:27.440 --> 03:50:33.520
[Guest]: but he yeah, he could do with losing some 10-20 kilos. With most people that come to

03:50:33.520 --> 03:50:40.440
[Guest]: me, I first say that I want to see your lipid profile and I want to prescribe them a few

03:50:40.440 --> 03:50:46.760
[Guest]: blood tests and I want to see what's going on inside. Outside ka toh I can see. And then

03:50:46.760 --> 03:50:53.080
[Guest]: when they came back with the blood test, I realized he's pre-diabetic and he's only 24.

03:50:53.080 --> 03:50:58.800
[Guest]: And so I started explaining to the mother that, hey, this is what it is. I mean, he

03:50:58.800 --> 03:51:03.680
[Guest]: really has to take care of his health now so that it doesn't turn into a full-fledged

03:51:03.680 --> 03:51:08.560
[Guest]: type 2 diabetes and it's too early for this to happen and it's lifestyle thing, it can

03:51:08.560 --> 03:51:15.360
[Guest]: be reversed, all this, all that. And after listening to me say all of this, this lady

03:51:15.360 --> 03:51:22.800
[Guest]: says to me, listen, he needs to lose 20 kilos. How can I register his profile on this matrimonial

03:51:22.800 --> 03:51:32.800
[Guest]: site because I cannot put 101 kilos there. And I want to register him. And for a moment,

03:51:32.800 --> 03:51:37.640
[Guest]: I didn't know what to say to her because I was like, you know, honestly, this should

03:51:37.640 --> 03:51:44.160
[Guest]: be the least of your worries. But then the guy was, I sort of became good friends with

03:51:44.160 --> 03:51:48.920
[Guest]: the guy and he followed my diet plan, he lost weight and all of that. And he was quite excited

03:51:48.920 --> 03:51:53.800
[Guest]: about it. But that's what I'm telling you, that there's such a disconnect between what

03:51:53.800 --> 03:52:01.000
[Guest]: the children want, what the parents want, what there's such, there's the communication

03:52:01.000 --> 03:52:08.600
[Guest]: between parents and children is broken right now and how. I had another person who came

03:52:08.600 --> 03:52:16.480
[Guest]: to me, he was 16 years old. And casually while talking to me, he was like, oh, I take sleeping

03:52:16.480 --> 03:52:23.360
[Guest]: pills. And casually. And I said, how do you have access to sleeping pills? And oh no,

03:52:23.360 --> 03:52:28.680
[Guest]: I was depressed when I was in 8th standard and then my parents are doctors. So they said,

03:52:28.680 --> 03:52:33.800
[Guest]: no, no, take this, this is mild and you'll get good sleep. And then I sometimes keep

03:52:33.800 --> 03:52:41.960
[Guest]: it and then sometimes I take it. And I was shocked because he was just making it sound

03:52:41.960 --> 03:52:46.760
[Guest]: like it's normal. And then sometimes you have to stop yourself as well because somebody

03:52:46.760 --> 03:52:51.440
[Guest]: strikes such connect with you because they're not able to talk to their parents that they

03:52:51.440 --> 03:52:58.800
[Guest]: think that their biggest problems or deepest desires can be shared with their nutritionist.

03:52:58.800 --> 03:53:02.560
[Guest]: So this person comes and tells me at some point, he's like, no, no, I really want to

03:53:02.560 --> 03:53:08.080
[Guest]: talk to you. And I was like, okay, fine. And then he was like, I'm addicted to porn. And

03:53:08.080 --> 03:53:13.640
[Guest]: I'm just sitting there and looking like what did I mean, I'm a sports nutritionist. And

03:53:13.640 --> 03:53:17.520
[Guest]: then of course at that by that by then you're experienced enough to say, hey, you know,

03:53:17.520 --> 03:53:23.320
[Guest]: I will refer you to somebody. And of course, I knew some people that I referred him to.

03:53:23.320 --> 03:53:29.000
[Guest]: But it reveals what's the problem with people. And a lot of it is communication. It's to

03:53:29.000 --> 03:53:36.040
[Guest]: do with the fact that we are so intolerant, we are so isolated in the society today that

03:53:36.040 --> 03:53:42.040
[Guest]: nobody has the time, not even your parents to really sit and understand from you what's

03:53:42.040 --> 03:53:47.240
[Guest]: happening in your life. What is it that you're happy about? What is it that you're unhappy

03:53:47.240 --> 03:53:51.760
[Guest]: about? Is there something they can do to help? But instead, a lot of parents would come at

03:53:51.760 --> 03:53:58.480
[Guest]: their children with their desires. You know, the child's expectations or experiences of

03:53:58.480 --> 03:54:05.640
[Guest]: their life are going in a different direction. And parents have absolutely no appetite to

03:54:05.640 --> 03:54:11.240
[Guest]: understand their children anymore. And they have a lot of money to pay nutritionist. Ki

03:54:11.240 --> 03:54:16.840
[Guest]: kisi aur ko aapka problem solve karne do. I will go pay them. I will take you to a psychologist.

03:54:16.840 --> 03:54:21.240
[Guest]: I will take you to a nutritionist. All that is wonderful. And it's needed. I don't say

03:54:21.240 --> 03:54:28.960
[Guest]: that parents should take things in their own hands. But in terms of understanding your

03:54:28.960 --> 03:54:34.520
[Guest]: own children, it's just, it's an it's a non negotiable thing, I think.

03:54:34.520 --> 03:54:39.640
[Amit Varma]: This is such a great insight about sometimes matters that seem to do with nutrition go

03:54:39.640 --> 03:54:41.480
[Amit Varma]: much deeper than that. And I'm just thinking of

03:54:41.480 --> 03:54:47.480
[Guest]: They almost always do. The people who have just, you know, just recently gained 8-10

03:54:47.480 --> 03:54:51.800
[Guest]: kilos or generally are active, they are not the ones who will come and pay you. They'll

03:54:51.800 --> 03:54:56.440
[Guest]: be they'll find some diet plan online, and they'll be fine with it. But the ones that

03:54:56.440 --> 03:55:01.720
[Amit Varma]: come to you have a lot, lot of deep issues. No, and I just think of that kid whose mother

03:55:01.720 --> 03:55:06.520
[Amit Varma]: wanted him to lose 20 kgs so she can put his picture on a matrimonial profile. And I'm

03:55:06.520 --> 03:55:10.040
[Amit Varma]: just thinking that my God, if I was a young man, and my mother was like that, of course,

03:55:10.040 --> 03:55:15.440
[Amit Varma]: I would eat pizza all day. Aur kya hai? You know, it's, it's, so here's a question what

03:55:15.440 --> 03:55:21.480
[Amit Varma]: you've pointed to is both something that's forever been there, that is parents imposing

03:55:21.480 --> 03:55:26.400
[Amit Varma]: their desires on their children and putting that pressure and so on. And, you know, not

03:55:26.400 --> 03:55:31.600
[Amit Varma]: allowing their kids enough agency. And that's always been a problem in India. And also something

03:55:31.600 --> 03:55:38.600
[Amit Varma]: that might be something that is exacerbated in modern times, which is that level of disconnect,

03:55:38.600 --> 03:55:44.560
[Amit Varma]: where a young person may feel that she has no one to talk to, that there's no connection

03:55:44.560 --> 03:55:49.680
[Amit Varma]: with the parents. And perhaps I can understand this friend could be with, this young person

03:55:49.680 --> 03:55:52.840
[Amit Varma]: could be with her friends in a cafe, and they're all looking into the smartphones and not into

03:55:52.840 --> 03:55:58.160
[Amit Varma]: each other's eyes and actually having a human conversation. So do you think that that specific

03:55:58.160 --> 03:56:03.520
[Amit Varma]: kind of disconnect is a greater problem today than it used to be once? Oh, I absolutely

03:56:03.520 --> 03:56:11.480
[Guest]: think so. Because, I mean, this happened, I was in a class of some 30-40 people recently

03:56:11.480 --> 03:56:19.480
[Guest]: and in some lecture, they said that, okay, list down a few people that you are closest

03:56:19.480 --> 03:56:24.960
[Guest]: to. And we would imagine that a lot of people will come up with five people that are like

03:56:24.960 --> 03:56:29.840
[Guest]: really, really valuable to them. But not a lot of people have so many people in their

03:56:29.840 --> 03:56:37.560
[Guest]: life that they completely trust with. And some of them have nobody. And I definitely

03:56:37.560 --> 03:56:44.880
[Guest]: think that with youngsters of today, I think the fact that they have nobody to talk to

03:56:44.880 --> 03:56:55.320
[Guest]: is one thing. But also, I think they're bombarded with so much so early, in terms of any topic

03:56:55.320 --> 03:57:03.280
[Guest]: that they don't know how to process anymore. And that I think is a fundamental problem.

03:57:03.280 --> 03:57:10.040
[Guest]: I think it was, to some extent, I find it good, if you have sort of a military type

03:57:10.040 --> 03:57:14.000
[Guest]: thinking where you're like, okay, I do this, I do this, I do this, and at some point life

03:57:14.000 --> 03:57:19.920
[Guest]: works out. But today, if you have a mobile phone at the age of 10 and 12 and 13, and

03:57:19.920 --> 03:57:26.320
[Guest]: you're being exposed to so much information that perhaps you don't even need. I mean,

03:57:26.320 --> 03:57:30.360
[Guest]: think about adults as well, right? People are finding it difficult to keep up with the

03:57:30.360 --> 03:57:36.760
[Guest]: information overload on Twitter. And these are adults. And if you have given a phone

03:57:36.760 --> 03:57:46.360
[Guest]: to children, teenage people who are on Instagram, what is their self-image going to turn out

03:57:46.360 --> 03:57:53.480
[Guest]: to be? And then, because you have Netflix, because you have, and they have on average

03:57:53.480 --> 03:57:59.200
[Guest]: more money than I think most of us had, at least the city goers, so they know how to

03:57:59.200 --> 03:58:07.840
[Guest]: spend it to get instant gratification. They are not having to turn to each other to, like

03:58:07.840 --> 03:58:13.920
[Guest]: I said, we were climbing up the Take D and then going and skating and all of that. I

03:58:13.920 --> 03:58:21.600
[Guest]: don't think these folks are doing that anymore. And so, right from childhood, what are the

03:58:21.600 --> 03:58:26.760
[Guest]: quality of relations you're carrying with you through your life? And the opportunities

03:58:26.760 --> 03:58:33.400
[Guest]: to build those strong relations are going to only keep going down, because your own

03:58:33.400 --> 03:58:40.320
[Guest]: effort is going to be less sometimes, opportunities are going to be less, or just because you

03:58:40.320 --> 03:58:47.240
[Guest]: are not around as many people as you would like to connect with. So yeah, I definitely

03:58:47.240 --> 03:58:56.520
[Guest]: feel they are disconnected, not only because of social media or so, but also I think the

03:58:56.520 --> 03:59:04.640
[Guest]: quality of conversations, what's happening in the country, the fact that there's this

03:59:04.640 --> 03:59:10.920
[Guest]: random mix of you're all going to good schools, but also schools are trying to put in a variety

03:59:10.920 --> 03:59:16.760
[Guest]: of ideas in people's minds. I was just speaking to a friend of mine whose young daughter started

03:59:16.760 --> 03:59:25.040
[Guest]: going to school, and apparently the school has said that we want equality, so we have

03:59:25.040 --> 03:59:32.640
[Guest]: the same shirt and pant dresses for guys and girls. And now here I'm thinking that is this

03:59:32.640 --> 03:59:38.440
[Guest]: an expression of equality that, okay, the girls will not have a pinafore and sash anymore,

03:59:38.440 --> 03:59:45.640
[Guest]: is that an expression of, and then how is a pant and shirt for a girl and a boy an expression

03:59:45.640 --> 03:59:48.520
[Guest]: of equality, if you're taking it from what men wear?

03:59:48.520 --> 03:59:50.400
[Guest]: Why not a pinafore for both?

03:59:50.400 --> 03:59:59.240
[Guest]: So, I feel like there's a mix of schools trying to try different things, and also sometimes

03:59:59.240 --> 04:00:06.960
[Guest]: going overboard, I think. Because I remember when we were growing up, we used to, I mean,

04:00:06.960 --> 04:00:12.480
[Guest]: I've gone to all these random places for my sport tournaments and stuff, and not once

04:00:12.480 --> 04:00:16.520
[Guest]: were our parents really bothered about what's going on, they would trust the school teacher

04:00:16.520 --> 04:00:21.520
[Guest]: that's going with us, and then let things happen. And they would just be like, okay,

04:00:21.520 --> 04:00:30.480
[Guest]: this is your 2000 rupees for your 3-4 days trip, and go have fun. And also you're not

04:00:30.480 --> 04:00:35.400
[Guest]: constantly in touch with them, you come back and you have things to talk about. Nowadays

04:00:35.400 --> 04:00:39.920
[Guest]: there's nothing like that. What do you connect with? You're constantly connected, what do

04:00:39.920 --> 04:00:49.120
[Guest]: you update them with? If you're going to talk to your parents, or your friends. So, yeah,

04:00:49.120 --> 04:00:51.200
[Guest]: that's my general thought process.

04:00:51.200 --> 04:00:56.200
[Amit Varma]: The Japanese have this lovely word called hikikomori, which is hikikomori are those

04:00:56.200 --> 04:01:02.400
[Amit Varma]: people who, those young people who don't see the outside world. So they live in their rooms,

04:01:02.400 --> 04:01:05.520
[Amit Varma]: and they might do whatever they do in their rooms, but they never come out, and the parents

04:01:05.520 --> 04:01:10.120
[Amit Varma]: will often just leave food outside their door, and they won't interact, and they just live

04:01:10.120 --> 04:01:15.840
[Amit Varma]: this completely solitary existence. The Japanese have a special term for it because those people

04:01:15.840 --> 04:01:21.840
[Amit Varma]: are outliers, different from everyone else. And I wonder if you're all turning into hikikomori

04:01:21.840 --> 04:01:26.640
[Amit Varma]: in modern times, and just thinking aloud, the danger there is this, that we can discuss

04:01:26.640 --> 04:01:31.320
[Amit Varma]: two kinds of addiction, and one is the addiction of sugar, and the other is the addiction of

04:01:31.320 --> 04:01:37.200
[Amit Varma]: say social media, right? And the addiction of sugar has outward signs, you know, when

04:01:37.200 --> 04:01:41.000
[Amit Varma]: things are going wrong, first, you get fat, then you'll get prediabetes, heart trouble,

04:01:41.000 --> 04:01:44.620
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah, everything goes wrong, then you go to a nutritionist like yourself and

04:01:44.620 --> 04:01:48.840
[Amit Varma]: tell them not just what your weight loss problems are, but all problems about your life, because

04:01:48.840 --> 04:01:53.960
[Amit Varma]: hey, what are nutritionists for? But there are outward signs of that addiction. And you

04:01:53.960 --> 04:01:59.000
[Amit Varma]: can figure out that, yeah, okay, this is because of sugar, this is how we fix it. But this

04:01:59.000 --> 04:02:05.160
[Amit Varma]: other addiction, I don't know what outward signs there are of it. These outward signs

04:02:05.160 --> 04:02:10.360
[Amit Varma]: are things that we observe in people like Jonathan Haidt famously said that, you know,

04:02:10.360 --> 04:02:13.800
[Amit Varma]: even though you have all the knowledge in the world available to you through the internet,

04:02:13.800 --> 04:02:18.200
[Amit Varma]: everybody's consuming what was produced in the last three days. It's one sensation after

04:02:18.200 --> 04:02:23.360
[Amit Varma]: another, after another, after another. All day, I might read 800 tweets and forget them

04:02:23.360 --> 04:02:29.760
[Amit Varma]: all by the time tomorrow comes around. Right? And the dangerous ways in which this harms

04:02:29.760 --> 04:02:34.760
[Amit Varma]: us as people, which will also show up physically, of course, as you pointed out, there are those

04:02:34.760 --> 04:02:39.200
[Amit Varma]: outward signs and those direct connections aren't there anymore. So I'm just kind of

04:02:39.200 --> 04:02:43.560
[Amit Varma]: thinking aloud. But you know, is this something that sort of worries you? Because at least

04:02:43.560 --> 04:02:49.320
[Amit Varma]: in terms of social media addiction, you've sort of stayed away, you are on Twitter. And,

04:02:49.320 --> 04:02:53.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, many of the people you might read or see around you are like that, but you've

04:02:53.360 --> 04:02:59.640
[Guest]: kind of stayed away. So what are your thoughts? So I think for me, Amit, the worst part of

04:02:59.640 --> 04:03:05.960
[Guest]: social media is valid seeking validation. Yeah, that's literally the worst part. I mean,

04:03:05.960 --> 04:03:11.160
[Guest]: you could, you could surf and you could see tweets and endlessly and yeah, I mean, you

04:03:11.160 --> 04:03:16.360
[Guest]: don't want to spend as much time on it. But I don't. I mean, that comes sec, that is secondary

04:03:16.360 --> 04:03:23.480
[Guest]: for me, as much as this validation, how many people liked my photo or didn't like me, how

04:03:23.480 --> 04:03:29.360
[Guest]: many wished me birthday or didn't wish me birthday. And I can imagine that if adults

04:03:29.360 --> 04:03:35.640
[Guest]: are also thinking about these things, then a teenager is really getting affected by it.

04:03:35.640 --> 04:03:40.960
[Guest]: How many friends followed me, how many didn't, and then there may be young people's power

04:03:40.960 --> 04:03:46.880
[Guest]: dynamics in it, whose boyfriend and girlfriend or ex-boyfriend, girlfriend follow each other.

04:03:46.880 --> 04:03:56.000
[Guest]: And I guess, then that discussion must be spilling into their class conversations, in-person

04:03:56.000 --> 04:03:59.680
[Guest]: conversations. And then what is the depth of those conversations? What, what, how do

04:03:59.680 --> 04:04:05.960
[Guest]: you grow? Like when we were growing up, in the evenings, we would go for walks with our

04:04:05.960 --> 04:04:12.280
[Guest]: friends, and that would bring up a variety of topics. And today, I don't know what these

04:04:12.280 --> 04:04:18.560
[Guest]: guys must be talking about. And if they have, they already have access to phones and, and

04:04:18.560 --> 04:04:25.240
[Guest]: all kinds of apps, then what, when, where is the time to talk about books? Where is

04:04:25.240 --> 04:04:38.160
[Guest]: the time to read poetry or, or discuss a film that you've seen? So, you know, your, your

04:04:38.160 --> 04:04:43.640
[Guest]: worldview is not being shaped, you're just being bombarded with information. And you're

04:04:43.640 --> 04:04:50.000
[Guest]: having surface level conversations based on that. And then I guess at some point, the

04:04:50.000 --> 04:04:55.080
[Guest]: realities of life just come at you. And then you feel like you've not thought about them

04:04:55.080 --> 04:05:02.160
[Guest]: at all, or you are not slowly onboarded into what's coming. But that's my thought, thoughts

04:05:02.160 --> 04:05:03.160
[Guest]: about it.

04:05:03.160 --> 04:05:07.200
[Amit Varma]: No, and, and, you know, one of the other themes that hate talks about, and various people

04:05:07.200 --> 04:05:14.760
[Amit Varma]: have spoken about, is there's been this growing rate of female teen suicides in the US. And,

04:05:14.760 --> 04:05:18.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, hate and others link it directly to social media in the sense that, you know,

04:05:18.920 --> 04:05:22.780
[Amit Varma]: a decade and a half ago, people were worried about what would happen to young boys because

04:05:22.780 --> 04:05:27.220
[Amit Varma]: of video games. And as it turned out, nothing at all. Video games were good for young boys

04:05:27.220 --> 04:05:30.680
[Amit Varma]: because I learned problem solving and all of those things, and it didn't harm them in

04:05:30.680 --> 04:05:34.380
[Amit Varma]: any way didn't make them more violent. But what happened to young girls because of social

04:05:34.380 --> 04:05:41.560
[Amit Varma]: media is that they became sort of slaves of this desire to seek validation, as you put

04:05:41.560 --> 04:05:46.240
[Amit Varma]: it, like earlier, the girls would hang around outside school or go for walks, like you said,

04:05:46.240 --> 04:05:49.600
[Amit Varma]: and they would talk about this, and they would talk about that, and so on and so forth. But

04:05:49.600 --> 04:05:55.840
[Amit Varma]: now everyone's got an Instagram presence in there. And Instagram always, you know, doesn't

04:05:55.840 --> 04:05:59.920
[Amit Varma]: show the real you, it shows a you that you want to project out to the world. And then

04:05:59.920 --> 04:06:07.800
[Amit Varma]: everybody is, is making their real self compete with these projected selves of all their peers.

04:06:07.800 --> 04:06:11.960
[Amit Varma]: And it is in that sense, a race into to the bottom race to a very dark place where you're

04:06:11.960 --> 04:06:18.560
[Amit Varma]: always posturing, posturing, signaling, signaling, and, and a lot of female depression and teen

04:06:18.560 --> 04:06:23.440
[Amit Varma]: suicides and all of that have been attributed to that. It's it's kind of an ongoing debate.

04:06:23.440 --> 04:06:27.200
[Amit Varma]: I think there was an internal Facebook survey, if I remember correctly, which actually backed

04:06:27.200 --> 04:06:32.360
[Amit Varma]: this up, but they suppress the survey, which is quite what you would expect. And that's

04:06:32.360 --> 04:06:36.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of tragic. And then as you say that if it's going to show up in things like depression

04:06:36.560 --> 04:06:41.160
[Amit Varma]: and suicide, it is also going to show up in what they eat and how they eat and their bodies

04:06:41.160 --> 04:06:45.360
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. So, so good for you, your market is growing.

04:06:45.360 --> 04:06:51.760
[Guest]: Oh, my God, I trust me. It's not, it's not a pleasant thing. Because if we weren't dealing

04:06:51.760 --> 04:06:58.000
[Guest]: with such grave and fundamental health issues, we would probably be discussing about how

04:06:58.000 --> 04:07:04.560
[Guest]: science can advance our abilities in general. I mean, look at athletics, where has it gone?

04:07:04.560 --> 04:07:10.680
[Guest]: I mean, how is Djokovic and how is Nadal able, how are they able to perform at the level

04:07:10.680 --> 04:07:18.800
[Guest]: that they are at 34 and 35? I mean, we would probably be digging more into that or challenging

04:07:18.800 --> 04:07:26.840
[Guest]: Djokovic on his water has power theories, if nothing else. But the other side of this,

04:07:26.840 --> 04:07:34.480
[Guest]: I mean, this whole rising cases of depression are a grave worry, I guess, to the society

04:07:34.480 --> 04:07:40.760
[Guest]: and then addictions. I mean, there's no end to addictions. Like, sometimes I think that

04:07:40.760 --> 04:07:45.720
[Guest]: when we think about addictions, we are talking about smoking and drinking. And I'm like,

04:07:45.720 --> 04:07:51.160
[Guest]: you know what, those are the known ones. Those are the ones that you've heard about all the

04:07:51.160 --> 04:07:57.240
[Guest]: time. But sometimes you have to be truthful to yourself. And if I ask you, can you go

04:07:57.240 --> 04:08:02.240
[Guest]: without your tea, morning tea and coffee? Are you going to be able to do it? Are you

04:08:02.240 --> 04:08:07.200
[Guest]: going to be able to, as a challenge, forget if you're doing keto diet or not, give up

04:08:07.200 --> 04:08:14.140
[Guest]: your roti and rice and dals for a week? We don't even know we are addicted to so many

04:08:14.140 --> 04:08:19.680
[Guest]: things that we are. And we end up talking about alcohol and smoking, which are sure,

04:08:19.680 --> 04:08:24.400
[Guest]: but sometimes it's better to know that these are addictions and get into it or get off

04:08:24.400 --> 04:08:31.640
[Guest]: it knowing that they are addictions than the other ones that are the slow poison in that

04:08:31.640 --> 04:08:37.000
[Guest]: sense. And which is why we are turning a lot of people are eating a lot of food when they

04:08:37.000 --> 04:08:42.120
[Amit Varma]: are depressed, which is also an addiction. Yeah, yeah, absolutely wise words. And I see

04:08:42.120 --> 04:08:46.840
[Amit Varma]: different addictions in myself, for example, you know, social media, for example, you know,

04:08:46.840 --> 04:08:51.040
[Amit Varma]: and you absolutely like about valid, right about validation in the sense that, you know,

04:08:51.040 --> 04:08:55.720
[Amit Varma]: the Facebook like button and the Twitter retweet, not so much the like, but more the Twitter

04:08:55.720 --> 04:09:00.880
[Amit Varma]: retweet just incredibly toxic. So there was talk about how if Musk ends up buying Twitter,

04:09:00.880 --> 04:09:05.600
[Amit Varma]: he might, you know, get rid of the retweet button, and he's not buying it as we now know,

04:09:05.600 --> 04:09:09.160
[Amit Varma]: and they won't get rid of the retweet button because they want to maximize engagement.

04:09:09.160 --> 04:09:12.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's what kind of does that. But let's let's move on to talking about positive things

04:09:12.960 --> 04:09:18.160
[Amit Varma]: like you said, so tell me a bit about your startup. How did you conceive of it when you

04:09:18.160 --> 04:09:23.640
[Amit Varma]: started thinking about it? And what did it evolve into as you eventually did your certification

04:09:23.640 --> 04:09:29.080
[Amit Varma]: did your course, went to Thailand and had your experiences and, you know, beat up people

04:09:29.080 --> 04:09:34.560
[Amit Varma]: box them on the streets, you know, demolished big men with tattoos into street fight. You

04:09:34.560 --> 04:09:41.040
[Amit Varma]: got into street fights? No. I wish I had a story for you. I was hopeful, you know, something

04:09:41.040 --> 04:09:49.880
[Guest]: for a moment. I've gotten into duels on during my Muay Thai classes, but nothing on the streets,

04:09:49.880 --> 04:10:00.160
[Amit Varma]: really. Yeah, so tell me about your startup. So yeah, the whole idea about that I have

04:10:00.160 --> 04:10:07.240
[Guest]: for my startup actually came to me when I was living in Dubai. And this was around 2015

04:10:07.240 --> 04:10:14.400
[Guest]: and 16. And these fitness apps were really coming into the market, the online fitness

04:10:14.400 --> 04:10:22.680
[Guest]: system, the whole app system. I had started following a trainer from the US called Jillian

04:10:22.680 --> 04:10:31.040
[Guest]: Michaels because she was from I think what you've heard from me so far. You can from

04:10:31.040 --> 04:10:36.960
[Guest]: that you can guess that I like trainers that are quite hard on their subjects. And she

04:10:36.960 --> 04:10:42.960
[Guest]: was a trainer on The Biggest Loser, the program from the US and I had watched it a few times

04:10:42.960 --> 04:10:48.960
[Guest]: and I was quite inspired by her style of training. And then she had come out with an app which

04:10:48.960 --> 04:10:56.520
[Guest]: did exercise videos and some diet guidelines and stuff. And I started following it and

04:10:56.520 --> 04:11:03.040
[Guest]: I was seeing a lot of progress. I was losing weight and I was really becoming a lot fitter.

04:11:03.040 --> 04:11:11.080
[Guest]: But the only thing I used to constantly feel is that the food that was suggested was not

04:11:11.080 --> 04:11:18.640
[Guest]: suitable to my Indian vegetarian preferences. And then I started thinking about it and I

04:11:18.640 --> 04:11:25.680
[Guest]: was like, hey, I want to build something where the exercises that I'm suggesting and the

04:11:25.680 --> 04:11:31.840
[Guest]: personalized food plans that I give with it are suited to the Indian audience. Because

04:11:31.840 --> 04:11:37.800
[Guest]: there is no point exercising if you have no guidance on the food that you should be eating

04:11:37.800 --> 04:11:44.960
[Guest]: and you're not going to see results with that approach that I will just follow the exercise

04:11:44.960 --> 04:11:50.640
[Guest]: and I will eat what I feel like or what I know about. I will follow whatever I know

04:11:50.640 --> 04:11:59.240
[Guest]: about fitness and nutrition. So I decided that I wanted to build an online platform

04:11:59.240 --> 04:12:11.120
[Guest]: that has a variety of exercises and a nutrition plan to go with it for the Indian folk. And

04:12:11.120 --> 04:12:20.120
[Guest]: so I built a platform which now has over 140 exercise videos and over 400 food items, each

04:12:20.120 --> 04:12:27.560
[Guest]: of them broken down into proteins, fats and carbs and calories and further guidance on

04:12:27.560 --> 04:12:35.000
[Guest]: whether we recommend that item or not. And so it's really a platform that I have built

04:12:35.000 --> 04:12:40.120
[Guest]: to educate, I think, people more than just tell them that this is what you should do

04:12:40.120 --> 04:12:47.480
[Guest]: to lose weight or so or to achieve your fitness goals. Because if you look at the exercise

04:12:47.480 --> 04:12:53.560
[Guest]: videos that we have, and it's called Halomi Fitness, by the way, H-A-L-O-M-I, and that's

04:12:53.560 --> 04:12:59.400
[Guest]: because I thought of it when I was in Dubai. And I was introduced to Halomi cheese there

04:12:59.400 --> 04:13:06.600
[Guest]: and cheese is a healthy protein item and then I wanted to bring it into my startup. So that's

04:13:06.600 --> 04:13:13.600
[Guest]: why it's called Halomi. But so my idea was to educate people and the videos that I have

04:13:13.600 --> 04:13:18.360
[Guest]: there talk about if you're doing this exercise, if you're doing a squat, for example, which

04:13:18.360 --> 04:13:23.040
[Guest]: muscle is it exercising, it has a voiceover that talks to you about the importance of

04:13:23.040 --> 04:13:28.160
[Guest]: that exercise. And they are only 30 second videos, but they still educate you. And my

04:13:28.160 --> 04:13:34.280
[Guest]: whole idea was that the the platform has a lot of tips on the on the questions that people

04:13:34.280 --> 04:13:41.600
[Guest]: have about pre workout and post workout food. I mean supplements and all those things, including

04:13:41.600 --> 04:13:48.600
[Guest]: the nutrition plan. And what I I sort of tried to do with my platform was even when it comes

04:13:48.600 --> 04:13:56.360
[Guest]: to the nutrition plan, what people struggle with with the apps is that if we suggest something

04:13:56.360 --> 04:14:04.080
[Guest]: to you, and you don't like it, then what happens? I asked you to eat something and you don't

04:14:04.080 --> 04:14:08.920
[Guest]: have it at home or you don't like it. And so we provide a lot of replacement options

04:14:08.920 --> 04:14:13.960
[Guest]: as well. So so that nobody feels like, hey, I'm cornered. You're asking me to eat this

04:14:13.960 --> 04:14:20.640
[Guest]: and I don't have it. So people have found that useful as well. And I've, I launched

04:14:20.640 --> 04:14:27.500
[Guest]: it in 2018. And it's completely bootstrapped at the moment. And at some point, hopefully,

04:14:27.500 --> 04:14:34.320
[Guest]: I will raise funding for it. But what I have found with people is the best thing that you

04:14:34.320 --> 04:14:41.400
[Guest]: can provide people is a plan to follow because a lot of people have the motivation to exercise.

04:14:41.400 --> 04:14:49.080
[Guest]: But what's the most tiring part is to to get out there and start thinking now what should

04:14:49.080 --> 04:14:57.080
[Guest]: I do? And if you solve that problem for people that hey, don't think just wear your your

04:14:57.080 --> 04:15:02.080
[Guest]: your fitness gear, and you have a plan that you need to follow. So this is really for

04:15:02.080 --> 04:15:08.760
[Guest]: people who find who understand that they have to be fit, who are willing to put in the work,

04:15:08.760 --> 04:15:13.880
[Guest]: but who are like, hey, I it matters to me that I know that I'm following something that

04:15:13.880 --> 04:15:20.600
[Guest]: is optimized for me. And then I will fully trust it. And I will open the app and I don't

04:15:20.600 --> 04:15:24.880
[Guest]: mind looking at it and following it. So this is really for those people who are aware but

04:15:24.880 --> 04:15:33.280
[Guest]: who want to be guided. So that's what my app, a web app, we have a web app. So you have

04:15:33.280 --> 04:15:39.600
[Guest]: to go through it's like a website, basically. And that's what we're trying to do, educate

04:15:39.600 --> 04:15:47.240
[Guest]: people and let them ask us questions, if they have any. And hopefully they carry forward

04:15:47.240 --> 04:15:52.080
[Guest]: all the learning that they've had at the end of the program. Because if we have not taught

04:15:52.080 --> 04:15:59.100
[Guest]: them enough, then we have not won with them. For us winning is is not that you have now

04:15:59.100 --> 04:16:04.640
[Guest]: lost weight or whatever, but you feel confident about what you've learned. If I have, if I

04:16:04.640 --> 04:16:11.160
[Guest]: ask you later on, how does paneer help you or so, you should have an opinion about it.

04:16:11.160 --> 04:16:16.200
[Guest]: If I ask you to tell me a little bit more about rice or so you should have learned something

04:16:16.200 --> 04:16:22.840
[Guest]: in those two, three months with us. And only then I can be sure that I've changed something

04:16:22.840 --> 04:16:29.720
[Guest]: fundamentally in how you will lead in your life. So that that's the whole idea.

04:16:29.720 --> 04:16:35.040
[Amit Varma]: No, that's great. And you asked a hypothetical question, how will paneer help you and I instantly

04:16:35.040 --> 04:16:39.040
[Amit Varma]: thought of Siddhant Vadukut. Those who know him will know what I mean. You know what I

04:16:39.040 --> 04:16:43.320
[Amit Varma]: kind of like about that approach, like even when I teach my writing course, for example,

04:16:43.320 --> 04:16:47.520
[Amit Varma]: the very first thing I talk about is that I am not going to give you a dogmatic list

04:16:47.520 --> 04:16:51.940
[Amit Varma]: of do's and don'ts, like don't use adverbs, don't use cliches, all of that. The 10 commandments

04:16:51.940 --> 04:16:58.020
[Amit Varma]: of bad writing according to Sri Sri Amit Verma, as it were. But instead, just talk about first

04:16:58.020 --> 04:17:02.520
[Amit Varma]: principles and build from there. So ultimately, you become your own mentor and you become

04:17:02.520 --> 04:17:07.320
[Amit Varma]: your own coach. And you know, you might still need other people to talk to and to drive

04:17:07.320 --> 04:17:11.840
[Amit Varma]: you. But intellectually, at least you know you're able to. Much in the same way as you

04:17:11.840 --> 04:17:16.440
[Amit Varma]: know, a good chess coach won't make you mug up moves, d4, d5, c4, queen's gambit, but

04:17:16.440 --> 04:17:22.000
[Amit Varma]: will instead teach you basic principles like space is important, occupy the center or initiative

04:17:22.000 --> 04:17:27.960
[Amit Varma]: is important. So develop your pieces. And I kind of love that approach and try to build

04:17:27.960 --> 04:17:33.080
[Amit Varma]: it in everything that I do. And with the help of your site, maybe I'll learn a little bit

04:17:33.080 --> 04:17:40.260
[Amit Varma]: more and become more of my own sort of coach. So where did sort of the MBA then come about

04:17:40.260 --> 04:17:44.760
[Amit Varma]: in your personal journey? Because like number one, I'm interested that you chose to do a

04:17:44.760 --> 04:17:49.440
[Amit Varma]: bootstrap startup in an age where everyone is raising funding and trying to be the next

04:17:49.440 --> 04:17:54.040
[Amit Varma]: unicorn and blah, blah, blah, which is a route you could have kind of taken. So why that

04:17:54.040 --> 04:17:58.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of stripped down choice that no bootstrap, I'll spend my own money, I'll do it on my

04:17:58.840 --> 04:18:05.160
[Guest]: own and you know. So first of all, Amit, I didn't come from a tech background, I came

04:18:05.160 --> 04:18:09.440
[Guest]: from an engineering background, but that's petroleum engineering. And so when I decided

04:18:09.440 --> 04:18:16.960
[Guest]: to do to go ahead and do the startup, I had to start bottoms up. And you know, I had to

04:18:16.960 --> 04:18:22.680
[Guest]: start by becoming a certified personal trainer and a nutritionist so that I don't put out

04:18:22.680 --> 04:18:30.640
[Guest]: something that I'm not confident about. And at the same time, I had to learn about what

04:18:30.640 --> 04:18:38.280
[Guest]: it is like to build an app, a web app and interactive platform. I had apps, I don't

04:18:38.280 --> 04:18:47.280
[Guest]: come from a family where anybody does a business or has done a business, forget startup. So

04:18:47.280 --> 04:18:52.280
[Guest]: I guess initially I said, hey, I'm going to show people that I have skin in the game.

04:18:52.280 --> 04:18:57.320
[Guest]: I'm serious about what I'm talking about. Because if you really think about startups

04:18:57.320 --> 04:19:02.640
[Guest]: and if people end up telling you, oh, but I quit my job to do my startup, that's enough

04:19:02.640 --> 04:19:09.720
[Guest]: proof of my seriousness. I would say that's, that's bullshit, because tomorrow you might

04:19:09.720 --> 04:19:16.600
[Guest]: take up another job. But when somebody has invested their hard-earned money into starting

04:19:16.600 --> 04:19:23.320
[Guest]: something regardless of how successful it is, that shows that they have skin in the

04:19:23.320 --> 04:19:28.560
[Guest]: game, that they're very, very serious, that they're willing to bet their money on something

04:19:28.560 --> 04:19:33.780
[Guest]: that they feel passionate about. And so that's, that's the reason I said, hey, I don't want

04:19:33.780 --> 04:19:41.640
[Guest]: anybody's interference. This is my own learning. This is all my journey. And when I was starting

04:19:41.640 --> 04:19:47.040
[Guest]: to work on my platform, also, I was still doing my courses and certification and everything

04:19:47.040 --> 04:19:52.680
[Guest]: and I really didn't think I had enough to convince an investor to come on board. Of

04:19:52.680 --> 04:20:01.120
[Guest]: course, I would have had some friends who would have invested and who may still, but

04:20:01.120 --> 04:20:10.400
[Guest]: because I could at the time support myself, I went into it. And the reason later on, I

04:20:10.400 --> 04:20:18.840
[Guest]: decided to do an MBA was because being an engineer, I'm crazy for optimizing things.

04:20:18.840 --> 04:20:26.440
[Guest]: And while it was a long and steep and very, very fulfilling journey to actually get something

04:20:26.440 --> 04:20:35.680
[Guest]: made and then launch it, I was, I was very upset that I sometimes I was eating, you know,

04:20:35.680 --> 04:20:42.640
[Guest]: with my, you know, having my, my arm wrapped around my head and bringing the food to my

04:20:42.640 --> 04:20:49.280
[Guest]: mouth on through the long pathways. And it was starting to worry, worry me a little bit

04:20:49.280 --> 04:20:54.160
[Guest]: because I was thinking constantly when I was trying to implement marketing strategies or

04:20:54.160 --> 04:21:00.080
[Guest]: do something or negotiate with somebody over some service, I was constantly feeling like,

04:21:00.080 --> 04:21:07.280
[Guest]: hey, I really feel there is, there is a, there is a better way of doing this. And I did not

04:21:07.280 --> 04:21:14.720
[Guest]: have any networks or connections in the startup world in India at the time. And so I said,

04:21:14.720 --> 04:21:20.080
[Guest]: hey, I want to form a network. The next time I have a question, I want to have a few people

04:21:20.080 --> 04:21:23.640
[Guest]: I can shoot emails to and say, hey, this is my problem. I want you to spend time with

04:21:23.640 --> 04:21:30.800
[Guest]: me because I had only started, I started the company by myself. I didn't start with a co-founder.

04:21:30.800 --> 04:21:35.600
[Guest]: So in that sense, there wasn't anybody to bounce off ideas with because you are trying

04:21:35.600 --> 04:21:39.920
[Guest]: to be very meticulous when you're putting your money into building the platform, building

04:21:39.920 --> 04:21:45.120
[Guest]: the product, everything is in your control. In that sense, you have set a goal on, on

04:21:45.120 --> 04:21:51.480
[Guest]: the date that you want to launch something. And I'm very, very particular about, I see

04:21:51.480 --> 04:21:56.000
[Guest]: a lot of people launching a lot of things now and you, they'll put it on Twitter and

04:21:56.000 --> 04:21:59.520
[Guest]: then you click on that platform and then you see a spelling mistake. And then I'm like,

04:21:59.520 --> 04:22:05.840
[Guest]: oh my God, I would never be able to take that. So I'm trying, in that sense, I have a bit

04:22:05.840 --> 04:22:12.440
[Guest]: of an OCD. But you, that all is in your control. But once you have launched your platform and

04:22:12.440 --> 04:22:18.000
[Guest]: now when customers are starting to interact with it, then in that sense, you have sort

04:22:18.000 --> 04:22:26.200
[Guest]: of given it in their hands now. And then the predictability of everything reduces. You

04:22:26.200 --> 04:22:32.560
[Guest]: can try different things and you may not have answers to how people are reacting, not only

04:22:32.560 --> 04:22:37.720
[Guest]: to your product, but also your marketing strategies. I decided that, hey, this is something that

04:22:37.720 --> 04:22:43.360
[Guest]: I want to learn. I want to learn how I can optimize how I am working before I put in

04:22:43.360 --> 04:22:53.000
[Guest]: much more money into it. And I want to sort of be in the right circles so that I don't

04:22:53.000 --> 04:22:58.660
[Guest]: constantly question myself. And while that is going to continue to happen, I guess now

04:22:58.660 --> 04:23:07.600
[Guest]: I will come, I have a bit more of a network that I trust and that knows that I can contact

04:23:07.600 --> 04:23:12.840
[Guest]: them at any point and ask them these questions. So it wasn't really about raising money in

04:23:12.840 --> 04:23:20.400
[Guest]: that sense for me early on, but about me starting to become more and more comfortable with running

04:23:20.400 --> 04:23:24.520
[Guest]: a business. I guess that's how I decided to do an MBA.

04:23:24.520 --> 04:23:29.180
[Amit Varma]: That's a fascinating journey from running to running a business. And you've pointed

04:23:29.180 --> 04:23:33.560
[Amit Varma]: out earlier about how you've taken up so many different kinds of challenges like running

04:23:33.560 --> 04:23:39.800
[Amit Varma]: 92 floors and 100 pushups and all of that in just 40 minutes and all that. But did anything

04:23:39.800 --> 04:23:43.440
[Amit Varma]: prepare you for a marathon scene in the unseen podcast recording?

04:23:43.440 --> 04:23:48.860
[Guest]: Oh my God, this is going to be one of the stories that I'm going to tell in some other

04:23:48.860 --> 04:23:58.520
[Guest]: podcast that this is also me testing my limits. I'm talking about myself. I mean, I guess

04:23:58.520 --> 04:24:03.160
[Guest]: few people, honestly, I mean, I think few people get a chance to talk about their story

04:24:03.160 --> 04:24:11.680
[Guest]: in this depth. And so, I mean, I have to thank you for delving so deep into your guest stories

04:24:11.680 --> 04:24:18.800
[Guest]: and really uncovering what sort of keeps them up at night in that sense, both in terms of

04:24:18.800 --> 04:24:21.600
[Guest]: what excites them, but also what bothers them.

04:24:21.600 --> 04:24:28.320
[Amit Varma]: No, we are not done yet. But we are almost done. You've been very kind with your time

04:24:28.320 --> 04:24:35.160
[Amit Varma]: and I don't want to push this too far. But my final bunch of questions deal around asking

04:24:35.160 --> 04:24:39.040
[Amit Varma]: you to give advice. And you said you don't like giving Gyan on Twitter. Well, now you

04:24:39.040 --> 04:24:43.720
[Amit Varma]: can give Gyan on the seen and unseen. And we can begin with advice for women. Like one

04:24:43.720 --> 04:24:48.280
[Amit Varma]: of the themes that concerns you and that you wrote about in the note that you sent me earlier

04:24:48.280 --> 04:24:53.520
[Amit Varma]: also is about the importance of sport in women's lives, the common health issues that women

04:24:53.520 --> 04:24:58.760
[Amit Varma]: face, and also what I was struck by, quote, women's general mentality with regards to

04:24:58.760 --> 04:25:03.480
[Amit Varma]: age and the ability of their bodies, stop quote. And I think in general, when you look

04:25:03.480 --> 04:25:10.640
[Amit Varma]: at gender, women in India, especially, seem to just basically accept a role that is given

04:25:10.640 --> 04:25:17.080
[Amit Varma]: to them and not exercise enough of their agency, which in most cases they can't, but even when

04:25:17.080 --> 04:25:21.560
[Amit Varma]: they can, they're kind of mentally suppressed in a way that no, this is what I am. This

04:25:21.560 --> 04:25:28.720
[Amit Varma]: is my role. These are my limits, and so on and so forth. And I guess that through your

04:25:28.720 --> 04:25:33.600
[Amit Varma]: journey, both with sport, both with nutrition, you know, you've kind of not just gone beyond

04:25:33.600 --> 04:25:39.400
[Amit Varma]: your own limits and all of that. But also, you know, would you would have a lot of advice

04:25:39.400 --> 04:25:44.920
[Amit Varma]: to women who are listening to this, for example, about, you know, about all of these things.

04:25:44.920 --> 04:25:51.600
[Guest]: So what are your thoughts? So, yeah, you're absolutely right. I do feel

04:25:51.600 --> 04:26:01.320
[Guest]: very strongly about women stopping themselves from finding out more about themselves. So

04:26:01.320 --> 04:26:08.240
[Guest]: I think it's very easy for us to, and valid, all valid, for us to say that we live in a

04:26:08.240 --> 04:26:14.920
[Guest]: patriarchal society, and there's a lot of gender bias and all of that. But if you start

04:26:14.920 --> 04:26:20.000
[Guest]: talking a little bit about solutions that are more in your circle of influence and more

04:26:20.000 --> 04:26:27.080
[Guest]: about things, start talking about things that you can do. I would say the first and foremost

04:26:27.080 --> 04:26:34.120
[Guest]: is I would start saying that forget what's your age and try and do the things that you

04:26:34.120 --> 04:26:41.480
[Guest]: have wanted to do, whatever is on your bucket list. And if you want to do anything at all,

04:26:41.480 --> 04:26:47.680
[Guest]: where you have told yourself that, I think I'm too old for it. I mean, I would say go

04:26:47.680 --> 04:26:54.800
[Guest]: and do that exact thing. Whether it is lifting weights, whether it is some trip that you

04:26:54.800 --> 04:27:05.440
[Guest]: want to take, some solo travel, whatever it is, I would say that is so important to your

04:27:05.440 --> 04:27:10.520
[Guest]: further growth. I would say that's stopping you then. If there is anything at all that

04:27:10.520 --> 04:27:16.080
[Guest]: you've given yourself an excuse for, and that excuse is your age, then I would say that's

04:27:16.080 --> 04:27:22.600
[Guest]: the exact and the first thing you should do tomorrow or as soon as you can. So that would

04:27:22.600 --> 04:27:31.080
[Guest]: be my advice. And think about it. If you look at women in the gym as well, I mean, there

04:27:31.080 --> 04:27:39.200
[Guest]: are men on the leg press in the gym where you're trying to push a plate basically and

04:27:39.200 --> 04:27:46.800
[Guest]: working your quadriceps. There are men who will sit on top of the place where you add

04:27:46.800 --> 04:27:55.680
[Guest]: weights because there's not enough plates in the gym. And then this gym dude who's being

04:27:55.680 --> 04:28:04.560
[Guest]: so very masculine and everybody else who's pumping him up are trying to add weight and

04:28:04.560 --> 04:28:09.120
[Guest]: show him that, oh, you can lift 200 kilos, 300 kilos. And he's basically doing all these

04:28:09.120 --> 04:28:16.360
[Guest]: half reps that from a personal trainer and a science point of view are just stupid. But

04:28:16.360 --> 04:28:22.080
[Guest]: they know all of this, but all of them gather together, pump each other's egos up. And even

04:28:22.080 --> 04:28:27.880
[Guest]: though they are doing some shit reps, they all come off it boasting about it. Oh, I did

04:28:27.880 --> 04:28:32.420
[Guest]: 200 kilos today. I did 300 kilos today. And nobody's really asking them if you really

04:28:32.420 --> 04:28:37.800
[Guest]: did the exercise properly or not. It doesn't matter. And then on the other hand, you look

04:28:37.800 --> 04:28:44.760
[Guest]: at women who are able to do things or who are not even asking anybody for help in the

04:28:44.760 --> 04:28:50.440
[Guest]: gym. These gym dudes have like groups that are helping pump them up. And here's women

04:28:50.440 --> 04:28:55.620
[Guest]: who've already sort of told themselves that I'm not going to go ask for help because sometimes

04:28:55.620 --> 04:29:00.720
[Guest]: you want somebody to sort of come pump you up a little bit. And then you do an exercise

04:29:00.720 --> 04:29:05.640
[Guest]: properly or so and you're and somebody says, oh, my God, you are really good. Oh, I don't

04:29:05.640 --> 04:29:11.920
[Guest]: I, you know, I think maybe accidentally or I don't know. So you'd give all kinds of excuses

04:29:11.920 --> 04:29:18.280
[Guest]: apart from boasting about what you just did. So in general, I think on a different note,

04:29:18.280 --> 04:29:24.680
[Guest]: I have to say I really, really, really admire women who can talk about themselves with pride

04:29:24.680 --> 04:29:28.520
[Guest]: without making it look like they're boasting about themselves. Because I think that's a

04:29:28.520 --> 04:29:36.200
[Guest]: skill and not a lot of women are able to do it. I am not able to do it myself as well

04:29:36.200 --> 04:29:43.800
[Guest]: as I would like to. Because women just don't know how to promote themselves, how to be

04:29:43.800 --> 04:29:49.800
[Guest]: proud of their own achievements. And on the other hand, men, even if they don't have a

04:29:49.800 --> 04:29:55.160
[Guest]: real achievement to boast about, will just gang up and then prop each other up and say

04:29:55.160 --> 04:30:00.960
[Guest]: that okay, you've done so well. And sometimes it works. Sometimes you have to fake it till

04:30:00.960 --> 04:30:06.800
[Guest]: you make it. And women who are even making it or even doing it are not boasting about

04:30:06.800 --> 04:30:13.000
[Guest]: it. So yeah, I do think that's my advice to women that, first of all, do the things that

04:30:13.000 --> 04:30:16.840
[Guest]: you have kept on the back burner for a very long time. And now you feel you're too old

04:30:16.840 --> 04:30:23.040
[Guest]: to do. I know a number of women who started lifting weights at the age of 37 and 38 and

04:30:23.040 --> 04:30:29.280
[Guest]: have won medals in the Commonwealth Games. But I also know a lot of women who are way

04:30:29.280 --> 04:30:35.520
[Guest]: past their 50s and are much fitter than me, are doing much better than me, who's much

04:30:35.520 --> 04:30:42.320
[Guest]: younger to them. And also, if you really take a look at my experience, when I started running

04:30:42.320 --> 04:30:48.480
[Guest]: that five kilometres that I did back in 2010, I used to look at some of my seniors who were

04:30:48.480 --> 04:30:56.280
[Guest]: four or five years elder than me. And I was maybe 22 that time and they were 27, 28. And

04:30:56.280 --> 04:31:02.120
[Guest]: I used to think, Oh, my God, she's 27, 28. And she's still running 5k and doing so well.

04:31:02.120 --> 04:31:07.000
[Guest]: Then I turned 27, 28. And I was doing really well. And I was looking at people who were

04:31:07.000 --> 04:31:12.880
[Guest]: 32, 33. And oh, my God, she's 32, 33. She's doing so well. Then I turned 30 to 33. And

04:31:12.880 --> 04:31:16.920
[Guest]: I was still able to do it. And now I look at women who are maybe 40 and be like, Oh,

04:31:16.920 --> 04:31:21.680
[Guest]: my God, they're so fit. So what does that prove that that just means that age is just

04:31:21.680 --> 04:31:27.600
[Guest]: a number so long as you are able to put in the work. And, and that's, that's pretty much

04:31:27.600 --> 04:31:34.360
[Guest]: my advice to women like learn to sort of talk about your, your achievements with a lot more

04:31:34.360 --> 04:31:39.720
[Guest]: pride and, and go do all the things that you put on the back burner.

04:31:39.720 --> 04:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: That's fantastic advice, even for men. And that also speaks to what you were saying before

04:31:43.840 --> 04:31:47.960
[Amit Varma]: the show started, that you've noticed so many women guests who come on the show will say

04:31:47.960 --> 04:31:52.160
[Amit Varma]: that Oh, what's interesting about my story, or Oh, Amit, please stop me if I digress too

04:31:52.160 --> 04:31:57.480
[Amit Varma]: much. And even you did that once or twice during this and the men never do that. And,

04:31:57.480 --> 04:32:02.360
[Amit Varma]: and you're right. And that sort of lack of confidence is sort of infuriating. I think

04:32:02.360 --> 04:32:07.800
[Amit Varma]: I've referred in a previous episode to this study I'd read about confidence that a company

04:32:07.800 --> 04:32:13.200
[Amit Varma]: apparently tried to stress with this internal workers where it brought out this, where it

04:32:13.200 --> 04:32:18.020
[Amit Varma]: advertises job opening and said, these are the 10 qualities we need. And the women simply

04:32:18.020 --> 04:32:22.960
[Amit Varma]: would not apply unless they met nine or 10 of those, while a man he meets four or five,

04:32:22.960 --> 04:32:27.120
[Amit Varma]: he will apply Bindas, you know, and, and this is a problem. And to an extent,

04:32:27.120 --> 04:32:31.320
[Guest]: I've noticed that I've been a victim of that myself. Sometimes women take everything too

04:32:31.320 --> 04:32:37.280
[Guest]: seriously. And if somebody says, okay, you know, you need these 10 things to apply, and

04:32:37.280 --> 04:32:42.320
[Guest]: they are literally trying to match everything one to one. And then there's something that's

04:32:42.320 --> 04:32:48.520
[Guest]: not matching, and then they're so worried about it. I guess that's how we are.

04:32:48.520 --> 04:32:52.120
[Amit Varma]: And we can change, which is, I think these words of yours might be so inspiring that

04:32:52.120 --> 04:32:55.920
[Amit Varma]: the Tiger Academy in Phuket will suddenly find all kinds of Indian women are landing

04:32:55.920 --> 04:32:57.880
[Guest]: up what is happening. Why has it happened?

04:32:57.880 --> 04:33:02.360
[Guest]: That would be so good. Yeah, I would, I would be the first one to go watch all these Indian

04:33:02.360 --> 04:33:09.720
[Guest]: women really push themselves there against all the, the apparently stronger looking German

04:33:09.720 --> 04:33:16.520
[Guest]: and Canadian and other women, Australian, because I, I'm very curious every, every time

04:33:16.520 --> 04:33:23.520
[Guest]: I see women pushing themselves, because everybody's bodies look different. But that is not a reflection

04:33:23.520 --> 04:33:29.760
[Guest]: of what their ability is. So as, as somebody who's watching, it becomes a very interesting

04:33:29.760 --> 04:33:33.760
[Guest]: thing. So yeah, I'd be the first one to go watch the spectacle.

04:33:33.760 --> 04:33:38.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I can imagine a potbellied Indian man also landing up at the Tiger Academy in

04:33:38.160 --> 04:33:43.560
[Amit Varma]: Phuket and refusing to, and refusing to pay. And when they ask him, why are you refusing

04:33:43.560 --> 04:33:51.400
[Amit Varma]: to pay? He'll say, this is in Phuket. I had to do one of those. It's sort of, okay. So

04:33:51.400 --> 04:33:57.680
[Amit Varma]: now the second of three categories of advice, and this is advice for people like me, who've

04:33:57.680 --> 04:34:04.400
[Amit Varma]: never engaged seriously with something like fitness or sport or whatever, and who in the

04:34:04.400 --> 04:34:08.880
[Amit Varma]: abstract love the idea of being fit and being sporty, but in the concrete have never done

04:34:08.880 --> 04:34:13.360
[Amit Varma]: anything about it. And, and you know, people like me would then argue that, look, I mean,

04:34:13.360 --> 04:34:16.960
[Amit Varma]: I have to sit in front of my laptop all the time. And where is the time? Actually, I can't

04:34:16.960 --> 04:34:21.320
[Amit Varma]: argue that because I'm fortunate enough to control a lot of my time. But most office

04:34:21.320 --> 04:34:25.760
[Amit Varma]: going people would say that, you know, we have so many responsibilities, ghar dekhna

04:34:25.760 --> 04:34:30.840
[Amit Varma]: hai, office dekhna hai, time hi nahi milta exercise ke liye, kaise kare, kya kare, sports

04:34:30.840 --> 04:34:35.060
[Amit Varma]: matlab, what do you mean sports, kahan khele, kya khele. So what's your advice to these

04:34:35.060 --> 04:34:40.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of people, not necessarily on what specific to do, because that obviously depends on circumstances

04:34:40.560 --> 04:34:45.120
[Amit Varma]: and all that. But just in terms of mindset, that how should we think about fitness? How

04:34:45.120 --> 04:34:51.480
[Guest]: should we think about our bodies? So Amit, first and foremost, I think everybody who

04:34:51.480 --> 04:34:57.480
[Guest]: says ki, arre main toh shyaam ko badminton khelta hu, I would first like to tell people

04:34:57.480 --> 04:35:04.120
[Guest]: that doing sport and doing fitness are two different things. And sport is where you're

04:35:04.120 --> 04:35:08.680
[Guest]: learning a certain skill, and then you're participating in the sport itself, but you

04:35:08.680 --> 04:35:15.740
[Guest]: already need to be fit to perform in the sport. So fitness and sport are different. If somebody,

04:35:15.740 --> 04:35:20.640
[Guest]: I mean, yeah, if you're active, it's still better than nothing. But if you're trying

04:35:20.640 --> 04:35:26.360
[Guest]: to achieve a certain fitness goal, and then do that through playing volleyball or basketball

04:35:26.360 --> 04:35:32.960
[Guest]: or whatever your sport is, that's not going to happen. So you cannot say that, okay, I've

04:35:32.960 --> 04:35:37.720
[Guest]: been playing badminton so regularly, and still I don't see anything. So you need to find

04:35:37.720 --> 04:35:43.160
[Guest]: time for fitness. And I agree that sometimes it's not that you don't have time in your

04:35:43.160 --> 04:35:49.520
[Guest]: day, but sometimes you don't have the mental space. And I would say that even 15 minutes

04:35:49.520 --> 04:35:56.620
[Guest]: of really committed exercise, but every single day, and when you're really pushing yourself

04:35:56.620 --> 04:36:01.600
[Guest]: can do wonders for people. And I don't see why 15 minutes should be difficult for anybody

04:36:01.600 --> 04:36:07.680
[Guest]: at all. So I would say start with 15 minutes if that's very, if going to the gym and lifting

04:36:07.680 --> 04:36:13.520
[Guest]: weights and all that seems too much for you right now, start with 15 minutes, but then

04:36:13.520 --> 04:36:19.440
[Guest]: make those 15 minutes count. There are a number of programs that would challenge you in 15

04:36:19.440 --> 04:36:23.400
[Guest]: minutes, and then make them count. And then you may come to a point where they're not

04:36:23.400 --> 04:36:27.880
[Guest]: challenging enough, then that's a good cue to ramp it up.

04:36:27.880 --> 04:36:33.160
[Amit Varma]: Sounds good. I mean, for me, I guess maybe that would just be standing for 15 minutes.

04:36:33.160 --> 04:36:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Like this is actually a sit stand desk, which is right here, but I don't spend so much time

04:36:37.640 --> 04:36:44.440
[Amit Varma]: standing. It's just that, you know, depending on my degree of slump, I'll adjust the height.

04:36:44.440 --> 04:36:48.160
[Amit Varma]: But that's that's kind of what happens. But the final category of advice really goes back

04:36:48.160 --> 04:36:52.640
[Amit Varma]: to something we spoke about at the start of the episode, where you spoke about parents'

04:36:52.640 --> 04:36:57.520
[Amit Varma]: attitude to their children, playing sports and so on. What advice would you have for

04:36:57.520 --> 04:37:02.520
[Amit Varma]: parents when it comes to their kids, whether it is in the context of being serious about

04:37:02.520 --> 04:37:08.800
[Amit Varma]: a sport, or whether it is just in context of what their kids do in their free time?

04:37:08.800 --> 04:37:14.160
[Amit Varma]: Should parents really care about the proportion of physical activity that is actually getting

04:37:14.160 --> 04:37:20.320
[Guest]: done? How does one look at this? That's an interesting question. I would say,

04:37:20.320 --> 04:37:28.520
[Guest]: first of all, parents need to expose their children to a variety of sport. And in general,

04:37:28.520 --> 04:37:35.680
[Guest]: try and keep an eye on what they show interest in. And I am not a very big fan of hum sham

04:37:35.680 --> 04:37:40.040
[Guest]: ko khelne bhejte hain. I'm not a big fan of that because I feel like there's no goal in

04:37:40.040 --> 04:37:46.400
[Guest]: goal to it. There is fun, there's mixing with other children and all of that, but that would

04:37:46.400 --> 04:37:53.880
[Guest]: also happen in a sport. I definitely feel that, just like you talk about a musical instrument,

04:37:53.880 --> 04:37:59.720
[Guest]: it's a discipline, it's a skill you're learning, and it's best started early. If you see that

04:37:59.720 --> 04:38:06.360
[Guest]: your child is showing interest in a certain sport, then I would definitely say that parents

04:38:06.360 --> 04:38:14.160
[Guest]: need to make that little extra effort to find the best coach or at school support every

04:38:14.160 --> 04:38:19.920
[Guest]: single initiative the school is making to help your child do better in that sport. Because

04:38:19.920 --> 04:38:25.440
[Guest]: somewhere I feel like our parents were very supportive, but they were also very supportive

04:38:25.440 --> 04:38:29.440
[Guest]: because they were supportive for their children. It's not like they knew a lot about the sport

04:38:29.440 --> 04:38:35.380
[Guest]: or anything like that. So whatever happened with us, in a sense happened accidentally.

04:38:35.380 --> 04:38:41.940
[Guest]: But it doesn't mean it'll happen accidentally for everybody. And which is why I would say

04:38:41.940 --> 04:38:49.720
[Guest]: my advice for parents is first of all, I think all children should follow a certain sport

04:38:49.720 --> 04:38:57.440
[Guest]: and provide them with every facility to flourish in it. And if it actually comes to a point

04:38:57.440 --> 04:39:03.400
[Guest]: where they actually show prodigal skills, then allow them to make it priority.

04:39:03.400 --> 04:39:08.120
[Amit Varma]: No, there's a book I think it's by Amy Chua called Tiger Mom. And I'm getting the feeling

04:39:08.120 --> 04:39:14.000
[Amit Varma]: that you'd be a bit of a tiger trainer, in the sense that you are so strict in terms

04:39:14.000 --> 04:39:18.640
[Amit Varma]: of badminton, badminton is not fitness, or I'm sending my kids out to play kids out to

04:39:18.640 --> 04:39:23.080
[Amit Varma]: play that's not fitness, you know, which I like, which is, which is great. I wish I had

04:39:23.080 --> 04:39:29.880
[Amit Varma]: a trainer like you when I was seven. So my very final question, brutal reality. So and

04:39:29.880 --> 04:39:35.240
[Amit Varma]: it's never too late to start. So you know, why not? So my final question for you is,

04:39:35.240 --> 04:39:39.200
[Amit Varma]: it's a traditional one. So you're obviously familiar with it, that for my guests, and

04:39:39.200 --> 04:39:44.040
[Amit Varma]: for me recommend some books, films, music that you like.

04:39:44.040 --> 04:39:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Does it have to do with the rousing sport action?

04:39:47.000 --> 04:39:52.440
[Amit Varma]: No, it's a general question, whatever is dear to you. So it could be something completely

04:39:52.440 --> 04:39:56.920
[Amit Varma]: that no one may associate with any of the things you do. But whatever is dear to you,

04:39:56.920 --> 04:40:01.120
[Amit Varma]: whatever is a desert island book or a desert island disc, whatever, something that you

04:40:01.120 --> 04:40:04.160
[Amit Varma]: feel so strongly about, you'd love to share it with everyone.

04:40:04.160 --> 04:40:11.200
[Guest]: Okay, so if I just talk about some of the topics that we've touched on on in the podcast,

04:40:11.200 --> 04:40:16.080
[Guest]: then the books that we spoke about in, in terms of Gary Taubes and Nina Teicholz, and

04:40:16.080 --> 04:40:23.240
[Guest]: you said you would also provide links to them. But apart from that, if you ask me about films,

04:40:23.240 --> 04:40:28.520
[Guest]: I would say I have a very mixed bag. I would, I would watch something like Everything is

04:40:28.520 --> 04:40:37.400
[Guest]: Illuminated by Jonathan Safran Foer. I would watch, I mean, a childhood favourite movie

04:40:37.400 --> 04:40:43.560
[Guest]: has been The White Balloon, which is an Iranian movie about a little girl and her and her

04:40:43.560 --> 04:40:50.520
[Guest]: wish to get a goldfish. I like a lot of Majid Majidi films as well. In terms of, in terms,

04:40:50.520 --> 04:40:57.680
[Guest]: I really enjoy Tamilian music. I enjoy Arabic music. And so I would say, you know, just

04:40:57.680 --> 04:41:05.200
[Guest]: Google some Tamilian and Arabic music and most of the tunes are, are lovely. I listen

04:41:05.200 --> 04:41:13.520
[Guest]: to a lot of Indian classical music. That's books, films. I love, I love some series on

04:41:13.520 --> 04:41:21.120
[Guest]: OTT now. I mean, I'm very predictable, Amit, in terms of loving, recently watched Panchayat

04:41:21.120 --> 04:41:26.320
[Guest]: 2 because I didn't have access to it in Berlin. And so when I came to India, I watched it.

04:41:26.320 --> 04:41:32.800
[Guest]: I really liked Schitt's Creek, for example, This Is Us. All the, all the, all the writing

04:41:32.800 --> 04:41:38.200
[Guest]: that talks about mundane everyday life and how it can be quite delightful really appeals

04:41:38.200 --> 04:41:45.200
[Guest]: to me. I have watched a lot of the documentaries on Netflix that are about sport and fitness

04:41:45.200 --> 04:41:50.720
[Guest]: and I think I definitely recommend them. Especially, I don't remember one, and if it's still on

04:41:50.720 --> 04:41:57.520
[Guest]: Netflix, but there was one that interviewed Serena Williams coach and some popular coaches

04:41:57.520 --> 04:42:05.200
[Guest]: from football and, and basketball. And I would definitely recommend people to see, see them.

04:42:05.200 --> 04:42:08.600
[Guest]: I'll link that from the show notes once you remember the name.

04:42:08.600 --> 04:42:18.900
[Guest]: Yeah. And yeah, pretty much pretty, very predictable. I don't think I go very, I'm not much of an

04:42:18.900 --> 04:42:27.000
[Guest]: explorer when it comes to books, I would say and, and films. Yeah. And especially having

04:42:27.000 --> 04:42:30.960
[Guest]: been in the, in the course in the last six or eight months, I have really not explored

04:42:30.960 --> 04:42:39.120
[Guest]: much in terms of films. But yeah, a lot of podcasts, I would, I would say, I mean, my

04:42:39.120 --> 04:42:44.320
[Guest]: way of listening to podcasts is also apart from, for example, knowing that your podcast

04:42:44.320 --> 04:42:48.880
[Guest]: is good, if I had to listen to something else, I would just, you know, go for a walk or something

04:42:48.880 --> 04:42:53.360
[Guest]: and say, hey, I'm going to listen to this today and see for myself if I find it interesting

04:42:53.360 --> 04:43:00.480
[Guest]: or not. And I listen to a lot of TED talks as well. I think it's like 15 minutes of quick

04:43:00.480 --> 04:43:05.680
[Guest]: wisdom on on some things that sometimes you have these last minute questions or something

04:43:05.680 --> 04:43:09.600
[Guest]: that's popped up in your head when you were like getting back home from somewhere. And

04:43:09.600 --> 04:43:13.640
[Guest]: you're just like, hey, what are people saying about it? I guess TED talks are a good way

04:43:13.640 --> 04:43:18.240
[Guest]: of getting, getting some quick knowledge.

04:43:18.240 --> 04:43:22.960
